<FIRST>r a AM-PizzaConnectionII     03-07 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pizza Connection II,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Charges Dismissed After Judge Blasts Prosecutors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday dismissed charges against
half of the 14 defendants in a massive, mob-linked drug conspiracy
trial, finding prosecutors failed to prove their case because of
``ineptitude.''
   ``If these drug dealers are walking free it's because you people
are not competent,'' U.S. District Judge John Sprizzo told
protesting prosecutors as he dismissed narcotics conspiracy charges
against seven defendants in the Pizza Connection II drug trial.
   ``You let them go,'' Sprizzo told prosecutors later in the day.
``Don't lay at my feet your ineptitude.''
   The judge then barred lawyers from talking to reporters about the
case.
   Sprizzo dropped the drug conspiracy charge after the government
finished presenting its case and defense lawyers, contending the
charge was too broad, made routine requests for the dismissal of
charges for lack of evidence.
   The trial, which began last October, is a spinoff from the
original, 17-month-long Pizza Connection drug trial, so named
because prosecutors accused the defendants of using pizzerias in the
Midwest and Northeast as fronts for their heroin dealing and
money-laundering conspiracy.
   Eighteen of the 19 defendants in the first Pizza Connection trial
were convicted.
   The 14 defendants in the Pizza Connection II case were accused of
participating in a massive conspiracy to distribute heroin, cocaine
and marijuana. Some also were charged with possession of drugs with
intent to distribute.
   The seven remaining defendants face maxiumum penalties of life in
prison if convicted.
</TEXT>
