<FIRST>u p AM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0755 03-07 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0755,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Hit By Fellow Dems For Anti-Daley Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 12th graf, ``Jackson identifies ...,''
to UPDATE with Jackson letter; picks up 13th graf, `` Jackson backed ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson fasted for three days because he
hungers for the defeat of Democratic mayoral nominee Richard M.
Daley, but some Democrats say Jackson's efforts are straining the
two-time Democratic presidential contender's party credentials.
   ``What kind of credibility does that give Jackson nationwide with
other Democrats?'' asks Illinois party Chairman Vince Demuzio.
``This is certainly not going to bode well for Jackson nationally if
he has any future ambitions, which I'm sure he does.''
   Jackson backed Mayor Eugene Sawyer in the Democratic primary won
last week by Daley, but that was because his candidate of choice _
Democratic Alderman Timothy Evans _ sat out the primary in favor of
a third-party bid in the April 4 general election.
   The attack on Jackson's party credentials is only the latest
event in what has become an imbroglio in the politics of Chicago's
black community since Harold Washington, the city's first black
mayor, died near the start of his second term in 1987.
   Jackson has tried to be a peacemaker, but his plea for unity
among supporters of Sawyer and Evans during the primary went
unheeded. Now his position is at odds with the man Jackson
successfully backed to head the Democratic National Committee.
   Ron Brown, the first black to hold the top post, has announced
his support of Daley, said Mike McCurry, spokesman for the DNC in
Washington.
   To top it off, Republicans have taken note of the black split in
Chicago and some see it as playing into the hands of new Republican
National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater, who is trying to lure
disenchanted blacks to the GOP.
   Jackson says he is unfazed.
   ``In these contests, sometimes you win the votes and sometimes
you don't, but you must always preserve your dignity,'' he said
Monday in a telephone interview while enroute from Tuskegee to
Montgomery, Ala.
   ``What that Democratic machine represents is a violation of
people,'' Jackson said of what he thinks would be a closed
Democratic party under Daley. ``It strips them of their dignity.''
   Daley denies that he represents the past or the politics of his
father, the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, who ran a vast patronage
army. Young Daley talks, as do others, of unifying the city and
giving all people opportunities.
   Jackson identifies the issue in his support of Evans, running on
the Harold Washington Party ticket, as ``reciprocity,'' meaning he
won't support those who haven't supported him.
   U.S. Rep. Marty Russo, D-Ill., a Daley ally who has criticized
Jackson's opposition to the Democratic mayoral nominee, received a
letter from Jackson that requested a meeting, Jackson spokesman
Frank Watkins said later Monday.
   ``If you are serious about unity in the Democratic Party, I am
perfectly willing to meet with you and Richard Daley to discuss a
similar deal,'' said the letter drafted by Watkins. ``If I do run
(for president) in 1992 will you support my candidacy as a favorite
son? That is the basis of a reciprocal deal.''
   Watkins said the letter was ``kind of a rhetorical device.''
   ``He's really not willing to talk to Daley,'' Watkins said.
``Rev. Jackson is supporting Tim Evans.''
   Jackson backed a slate of Democratic Cook County candidates last
year, including Daley in his successful bid for a third term as
county state's attorney. But he notes Daley didn't support him in
his 1988 presidential bid and didn't endorse Washington in 1987.
   ``I reached out to Daley and endorsed him, and yet he seems to
have no sense of obligation to be reciprocal or fair,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson denies that race is the only issue, although Daley is
white and Evans is black. He says the issue is one of ``going
forward'' instead of backwards.
   ``In Daley, there is relief for those who have a history of
monopolizing; grief for those who've been locked out,'' Jackson said
Saturday at an Operation PUSH meeting where he also announced his
three-day fast. Jackson, who was taking only liquids, planned to
return to a normal diet on Tuesday.
   A mostly white coalition of aldermen elected Sawyer over Evans a
week after Washington died and many Evans supporters sat out last
week's primary. Sawyer got about half the votes Washington did from
the city's 19 predominately black wards.
   Some political analysts say Jackson's run against the party's
endorsed candidate in Chicago will have little bearing on his
national standing.
   ``It will certainly be used against him, but I think Chicago
politics is seen as .. a unique situation,'' Thomas Cavanagh
director of Johns Hopkins University's Center for the Study of
American Government in Washington, said Monday. ``People who like
what he stands for probably won't care if he endorses the
(Democratic mayoral) nominee or not.''
</TEXT>
