<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--OnlyLaundry     03-07 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Only Laundry,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulations Force Town's Only Laundry to Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents left high and dry when this town's
only coin-operated laundry was forced to close over safety concerns
now have to drive at least 15 miles to wash their clothes.
   Others among the 50 or so Wash-Out customers travel 30 miles to
do their laundry in other towns.
   ``I feel very badly if someone has to travel 32 miles to do a
load of laundry,'' said Virginia Pierce of the state Department of
Natural Resources. ``On the other hand, I would feel a lot worse if
someone contracted a disease that terminated their life.''
   Authorities said Wash-Out's owner, Dennis Morse Jr., used to
allow waste water into a sewer near a neighboring nursing home. But
he was told last year the state agency would not renew its permit if
the laundry continued to dump water there.
   ``They're going to have to change the law, because if they don't,
you're not going to see a Laundromat in a small town,'' said Morse,
who closed his 13-year-old business recently.
</TEXT>
