<FIRST>r i PM-FoodSmugglers     03-07 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Food Smugglers,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Border Authorities Block More Than 3,000 Food Smugglers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3,000 Poles have recently been
caught trying to smuggle food into Western Europe to sell at a
profit, the official PAP news agency reported.
   In one case, a Pole tried to smuggle a goat and a baby pig into
West Berlin, Zygmunt Janczyk, spokesman for the main customs office,
was quoted as saying.
   ``We will fight this negative phenomenon until it vanishes
completely,'' Janczyk was quoted as saying in the report Monday.
   PAP did not say during what period of time the offenders were
caught by customs officials.
   PAP did not say during what period of time the offenders were
turned back. Communist authorities on Jan. 1 eased procedures to
obtain passports and thousands of Poles have headed West to trade,
mainly to West Berlin or Austria where visas are not required.
   Janczyk said Poles were allowed to take enough food for their
journey, but a 300 percent customs duty is charged on any excessive
amount.
   He said some Polish passengers on a train en route to West Berlin
threw food away when they saw customs officers approach.
   Trading in the West is tempting to Poles because they can buy
goods in Poland for zlotys, sell them for hard currency in the West
and then convert that money back into zlotys at the black-market
rate for a profit.
</TEXT>
