<FIRST>u a AM-Immigration-Nelson     03-07 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigration-Nelson,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Immigration Commissioner Alan Nelson Being Ousted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service
Commissioner Alan C. Nelson will be replaced as part of a ``major
turnover'' in the administration intended to reflect President
Bush's priorities and views, the Los Angeles Times said.
   Despite a concerted effort by Nelson to hold onto his job, the
search for his replacement is under way, the newspaper said in
Tuesday editions.
   Nelson presided over the government's massive program to give
legal status to illegal aliens.
   The report came in the wake of a recent Justice Department audit
that was highly critical of INS management practices, citing such
problems as missing documents, massive backlogs of cases and failure
to conduct background checks on many applicants for citizenship.
   In addition, Nelson has been criticized for the agency's plan to
dig a four-mile-long ditch on the Mexico-California border near San
Diego to deter smuggling.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, whose department oversees the
INS, wants to bring ``new blood'' to the agency, the Times said.
   The president indicated ``he would like to see major turnover of
people in the Administration to reflect his views and priorities,''
a Justice Department source told the Times.
   ``The attorney general has been engaged in the process of
interviewing people for major positions,'' said spokesman David
Runkel. ``No determination has been made with regard to INS.''
   No decision on a replacement is expected this month, the Times
said. Administration sources said several people have been mentioned
as possible successors to Nelson, but no front-runner has emerged.
   ``We're not in a position to confirm or deny that. To the best of
my knowledge, he has not been told that. I just talked to him,''
said Nelson's chief spokesman, Greg Leo.
   The report that Nelson was being ushered out was no surprise to
several immigrant rights activists.
   ``There are enough people out there who want him out to start a
club,'' said Mario Moreno of the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Educational Fund.
   Nelson, a former San Francisco attorney who took over the job in
1982, oversaw implementation of the landmark 1986 immigration reform
law and was sharply criticized by alien advocates who said he was
slow in informing the public about the measure's provisions.
</TEXT>
