<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama     03-07 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crisis in Relations Drags on; Election Seen as Rigged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the prospect of a rigged election
perpetuating the rule of Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega,
administration officials and other experts see little hope of any
thaw in U.S.-Panamanian relations.
   Panama's ruling coalition has selected a Noriega confidant,
Carlos Duque, as the official candidate in the May 7 election, an
indication that Noriega intends to continue running the government
from behind the scenes, much as he has for the past five years.
   This is causing headaches for U.S. policy makers, who see Panama
as one of the major hemispheric issues facing the new
administration, ranking alongside debt, drug trafficking and Marxist
penetration of Central America as priority problems. A prime concern
is the continued smooth functioning of the Panama Canal.
   Almost nothing has gone right for the United States in Panama
since relations began to deteriorate in June 1987. A year ago,
administration officials confidently predicted Noriega would quickly
fall after a series of U.S. sanctions were imposed.
   But Noriega, the Defense Force commander who is under indictment
in Florida on drug smuggling charges, has survived the challenge,
leaving U.S. officials perplexed and divided on what to do next.
   Gen. Fred Woerner, the Panama-based commander of U.S. forces in
Latin America, has taken the unusual step of going public with his
concerns, suggesting that Noriega is the beneficiary of a policy
vacuum in Washington.
   There is virtually unanimous agreement among government and
outside analysts that Noriega is laying the groundwork for a
fraudulent election.
   Woerner says Noriega ``has been moving adroitly to manipulate''
the balloting against an opposition slate.
   The State Department said last month that ``it is hard to imagine
a free and fair election'' being carried out in an atmosphere of
``heavy-handed repression and intimidation.''
   A report released last week by the Puebla Institute, a lay Roman
Catholic human rights group, said Panama denies basic civil
liberties and that Noriega allies control the electoral tribunal and
voter lists and also are in charge of the balloting.
   Leslie Hunter, who wrote a portion of the report, said there is a
widespread expectation in Panama that ``these elections will be the
most fraudulent of all in a series of fraudulent elections'' in that
country.
   Carl Gershman, president of the U.S.-funded National Endowment
for Democracy, said a huge majority of Panamanians oppose Noriega
and they may be able use the election process to their advantage.
   Gershman, who returned recently from Panama, said Noriega could
be weakened politically from the process if it exposes the depth of
the sentiment against him.
   Noriega may be faced with a choice of calling off the election or
engaging in massive fraud to ensure victory, leaving him in a
difficult position both at home and internationally, Gershman said.
   Ambassador Juan Sosa, a captain of the anti-Noriega forces in
Washington, agreed that Noriega may have to confront that unhappy
choice. ``Nobody believes the election will be a solution in the
struggle,'' Sosa said.
   Sosa was appointed by ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle as
ambassador, and the United States continues to recognize both. In
February 1988, Delvalle tried to fire Noriega but instead was
deposed by Noriega's allies hours later.
   Latin American democracies have kept a diplomatic distance from
the Noriega-led government, and the United States has shunned
virtually all dealings with it.
   This has created a variety of problems for U.S. diplomats in
Panama, including obtaining such mundane items as license plates and
driver's licenses. To minimize hardship, the State Department has
sharply reduced its staff in Panama and additional cuts are under
consideration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EspionageCase     03-07 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Espionage Case,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Warrant Officer Asks Mercy After Pleading Guilty to Spy Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army Warrant Officer James W. Hall III feels
remorse for spying in behalf of Warsaw Pact nations and hopes for
clemency from the military judge before whom he pleaded guilty to 10
counts of espionage, his lawyer says.
   Vaughn E. Taylor, Hall's civilian counsel, said Monday that the
30-year-old New York City native is ``truly sorry for whatever
damage he may have done to national security'' and will ``throw
himself on the mercy of his military judge.''
   Under a plea agreement, Hall cannot receive the death penalty.
   Hall admitted during his court-martial Monday that he
participated between 1983 and 1988 in a conspiracy to deliver
classified military information to East Germany and the Soviet Union.
   Col. Howard C. Eggers, the military judge presiding at the
court-martial at Fort McNair in southwest Washington, will decide
whether to accept Hall's plea after hearing the prosecution's case
and defense witnesses. Court officials said the final verdict and
sentence probably would come Friday at the soonest.
   Hall, an intelligence analyst with a top-secret security
clearance, was arrested Dec. 21 near Savannah, Ga., and accused of
delivering film and documents dealing with communications
intelligence and war plans to Warsaw Pact nations.
   At the time of his arrest, Hall was assigned to the 24th Infantry
Division and worked as an intelligence analyst in the Army's G-2
intelligence section. He joined the Army in 1976 and spent most of
his career in Europe working as an analyst of intercepted radio and
telephone traffic and coded messages.
   Hall pleaded guilty under an agreement that prohibits the
government from seeking the death penalty. The maximum punishment he
could receive is life in prison, forfeiture of all pay and
allowances, dishonorable discharge and a fine.
   A still-secret part of the plea agreement outlines the sentence
that Hall will receive unless the presiding judge, who is not
permitted to see the sentencing agreement, imposes a lighter
sentence. If the judge imposes a sentence that is harsher than the
one in the agreement, the agreement will prevail.
   Hall waived his right to a grand jury-type hearing to determine
if a court-martial was warranted and agreed to be tried by a single
military judge rather than a panel of officers.
   He also agreed to submit to ``unlimited debriefing'' and
polygraph examination by government officials and to testify, if
called, at grand jury proceedings against Huseyin Yildirim, a
Turkish-born, naturalized citizen to whom Hall allegedly passed the
classified information.
   The plea agreement requires that Hall sign away any profits he
might earn in the future from any publication based on his
involvement in the espionage case.
   Taylor said through a military spokesman that he would not
comment on Hall's motivation for passing classified information
until after Hall has been questioned by Eggers during the closed
part of the court-martial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
