<FIRST>r w PM-Heflin-Tower     03-07 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heflin-Tower,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heflin no Stranger to Partisan Battles Over Presidential Appointments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Senate Democrat to support Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower has frequently sided with Republicans
but also cast crucial votes against three of former President
Reagan's nominees.
   Sen. Howell Heflin of Alabama was Reagan's most consistent
Democratic supporter in the Senate, but he played a major role in
the Senate rejection of Supreme Court nominee Robert H. Bork.
   He also cast the deciding vote in the Senate Judiciary
Committee's rejection of two other Reagan nominees, William Bradford
Reynolds for the number three post in the Justice Department and
Jefferson B. Sessions for a federal judgeship in south Alabama.
   But Heflin on Monday announced that he would break ranks with his
Democratic colleagues and support Tower's confirmation.
   ``I will rely on his pledge and give him a chance to prove
himself,'' Heflin said in a speech on the Senate floor, referring to
Tower's promise to swear off drinking if he is confirmed to head the
Pentagon.
   Heflin met privately with President Bush for 45 minutes last week
to discuss the Tower nomination. He said afterward that he believes
a president's appointments should be confirmed unless it can be
proven ``that the person is flawed or that he would be a detriment
to the country.''
   In Tower's case, Heflin said he was not convinced after reading
the FBI reports that the former Texas senator has a drinking problem
that would disqualify him from serving in the nation's top military
post.
   ``In reviewing all of the charges, I have concluded that his
conduct in many areas is not applaudable and not without justifiable
criticism, but on the other hand, not disqualifying,'' he said.
   Heflin also cited Tower's qualifications for the Pentagon post
and said that in the six years that he served with Tower in the
Senate, between 1978 and 1984, he never saw nor heard any evidence
that Tower had a drinking problem.
   Had Tower been nominated for a lifetime judgeship, Heflin might
well have voted against confirmation. But he said the since the
secretary of defense serves at the pleasure of the president, Bush
will be responsible and accountable for Tower's conduct.
   ``It is the president's cabinet,'' Heflin said, ``not Congress'
cabinet.''
   Heflin, a 67-year-old ex-Marine and former Alabama chief justice,
was widely criticized in Alabama for his opposition to both Bork and
Sessions, but neither vote appears to have caused him any lasting
political damage.
   First elected to the Senate in 1978 with more than 90 percent of
the general election vote, Heflin was re-elected in 1984 with 63
percent of the vote against a conservative GOP opponent.
   His only announced challenger in 1990 is Republican state Sen.
Bill Cabiness of Birmingham, a businessman who chaired the state's
delegation to the Republican convention that nominated Bush for
president.
</TEXT>
