<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-07 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawmaker wants the state to change its
name to ``Dakota'' to project a simpler, warmer image, but one
newspaper suggests officials should take a hint from their neighbor
to the north.
   Sen. Tim Mathern is sponsoring a resolution to drop ``North''
from the state's name, a change voters would have to approve.
Supporters say ``North'' connotes a cold, harsh climate.
   Mathern told the state Congress' Joint Constitutional Revision
Committee on Monday that the adjective detracts from the word
``Dakota,'' which means ``friend'' or ``ally'' in the Sioux language.
   ``Dakota speaks to what we are most proud about, the
wholesomeness and hospitality of our people,'' he said.
   Business also would appear to support the change, said state
Tourism Director Jim Fuglie. Telephone books in North Dakota's four
largest cities list only 27 businesses with ``North Dakota'' in
their name while 233 use ``Dakota,'' he said.
   A Montana newspaper poked fun at the debate by sponsoring a
contest to suggest a better name. The winner of The Billings Gazette
contest was ``Manitscolda,'' pronounced ``Man-it's-cold-uh,'' an
apparent takeoff on North Dakota's northern neighbor, Manitoba.
   The committee took no action on the resolutions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Crothers thought his pet
lizard was a goner until he began hearing about sightings of a
creature variously described by frightened residents as a 6-foot
alligator or a diminuitive Godzilla.
   Then he knew that Cleopatra, his 3{-foot Nile monitor lizard, was
alive and leaping.
   ``I had already supposed she was dead or someone had stolen her.
But when I heard a few months ago about this thing people were
seeing, I knew right away,'' he said.
   Animal control officers captured Cleopatra on Saturday after a
resident reported seeing the lizard.
   Crothers no longer has room in his life for the reptile, though,
so he sold the lizard to a woman for $75 on Sunday.
   ``I have a 10-month-old daughter and my wife doesn't want it
around the baby,'' he said. ``I don't have the money to go buy it a
new cage, and anyway, I can't keep pets at the apartment I have now.
It's three strikes and you're out.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FREDERICK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials trying to reclaim city streets
from flocks of messy birds have found an unlikely ally: brightly
colored beach ball-sized balloons with huge, buggy eyes.
   ``Supposedly, they look like predators and the birds go somewhere
else,'' Mayor Ronald N. Young said.
   Flocks of blackbirds, crows and other birds have been befouling
sidewalks, cars and pedestrians in this city 45 miles west of
Baltimore.
   ``I was learning how to do the two-step real well,'' said Bonnie
Zimmerman, a secretary at city hall, which is surrounded by trees
and has received a heavy bombing from the birds.
   Advice on how to solve the potentially unsanitary problem has
been plentiful, ranging from mass poisonings to a community bird
shoot.
   Officials seeking a bloodless solution tried electronic chirping
devices and plastic owls without success. But since setting up about
two dozen of the menacing ballooons, the birds have moved along and
city workers have reclaimed park benches in front of city hall.
   ``We're crossing our fingers,'' said Robert L. Strine, the city's
director of public works. ``The short-term results appear good.''
</TEXT>
