<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-PeaceNow     03-07 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Peace Now,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel's Largest Peace Movement Under Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's largest peace movement has come under a
new barrage of criticism from hawks and Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir is heading the attacks by questioning group members' loyalty
to their country.
   Shamir's remarks Sunday that Peace Now activists are in cahoots
with ``the most dangerous and extremist of our enemies'' triggered a
barrage of accusations and counterattacks.
   Peace Now members, like all other Israeli citizens, serve in the
armed forces and do annual reserve duty.
   ``They are sabotaging Israel's political war, the war for
Israel's security ... They are helping the most dangerous and most
extremist of our enemies,'' Shamir said.
   Tzahi Hanegbi, a member of Shamir's hard-line Likud bloc, agreed.
   ``At the height of the uprising when there are blood riots and
Jews are being murdered, they (Peace Now members) go crawling toward
the leaders of the uprising and break a rule that every
self-respecting Jew abides, which is to wait for the government's
decisions,'' Hanegbi said.
   He was referring to the actions Saturday of thousands of Peace
Now members, who tried to drive into the occupied territories to
talk peace with Palestinians. The army, which bars political
activity in the occupied areas, sealed the West Bank and turned back
activists headed to Arab villages.
   Underlying the attacks on Peace Now, however, is the group's
controversial decision several months ago to change its stand toward
the Palestine Liberation Organization _ which right-wing circles
still consider a terrorist organization dedicated to the destruction
of Israel _ and call on the government to talk peace with Chairman
Yasser Arafat.
   The government refuses to negotiate with the PLO.
   Peace Now also favors territorial compromise.
   The loosely organized Peace Now does not keep membership rosters,
and therefore has no clear estimate of its popularity. But scores of
thousands of people turned up at a recent rally calling for talks
with the PLO.
   On Monday, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens urged leftist legislator
Yossi Sarid to cancel a scheduled trip to New York later this week
for a Columbia University conference with PLO officials.
   ``This is an attempt to try and influence the (Israeli)
government, not through a debate in Parliament or through
elections... but through the foreign media and foreign
governments,'' he said. ``This, to my mind, is something that should
not be done.''
   Yisrael Harel, a leader of the Gush Emunim Jewish settlement
movement in the occupied territories, has accused Peace Now of
running to talk with Palestinians while resisting talks with
right-wing Israelis.
   ``The agenda should be that first we come to a national
consensus, and then present that to the Arabs,'' Harel said.
   Shamir, meanwhile, called Peace Now ``the most marginal of
marginal elements,'' and added: ``They aren't worth the paper used
to write on about them.''
   Twenty legislators of left-wing parties and the center-left Labor
Party signed a letter to the prime minister, demanding he retract
the statements, made at a meeting of his right-wing Likud bloc.
   Peace Now activist and playwright Benny Barabash had harsh words
for Shamir, and accused him of ``starting a drive of incitement and
bloodletting.''
   He was referring to the 1983 murder of peace activist Emil
Greenzweig, killed by a fellow Israeli who hurled a hand-grenade
into an anti-war and Peace Now rally.
   Peace Now does not plan to give up its struggle.
   The movement was formed in 1978 as a pressure group to persuade
then-Prime Minister Menachem Begin to make concessions for peace
with Egypt. A peace treaty was signed the following year, with
Israel returning the entire Sinai desert captured in 1967.
   Movement leaders feel the 15-month-old Palestinian uprising has
created an historic opportunity for another peace settlement in the
region.
   ``It's our job to prepare people's hearts for compromise,''
Barabash said.
   Some 399 Arabs and 17 Israelis have been killed in the
Palestinian revolt against Israel's 21-year occupation of the Gaza
Strip and West Bank.
</TEXT>
