<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-07 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Share Prices Recover, Dollar up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
on Tuesday, and the dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 9.63-point
loser Monday, rose 61.08 points, or 0.19 percent, and closed at
31,937.94. The index plunged in early trading but turned around by
midmorning.
   The dollar closed at 129.03 yen, up 1.40 yen from Monday's
127.63-yen finish. It opened at 129.25 yen and ranged between 128.87
yen and 129.28 yen.
   ``The arrest of (Hisashi) Shinto certainly caused the early
morning decline in the index, but a majority of investors seemed to
have recovered from their (initial) discouragement,'' said an
analyst with Nomura Securities in Tokyo.
   Prosecutors on Monday arrested Shinto, former chairman of the
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., Japan's largest company, on
charges of bribery in connection with a major stock scandal
involving top politicians. His arrest was expected to spark concern
over the fate of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's administration.
   Another factor affecting the Nikkei index, a key barometer for
the market, was Tuesday's account settlement in the futures market,
the analyst said. Participants were inclined to sell off issues and
buy cheaper future issues, he said, speaking anonymously.
   In currency dealings, trading was described as light as market
players stepped to the sidelines following news of the arrests of
Shinto and his former secretary, said a dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Because the dollar had risen quite high against the yen already,
participants were reluctant to continue their dollar buying, but
``there are no incentives not to buy the dollar either,'' the dealer
said.
   Meanwhile, Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told reporters
Tuesday that the yen's decline ``did not have anything to do (with
Shinto's arrest). It's a market, afterall, and who knows why it
moves.''
</TEXT>
