<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-07 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Affordability Measure Down in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increases in housing prices and mortgage
interest rates caused a January drop in an index measuring the
ability of a typical American family to buy a home, a real estate
trade group says.
   The National Association of Realtors says its affordability index
was at 108 in January, down from 111.2 in December. It was the
largest month-to-month drop since a similar decline in January 1988.
   The new January number means that a family earning the median
income of $32,207 annually had 8 percent more income than needed to
qualify for a mortgage covering 80 percent of the purchase price of
a median-priced home.
   The median price for an existing home in January was $91,500,
meaning half the homes sold for more and half for less. January's
median was up $2,800 from the previous month.
   The mortgage rate used to calculate the index rose to 9.61
percent in January from 9.59 percent, representing a composite of
fixed and adjustable rates.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>FDA Warns About Garlic Mix</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some commercial and homemade chopped garlic and
oil mixes can cause potentially fatal botulism if left at room
temperature, the federal government warns.
   The Food and Drug Administration also asked producers of the
commercial products to review their labeling to assure that the need
for refrigeration is clearly marked on shipping cartons and the
product containers.
   The warnings follow an investigation in Kingston, N.Y., last
month in which two men and a woman were hospitalized with botulism
after a dinner at the home of one of the victims. The three had
eaten a chopped garlic and oil mix that had been used in a spread
for garlic bread, the FDA said.
   The agency said garlic and oil mixes containing little or no
acidifying agent such as phosphoric or citric acid should be kept
refrigerated at all times _ from manufacture to consumption.
   FDA studies have shown that garlic in an oil mixture can support
growth of clostridium botulinum bacteria, whose spores produce a
deadly toxin under certain conditions.
   Botulism is characterized by blurred or double vision, speech and
breathing difficulty and progressive paralysis. Without prompt and
correct treatment, a third of those diagnosed with it may die, the
FDA said.
   Preliminary findings in the Kingston incident being investigated
by the New York Department of Health implicated a commercially
prepared mix called Colavita Chopped Garlic in Extra Virgin Olive
Oil, distributed by Colavita Pasta and Oil Co., Newark, N.J. The
firm is recalling the product and told New York officials that
distribution was discontinued more than a year ago, the FDA said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Quello Says `Exorbitantly Paid' Media People Campaigned Against Pay</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Hike
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Federal Communications
Commission is castigating ``exorbitantly paid'' television
journalists and entertainers who he said carried out an
unconscionable campaign against the recent attempt in Congress to
raise the pay of high-level federal officials by 51 percent.
   Commissioner James H. Quello, who would have gotten the pay hike
had it cleared Congress, said it was ``the ultimate in
unconscionable self-appreciation for TV and cable personalities ...
many of whom make 10 to 25 times more than a senator or congressman,
to indulge in a Messianic binge against a salary adjustment to keep
pace with inflation for congressmen, key government officials and
judges.''
   ``Are exorbitantly paid personalities and anchors who utilize
government licensed airwaves to accommodate their perpetual quest
for ratings, money and power really performing more valuable service
than those that grant and manage communications licenses, pass laws
and govern the nation? I think not,'' Quello said in a speech for
the New York chapter of the Federal Communications Bar Association.
   The pay plan would have raised congressional salaries from
$89,500 to $135,000. Quello said Congress and the news media
``failed to emphasize enough that this was a catch-up increment''
recommended by the panel ``to keep government pay abreast of
inflation.''
