<HEAD>NICOSIA: into hiding.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The death threat from Iran's fundamentalist patriarch prompted
the 12 European Economic Community nations and several other
countries to withdraw their ambassadors from Iran.
   In a conciliatory move, Britain's Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey
Howe said after the Iran parliament vote last week that ``The
Satanic Verses'' has offended some Britons as well as Moslems.
   Tehran Radio welcome the statement, but demanded that Britain
take ``concrete action.''
   Iran suggested London could defuse the crisis by banning the
novel and prosecuting Rushdie. Britain has steadfastly refused to do
either.
   Nineteen people have died in Pakistan and India in violence
related to the book, which has been banned in countries including
Pakistan, India, Kenya and Egypt.
