<FIRST>r p PM-HumphreyRetiring     03-07 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Humphrey Retiring,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative GOP Senator Won't Seek Third Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Gordon Humphrey says a man can
take only so much of ``meeting presidents and meeting prime
ministers and spending hundreds of billions of dollars a year,'' and
is calling it quits after this term.
   ``You only get one life, and I didn't want to spend the rest of
my productive years in Congress,'' said the 48-year-old Republican,
who describes himself as the most conservative voice in the Senate.
   He said he would return to private life, although he did not rule
out a future run for office.
   Humphrey, with two years left on his six-year term, said he was
making his decision public now to give potential Republican
candidates a chance to raise money needed for the race.
   ``I have to admit I was very tempted to run again, not
withstanding my pledge of old to limit myself to two terms,''
Humphrey said. ``Power, after all, is not only corrupting ... but
it's addictive. It's fun exercising power; politics is fun.''
   The problem, he said, is ``you get caught up with it, meeting
presidents and meeting prime ministers and spending hundreds of
billions of dollars a year. ...
   ``You lose touch with the real world,'' he said. ``I don't think
I've reached that part yet, but I think it could happen in a third
term.''
   A former airline pilot who never considered himself a politician,
Humphrey had never held office before he ran for the Senate in 1978
and pulled a stunning upset over Democratic incumbent Thomas
McIntyre.
   He easily won re-election in 1984, and would have been considered
the favorite to win again in 1990 in a heavily Republican state.
   Humphrey occasionally criticized the Reagan administration for
softening its stance against communism and supporting a
congressional pay raise.
   But his voice has been heard the loudest as an opponent of
abortion and the pay raises and as a supporter for the Afghanistan
rebels.
   Humphrey has consistently been given 100 ratings by conservative
groups that monitor Senate votes and zero ratings by liberal groups.
   Humphrey called Congress a ``wonderful institution, but human
nature mucks it up an awful lot.'' He complained that Congress is
deteriorating because it is ``becoming more and more powerful at the
expense of the presidency.''
   ``We used to hear about the imperial presidency,'' he said.
``Nowadays, we're hearing about the imperial Congress.''
</TEXT>
