<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0610EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0770 03-07 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0770,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mikhail Baryshnikov Stars in `Metamorphosis' on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs with other New York reviews; No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Misha talks! Yes, Mikhail Baryshnikov has as much
stage presence as a theater actor as he does as a dance superstar.
   He proves it in ``Metamorphosis,'' a riveting adaptation of Franz
Kafka's short novel that arrived Monday night at Broadway's Ethel
Barrymore Theater.
   Baryshnikov is fine. But the real star of the evening is director
and adaptor Steven Berkoff, who imposes a theatrical unity on the
play that is astonishing.
   Every component of this stylized production serves the script
brilliantly _ from setting to costumes to lighting to music to
movement to acting. There is a seamlessness to this production, a
quality that also enhanced Berkoff's provocative staging of
``Coriolanus,'' which played recently at the New York Shakespeare
Festival.
   Still, most theatergoers will focus their attention on
Baryshnikov. In his first dramatic stage role, he portrays Gregor
Samsa, a hard-working traveling salesman who wakes up one morning
and finds he is turning into an insect, a dung beetle to be specific.
   You'd expect his physical movements to be superb, and they are.
Dressed in a striped waistcoat and knickers and wearing wire-rimmed
spectacles, Baryshnikov epitomizes Kafka's beleaguered little man,
while at the same time suggesting the insect. He uses his feet,
hands, arms and legs to mime his gradual change into the bug. It's a
startling transformation, powerful, unnerving, yet touched with pity.
   But Baryshnikov also is in command of his voice, using it to
great effect in sorrow _ listen to him call out for his mother _ and
in humor, particularly when he munches the food thrown to him by his
horrified family.
   The action, lasting some 95 minutes without intermission, unfolds
on a raked stage with black lines radiating across a gray floor. The
scenic supervisor is Duke Durfee. A large skeleton of black metal
bars shaped like a spider fans out across the playing area. Three
spider-like stools are strewn across the footlights. Upstage, above
a small ramp, is a cage where Gregor spends much of the evening
watching his family. There are no props. Everything is suggested
rather than played realistically.
   Three other actors, portraying Gregor's family, share the stage
with Baryshnikov for the entire play. Each is a distinctive,
memorable character. Rene Auberjonois plays the father, a gruff
bully fearful of losing his son's meal ticket, while Laura Esterman
is right on the edge _ and on target _ as the loving yet fearful
mother. Madeleine Potter exudes a steel reserve as Gregor's faithful
sister.
   Mitch Kreindel and T.J. Meyers offer fine comic cameos as an
outraged chief clerk and a fussy lodger. In a way, they all scurry
like insects in a frenzy over Gregor's hideous transformation.
   Berkoff sees ``Metamorphosis'' as an existential horror story
with no way out for the tormented Gregor or for the other, almost
hysterical characters.
   The director captures that mood of desolation through dramatic
use of lighting, supervised here by Brian Nason. There are several
episodes when giant shadows play across the back wall of the set,
giving the drama a nightmarish quality. Larry Spivack's music
contributes to that tension, building in volume as the family
realizes what has happened to Gregor and what eventually must be
done to get rid of him.
   Berkoff's production ends on a poignant note. The final image _
Baryshnikov curled up in almost a fetal position _ is haunting. But
then the whole show is a series of haunting images, pictures that
reinforce Kafka's striking story of what society does to those who
are more than a little different.
   In other reviews, Frank Rich wrote in The New York Times: ``It's
hard to guess who will suffer most ... devotees of Franz Kafka,
whose story is distorted into Marxist kitsch by this adaptation, or
fans of Mikhail Baryshnikov, whose stage debut as a dramatic actor,
however dignified, amounts to little more than a sideshow to the
loud circus surrounding him.''
   ``Kafka never lets the human dimension disappear, however surreal
the situation,'' Howard Kissel wrote in the Daily News. ``Berkoff,
on the other hand, never lets the human dimension appear at all. ...
As an attempt to convey Kafka's world, Berkoff's adaptation is
tiresome. As a piece of merchandising, though, it's a triumph.''
   ``The Berkoff play itself is an expressionist impression of the
Kafka original _ with little of the finite detail that makes the
Kafka so chilling and moving,'' wrote Clive Barnes in the New York
Post. ``... However, whatever objections one may have to Berkoff as
an adaptor, his work here as director is fascinating and
unquestionably effective.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
