<FIRST>r a PM-Brite-MissingMayberry     03-07 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brite-Missing Mayberry,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Real-life Hometown of Mayberry Star Victim of Technical Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well gol-l-l-l-y! Not only was Sheriff Andy
Taylor's hometown of Mayberry mythical; the hometown of actor Andy
Griffith, who created the role, hasn't existed for decades.
   Mount Airy has been in a Twilight Zone.
   As a result of a typographical error, the city's charter was
inadvertently repealed by the Legislature on March 29, 1967. That
means that such official acts as tax levies, elections and town
expenditures haven't been valid _ technically _ since then.
   ``Whoops,'' said state Rep. David H. Diamont. ``Legally, the
whole town hasn't existed for 22 years.''
   To patch things up, Diamont has introduced a bill to validate all
acts by the Surry County municipality's town board since the foul-up.
   Legislative officials aren't sure who made the mistake, but
believe it apparently occurred in drafting legislation or in putting
the law on the books.
   Gerry F. Cohen, director of bill drafting for the Legislature,
said staffers recently spotted the error after Mount Airy officials
asked about a law concerning the appointment of the tax collector.
   ``We found the disappearance of Mount Airy while doing
research,'' Cohen said. ``I wouldn't be surprised if there were
other missing cities out there.''
</TEXT>
