<FIRST>r i PM-India-Afghanistan     03-07 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Afghanistan,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>India to Provide Afghan Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India will provide economic and
humanitarian aid to the embattled Soviet-backed government of
President Najib in Afghanistan, officials of both countries say.
   Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil of Afghanistan declined to give any
details of the assistance, which was announced Monday as he
completed a five-day visit.
   He would not say if it would involve an airlift of food to the
besieged Afghan capital of Kabul. Most of the Afghan countryside is
in guerrilla hands.
   A spokesman for India's Foreign Ministry also said agreement had
been reached but gave no details.
   The Afghan official accused Western nations of thwarting relief
missions. A U.N. airlift of food was halted after one flight last
month when airline crews refused to fly to Kabul, fearing for their
safety.
   The United States, western European nations and their allies
closed their embassies in Kabul in January and February as the
Soviet Union withdrew the last of its troops from Afghanistan.
   The Western allies said they were worried security would
deteriorate after the Soviet withdrawal was completed on Feb. 15.
   India is the only non-Soviet bloc nation that maintained
relations with Kabul after the Soviet Union intervened in
Afghanistan in 1979 to prop up its client regime.
   Speaking in Dari through an interpreter, Wakil repeated his
government's complaints that the United States and Pakistan were
continuing to support the guerrillas who have been fighting to
unseat his government for a decade.
</TEXT>
