<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TownProfits     03-07 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Town Profits,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>2{ Years After Town's Takeover, Furniture Company Builds Pride</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROPHETSTOWN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visionaries in this aging small town
wanted to bring profits to Prophetstown to save it, so they went out
and bought a company.
   ``We figured if we didn't grow, we'd die,'' said Howard ``Bud''
Thompson, 58, a hog hauler and president of Prophetstown
Manufacturing Inc., which brought Clear Creek Furniture Co. to this
community of 2,100.
   ``It's going to take something like this to keep small towns
alive, revived, or whatever you want to call it,'' he said. ``As you
go around Illinois you can smell death.''
   Clear Creek has eight workers who saw, sand and spray finish on
oak furniture patterned after designs of the 18th and 19th century.
The furniture sells in 14 states, especially the Midwest.
   With the federal government's approval, local officials created
PMI, sold $10 shares and made an offer to Darrell Milsap: You need
the capital, we want your furniture.
   Milsap and his wife, Diane, packed up the company and moved 75
miles from Granville in north-central Illinois to the banks of the
Rock River in Whiteside County, where they manage the business now
owned by PMI.
   ``It's very difficult to keep a small town going,'' said Clear
Creek's chief assembler, Wayne Proeger, 34, turning off his electric
saw to talk about the company and the future of his hometown,
population 2,100, about 140 miles west of Chicago.
   ``I like living in small, rural communities. There's more of a
relationship between citizens. In big cities people don't talk to
one another.''
   Thompson, a member of the Illinois State Board of Education,
believes the furniture company has boosted the town's pride. When
PMI was selling stock to make the purchase of Clear Creek possible,
it posted signs that said, ``Buy A Share In Prophetstown's Future.''
   Many did.
   ``The spirit has returned,'' said Thompson, who noted that
residents, many of whom are elderly, recently voted twice over 12
months to raise their taxes.
   ``People keep their lawns mowed and their bushes trimmed. Pride _
it's an ingredient I sure appreciate. I know it sounds a little
hokey, but that's what it's all about.''
   PMI hopes to add a few more small companies to Prophetstown's
economy, moves that would depend on the profits earned at Clear
Creek.
   Last year, Clear Creek had sales of $280,000. Thompson is
projecting sales of $360,000 for 1989, and Milsap hopes to add a
second shift.
   ``Sales haven't been a problem,'' said Thompson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-07 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Hits Atlantic Seaboard With Snow, Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow and rain was falling along much of the Atlantic seaboard
this morning while rain was falling in northern California and parts
of the Pacific Northwest.
   A storm centered over North Carolina produced snow from the Ohio
Valley to the middle Atlantic states and southern New England. The
heaviest accumulations were in Pennsylvania, where up to 10 inches
blanketed the Laurel Mountains in the western part of the state and
up to 6 inches fell in eastern areas.
   Winter storm warnings were in effect today for northern and
central portions of Maryland and Delaware, northern Virginia and the
eastern part of West Virginia.
   Showers and thunderstorms doused part of the southern Atlantic
Coast region. Fayetteville, N.C., recorded 1.37 inches of rain in
the six hours ending at 1 a.m. EST. Several other areas between
Maryland and South Carolina had over three-quarters of an inch.
   In the West, a cold front carried rain into northern California
and parts of the Pacific Northwest.
   A winter storm watch was posted for late today for the Lake Tahoe
area of Nevada and the northern Sierra Nevada range of California.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation this morning.
   Today's forecast called for snow in the middle Atlantic region,
with some lingering snow likely in the central Appalachians and the
upper Ohio Valley. Rain was expected to be scattered across the
Carolinas and central and southern Florida, and widespread from the
northern and central Pacific Coast to Idaho and Utah.
   Highs were forecast to be in the teens and 20s from the Northeast
to the Great Lakes; the 30s from eastern parts of the northern
Plains through the middle Mississippi Valley, the lower Ohio and
Tennessee valleys into southern Virginia; the 60s and 70s from
central and Southern California through the southern Rockies to the
Rio Grande Valley of Texas, and across much of the Florida
peninsula; and the 80s to near 90 degrees across the desert
Southwest. Highs elsewhere were expected to be in the 40s or 50s.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 14 degrees below zero at
Houlton, Maine, to 77 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 36 cloudy; Boston 14 windy; Buffalo 10 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 54 fair; Cincinnati 21 snow; Cleveland 18
windy; Detroit 13 windy; Miami 72 partly cloudy; New York 24 windy;
Philadelphia 23 snow; Pittsburgh 17 snow; Portland, Maine 4 fair;
Washington 26 freezing drizzle.
   _Central: Bismarck 14 fair; Chicago 20 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 24
fair; Denver 36 fair; Des Moines 20 partly cloudy; Indianapolis 18
fair; Kansas City 24 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 15 partly cloudy;
Nashville 32 drizzle; New Orleans 35 cloudy; St. Louis 21 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 36 fair; Anchorage 17 fair; Las Vegas 55 fair;
Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 63 fair; Salt Lake City 36 foggy; San
Diego 58 fair; San Francisco 55 cloudy; Seattle 37 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal -12 fair; Toronto 3 partly cloudy.
