<FIRST>r a PM-People-Cronkite     03-07 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Cronkite,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cronkite Says `Trash' Television Harming Good Journalism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists today are generally more
responsible than ever, but some ``trash television'' interview
programs are ``absolutely, totally useless stuff,'' says Walter
Cronkite.
   The former CBS anchorman said programs that depend on the sordid,
lurid and sensational endanger good journalism.
   ``I am concerned about the garbage that is masquerading as
television these days,'' Cronkite said. ``Most of it is real
scandal-tabloid journalism ... absolutely, totally useless stuff.''
   But, Cronkite said, ``We're very lucky. ... We have a more
responsible press today in this country than we've ever had.''
   He said reporters now are much more enterprising and
conscientious than during the mid-1940s and several years after,
when journalists were passive and practiced ``reporting by handout.''
   Cronkite, who lives in New York, made his remarks Monday during a
news conference to pitch a local water pollution documentary he
narrated. He signed off for the last time as anchor of ``The CBS
Evening News'' eight years ago Monday.
</TEXT>
