<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Iran     03-07 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Iran,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Fear for Hostages After Iran Breaks Ties With Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Verses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives and friends of Britons believed held in
Lebanon and Iran said today that Iran's decision to break diplomatic
ties with Britain will make it harder to free the captives.
   ``Hostages' families all around the world will be upset that a
major player in this game is now out of the arena,'' said John
Waite, a cousin of missing Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite. ``We
will have to sit back and wait, rather dismayed.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported today that
Iran decided to sever ties at the end of a one-week deadline that
Iran's parliament had set for Britain to disavow Salman Rushdie's
novel, ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Britain withdrew its diplomats from Iran after Iran's spiritual
leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, called for Rushdie's death on
Feb. 14. The novel has set off worldwide protests by Moslems holding
the book to be blasphemous.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Saturday that Iran must
repudiate the death threat before diplomatic relations can be
normalized.
   Britain seeks the release of three of its nationals held in
Lebanon by pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists _ Waite, journalist
John McCarthy and teacher Brian Keenan, a Belfast man with dual
British and Irish nationality whose release is also sought by the
Irish government.
   The Foreign Office says it also seeks word on Alec Collett, a New
York-based British journalist whose Palestinian abductors claim they
killed him. His body was never found.
   ``Nothing can ever be resolved unless there can be discussions
with the other side _ that was the whole basis of Terry's life,''
said John Waite, whose 49-year-old cousin vanished in Beirut on Jan.
20, 1987, while trying to negotiate the release of two U.S. hostages.
   Waite said many Moslems had been ``deeply insulted'' by Rushdie's
novel. But he added, ``I don't see that the British government could
have acted in any other way'' over Khomeini's death threat.
   The brother of British businessman Roger Cooper, imprisoned in
Tehran for alleged spying, said he expected the diplomatic break to
remain for ``quite some time.''
   ``Iran doesn't like losing face, and they are unlikely to come
forward with a begging bowl,'' said journalist Paul Cooper. ``This
will have a very negative effect on the chances of my brother and
the hostages (in Lebanon) being released. It is a sad day.''
   ``Our government appears to have made the condition that Khomeini
should retract what he said, but he is not the type of person to do
that,'' Cooper told reporters.
   Chris Pearson, a friend of McCarthy, said the hostages' prospects
of being freed ``have evaporated for the time being.''
   Fifteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing in
Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson, the chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
