<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0850EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DeathPenalty     03-07 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Penalty,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator Sees New York Restoring Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York will have a new death penalty law by
Nov. 1, predicts the chief Assembly sponsor of legislation to put
the state's electric chair back into use after a 26-year hiatus.
   The Democrat-controlled Assembly approved a bill to restore
capital punishment, following an emotional debate that lasted more
than five hours Monday night.
   On the strength of the 97-48 vote, sponsor Vincent Graber, a
Buffalo-area Democrat, predicted his chamber would override a
promised veto by Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   The Republican-controlled state Senate is certain to do likewise,
having approved the death-penalty bill each year for 12 years, most
recently last month. The Senate has voted to override Cuomo's
vetoes, but the Assembly hasn't.
   Monday's 97 death penalty supporters plus two who were absent add
up to 99 ``yes'' votes in the 150-member Assembly. Graber predicted
he would have the 100 votes needed for a veto override by the time
the attempt comes, probably in May.
   ``Certainly it's a whole new ballgame,'' said Graber of the
political pressure that will face death penalty opponents. ``I think
one of them will blink.''
   New York is one of only 13 states without a death penalty law,
and the only one among the nation's seven largest states. New York's
old death penalty statute was gradually eliminated by a series of
court rulings, and the electric chair was last used in 1963.
   Cuomo favors a life-without-parole sentence for murderers.
   During the debate, Graber noted that the number of murders in New
York state last year rose to 2,225, an increase of 213 murders from
1987. And pointing out that most of those murders occurred in New
York City, Graber read off a list of what he said were the 20 most
dangerous Assembly districts in the state. All were in New York City
and all but one were represented by legislators who had voted
against the death penalty bill in the past.
   ``I wouldn't want to reside in one of these Assembly districts,''
Graber said. ``Not having a death penalty in this state isn't
working.''
</TEXT>
