<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0922EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-War     03-07 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-War,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Expected to Launch Offensive on Key Afghan Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western diplomats said today they
expect Moslem guerrillas soon will launch a long-awaited offensive
against communist forces who still hold Afghanistan's key cities
following the Soviet pullout.
   Insurgents fighting to establish an Islamic republic hint they
are preparing a decisive battle to bring down the Marxist Kabul
government once spring melts snowbound mountain passes, the
diplomats said.
   ``The battle plans appear likely to be executed roughly
simultaneously, with serious fighting expected in most areas during
the month,'' one Western source said on condition of anonymity.
   Guerrilla spokesmen in neighboring Pakistan said an interim
government announced Feb. 24 by the fighters may hold its first
meeting inside Afghanistan on Thursday.
   Washington and Islamabad, the guerrillas' main backers, have
withheld formal recognition of the rival government until it
establishes a capital and begins a functional administration.
   ``Regime forces are extremely worried about the imminent massive
assault by the Afghan (guerrillas) in many areas,'' the Afghan News
Agency of guerrilla leader Gulbaddin Hekmatyar claimed Monday.
   It said the insurgents have sent clandestine messages to
civilians to flee eastern Jalalabad city and the southeastern city
of Kandahar. Diplomats earlier reported similar notices in the
capital.
   Combined assaults on the key cities of Kabul, Jalalabad, Kandahar
and Herat in the west will be tricky.
   Guerrilla field commanders have disagreed over timing and tactics
for fear of causing unnecessary civilian casualties. Many have
argued for an extended siege to encourage defections in hopes the
communists will collapse from poor morale.
   Nearly 1.5 million Afghans, or 10 percent of the population, have
died in the civil war since the ruling People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan seized power in a 1978 coup.
   Soviet forces intervened in December 1979. They withdrew last
month after losing 13,000 men.
   Western diplomats in Pakistan said commanders based near
Jalalabad also are concerned about their ability to control outsize
guerrilla groups that have converged there.
   ``(It) could become a problem, entailing unnecessary killing and
destruction,'' said one source.
   Combined reports indicate fighting around Afghanistan is on the
rise after a winter lull.
   The guerrillas claim thousands of government troops have
surrendered or been captured since the last Red Army soldiers went
home on Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
