<FIRST>r a PM-SeaLions     03-07 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sea Lions,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Sea Lion Swims Back To Ballard Locks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California sea lions with a taste for trout are
frustrating wildlife officials by swimming nearly 300 miles back to
Seattle's ship canal within days after they are trucked off to the
ocean.
   Agents trying to protect a wild fish run caught three more sea
lions on Monday, said Susan Ewing of the Washington Department of
Wildlife.
   But a third sea lion that was trapped and shipped to the Pacific
Ocean has returned to the Ballard ship locks, a favorite fishing
ground for the sea lions, said Hal Alabaster, spokesman for the
National Marine Fisheries service.
   The latest returnee was discovered in the floating capture cage
being used to trap the sea lions in an effort to protect steelhead
trout migrating from Puget Sound to Lake Washington through a ship
canal, Alabaster said.
   The three sea lions that have returned have made the 280-mile
trip in four days.
   ``I think we're kind of taking it in stride,'' Ms. Ewing said.
``At least we're giving the fish some relief.''
   Wildlife agents plan to ship all the captured sea lions to
Klipsan Beach on the southwestern Washington coast.
   Eleven sea lions have been transported to the beach. Two others
that were trapped died after they were sedated for tagging, and five
more were let go because cold weather made it risky to drive them to
the coast.
</TEXT>
