<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SkeletalBaby     03-07 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skeletal Baby,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Dead Baby May Have Lived About A Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELKRIDGE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The skeleton of an infant found in a trunk
appears to have been a girl who lived about a month before dying of
an unknown cause 50 years ago, according to a Smithsonian
Institution anthropologist.
   Douglas H. Ubelaker, curator of anthropology at the Smithsonian,
said Monday the age of the baby's remains ``were compatible'' with a
T-shirt the infant was wearing that bore the logo ``World's Fair
1939.''
   He and the state medical examiner, Dr. John E. Smialek, said the
infant appeared to have been alive for as long as a month before it
died and there was no evidence of any fatal injury or disease that
might have caused the death.
   Smialek said his office is ``listing the cause of death as
undetermined.''
   The remains were found Feb. 15 in an steamer trunk kept by the
late Martha C. Shields in the basement of her home in this small
town about eight miles south of Baltimore. The skeleton was wrapped
in blankets, along with a Bible, a small chest and the remnants of a
baby girl's white dress.
   Mrs. Shields' children, Robert, 29, and Joyce, 31, told state
police that they made the discovery Feb. 15 when they opened the
trunk expecting to find their mother's will.
   When the two were young, their mother had warned them never to
play near the trunk, they said. Before she died Feb. 13 of a liver
ailment and other problems, the 67-year-old woman asked them to take
care of what was inside it, police said.
   Neither child could remember any family discussion of a sister
who died at birth or shortly afterward.
   Smialek said the examination of the remains did not determine
whether Mrs. Shields bore the child.
   Detective Michael E. Davey of the Maryland State Police said he
has drawn a blank on his investigation.
   ``Unless somebody comes forward, there is nothing more we can
do,'' he said. ``We can't even determine if a crime occurred.''
</TEXT>
