<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Bomb,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Land Mine Explosion Kills Five Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five children died when a bomb
resembling a toy exploded in a refugee village on Pakistan's border
with Afghanistan, a newspaper reported today.
   The independent English-language newspaper The Nation said a
sixth child was seriously injured in Monday's explosion.
   One of the children spotted an object that looked like a toy, and
when they picked it up, the object exploded, the Lahore newspaper
said, citing unidentified government officials.
   There was no immediate official comment on the report.
   More than 3 million Afghan war refugees live in Pakistan, which
has been the target of hundreds of bomb explosions. Most have ripped
through crowded bazaars in villages and cities in the Northwest
Frontier Province that borders Afghanistan.
   Most Afghan refugees live in tent villages and sprawling camps of
adobe huts in the border province.
   Local authorities charge Afghanistan's ruling communists are
behind the explosions. Many Afghan guerrilla groups are based in
Pakistan.
   A civil war has raged in Afghanistan since 1978. In December
1979, Soviet troops intervened to back the government, but the
Soviets withdrew all troops Feb. 15.
