<FIRST>u i PM-Korea-PlaneBombing     03-07 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Plane Bombing,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tight Security as North Korean Stands Trial for Plane Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of police and security guards
held back vengeful relatives today as a confessed North Korean agent
went on trial for the bombing of a South Korean airliner that killed
115 people.
   ``I`m here to kill you!'' shouted one person. ``Bring back my
husband!'' another screamed at Kim Hyon Hui as security agents led
her into the courtroom.
   She buried her face in her hands and sobbed.
   In January 1988, she admitted on South Korean television that she
planted a bomb disguised as a radio and liquor on the Boeing 707 in
November 1987 to disrupt last summer's Olympic Games in Seoul. She
also told the court today she had been a North Korean agent.
   The Korean Air plane flying from Baghdad to Seoul disappeared
over the Andaman Sea as it approached the Burmese coast. All 115
passengers and crew were lost.
   North Korea denies it had anything to do with the bomb.
   About 1,500 police and security agents guarded the court today to
prevent disruption from relatives and possible threats from North
Korean agents.
   Crying and sobbing relatives among a few allowed into the
courtroom interrupted the hearing repeatedly, demanding the
defendant's death. Twenty security agents surrounded her.
   Some relatives shouted claims that Kim actually was a South
Korean agent used by the government to discredit the north and stir
up support for the Seoul administration.
   Prosecutor Ahn Kang-min reviewed Kim's life story, questioning
her about her training as a North Korean intelligence agent. The
accused sat slumped forward, replying ``yes'' to all the questions.
   The defendant repeated an earlier statement that she received the
order to blow up the plane through a top Communist Party official
who said he acted for Kim Jung Il, son and political heir of North
Korean leader Kim Il Sung.
   Ahn presented charges of mass murder, destruction of an aircraft
and violation of national security and civil aviation laws.
   The court adjourned until March 21, when defense lawyers will
present their case.
   Court sources who declined to be identified said the woman
probably will be saved from the death sentence because she allegedly
was duped by North Korean intelligence.
   The bomber has said North Korean officials fooled her into
believing South Korea was a police state, but she realized she was
duped after she was brought to Seoul.
   Other captured North Korean intelligence operatives have been
pardoned and used as propaganda symbols against the north.
   The defendant and an elderly man who helped her plant the bomb
were arrested shortly after the blast in Bahrain. They tried to take
cyanide hidden in cigarettes. The other agent died. Kim recovered
and was extradited.
   South Korea successfully hosted the Olympics last September.
Communist North Korea boycotted after it unsuccessfully demanding to
be a co-host of the Games, which it saw as a major political coup
for Seoul.
   The two Koreas have been enemies since the division of the Korean
peninsula in 1945.
</TEXT>
