<HEAD>Kohl Asks Soviet Union To Withdraw Chemical Weapons From Eastern
Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arms Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl today called on
the Soviet Union to remove its chemical weapons from Eastern Europe,
a day after the United States said it wanted to speed their removal
from West Germany.
   ``The United States has taken a step that the Soviet Union and
its allies should now follow without delay,'' Kohl said.
   ``I call on the Soviet Union, in turn, to pull out its chemical
weapons stationed in Eastern Europe and to destroy them,'' Kohl said
in a statement issued to the news media.
   On Monday, U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
President Bush is exploring ways to accelerate the removal of aging
U.S. chemical weapons from West Germany.
   ``The United States is prepared to lead in dealing with this
problem,'' Baker said.
   Kohl said he was hopeful that the weapons could be withdrawn
ahead of a 1992 deadline agreed upon by both sides in 1986.
   Government officials said Monday the weapons would be removed and
destroyed in the United States.
