<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Judge-Bribery     03-07 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Judge-Bribery,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Pleads Guilty To Bribery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three city judges charged after a federal
bribery investigation pleaded guilty today in a deal that set her
maximum sentence at five years in prison, court officials said.
   Recorder's Judge Evelyn Cooper was to have gone on trial today in
U.S. District Court on charges of accepting $9,000 in bribes to fix
two criminal cases and arrange for a convict's early release. The
indictment also charged her with failing to report income from the
bribes.
   Cooper, 47, pleaded guilty to one count of extortion of $5,000
and to signing a false tax return for 1984, said a court spokeswoman
who would not give her name.
   Cooper had faced 20 years in prison if convicted of bribery, and
three years for filing a false tax return. No sentencing date was
set.
   In the other bribery cases, a state district judge is serving a
10-year sentence and another judge was acquitted last week of four
bribery charges but a mistrial was declared on a racketeering charge.
</TEXT>
