<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PLO-Habash     03-07 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO-Habash,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marxist PLO Leader Vows to Escalate Struggle Against Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a Marxist PLO faction today
said his group would increase guerrilla attacks against Israel,
saying such actions were not included in the Palestine Liberation
Organization's renunciation of terrorism.
   George Habash, leader of the Marxist Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, told a news conference ``there is no
resolution (by the Palestine National Council) ... providing for a
truce in south Lebanon between us and the Israelis.''
   He said his guerrillas ``will not only keep up the armed
struggle, but also will escalate it and diversify its forms and
methods.'' He did not elaborate.
   His organization is the second-largest faction of the PLO after
Yasser Arafat's Fatah.
   In December, the United States ended a 13-year ban on public
contacts with the PLO and initiated dialogue with PLO chief Arafat
after he renounced terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   Arafat's announcement was more explicit than a statement issued
by the Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, in
November.
   Arafat, like Habash, has said military operations against Israel
were not considered terrorist acts. But he recently indicated he
would be willing to negotiate a truce in south Lebanon.
   Washington has said guerrilla attacks in south Lebanon could have
a negative impact on the U.S.- PLO dialogue. There has been no
progress in the talks since President Bush took over in January.
   Since December, guerrillas have clashed three times with Israeli
troops and their allies in south Lebanon. Ten guerrillas have been
killed in the shootouts, but no Israelis have been hurt.
   Israeli officials have said that in all three cases, the
guerrillas were planning to infiltrate into Israel, but were
uncovered while still in Israel's self-designated security zone in
south Lebanon. Israel set up the buffer in 1985 when it removed the
bulk of its forces, three years after invading Lebanon.
   Israeli jets have struck Palestinian targets in Lebanon three
times this year, killing two guerrillas and wounding 34 people.
</TEXT>
