<FIRST>u p PM-TownMeeting 1stLd-Writethru a0504 03-07 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Town Meeting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Current Issues In Traditonal Format Mark Town Meeting Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with cold affecting turnout, results of Monday
night meetings. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electing a successor to socialist Bernie
Sanders as Burlington's mayor, a push to bring back the death
penalty and a host of environmental issues were on the agenda today
as Vermont observed its annual Town Meeting Day.
   Voters braved wind chills of 43 degrees below zero to travel to
their local town halls and settle affairs for another year.
   In Burlington, turnout was described as light to moderate.
``Maybe their cars, some of them probably wouldn't start this
morning,'' said Jean Poulin, an office assistant in City Clerk James
Rader's office.
   Burlington, population 38,000 and the nearest thing Vermont has
to a big city, will be choosing between a liberal Democrat and two
candidates further to the left to replace Sanders.
   The 47-year-old mayor, nationally known for outraged rhetoric
against American corporate capitalism, is taking leave from
politics, at least temporarily, to teach and write.
   Peter Clavelle, who eschews the socialist label but is running
under the banner of Sanders' Progressive Coalition, is favored to
win over Democrat Nancy Chioffi and Greens party candidate Sandra
Baird.
   Clavelle initially angered many Sanders backers by ducking even
the Progressive label, calling himself only an ``independent'' in
his first batch of campaign literature. But lately he has more
clearly articulated the activist politics he helped execute as chief
of the Community Economic Development Office under Sanders.
   In about three dozen towns around Vermont, residents will be
voting on a non-binding resolution asking the Legislature to
reinstate the death penalty, last used in the 1950s.
   On Monday night, at least six towns approved the death penalty
resolution. It was tabled in one community and rejected in three,
including Rockingham, where residents said they were afraid of
sending an innocent person to the electric chair.
   At least nine towns will decide whether to form environmental
conservation commissions. Nine communities already have such boards,
which are volunteer groups created to protect a town's natural
resources.
   In several other communities, voters may authorize selectmen to
create funds with local taxes to protect land resources such as
farmland, waterfront property and scenic areas.
   Several towns approved resolutions expressing worries about a
proposed pipeline to bring natural gas from western Canada through
New England. In Rockingham, where the proposed line would go through
a historic cemetery and two church parking lots, residents approved
a resolution to examine the safety and economic need for the line.
   In Hartford, residents approved a resolution giving them a say if
the state tries to locate a proposed 15,000-seat sports and arts
complex in their town. Proponents want the complex to keep the Volvo
International Tennis Tournament in the state.
</TEXT>
