<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0502 03-07 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Reports Progress In Talks With Polish Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs with meeting over, Walesa reporting progress;
pickup 2nd graf pvs, ``The session ...'' TRIMS thereafter to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa today met
with Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak and later reported progress in
monthlong negotiations between the opposition and communist
government.
   He announced the last session of the talks would be held April 3,
and various working groups composed of experts will finish putting
the final touches on the accord by March 20.
   The period between March 20 and April 3 would be devoted to
reviewing the agreement, he said.
   ``All basic problems, like pluralism, ... will be achieved in
time, in line with our commitments,'' said the Solidarity leader,
looking cheerful after the eight-hour meeting with the leader of the
government side in the talks. ``I am very satisfied.''
   Walesa indicated agreement was reached on legalizing the three
main banned independent organizations at issue in the talks _ the
Solidarity trade union movement, the farmers' union Rural Solidarity
and the Independent Students Association.
   Agreements on ``all those organizations, a mininum of three''
will be achieved, he said.
   He said further talks with Kiszczak might be necessary.
   ``We are removing obstacles that have appeared here and there.
But we are only removing them politically, and the rest must be
worked out at the (various working group) tables,'' he said.
   Walesa spoke outside the Roman Catholic episcopate in Warsaw
after returning with a vanful of advisers from the meeting in a
secluded government villa outside the capital.
   The session came the morning after a Communist Party session that
gave Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski qualified support for his policy of
rapprochement with the opposition, government spokesman Jerzy Urban
said in a telephone interview.
   Urban described Monday's meeting of the party's governing Central
Committee as ``very difficult.''
   He said committee members ``expressed different fears and doubts,
remembering the events of 1981,'' when Solidarity grew in membership
to include one of every three Poles and pressed its demands with
general strike threats.
   Authorities suppressed the free trade union movement in a
December 1981 military crackdown, ending its 16-month legal
existence.
   ``The general outcome of the meeting (Monday) was approval for
the party leadership,'' Urban said.
   Walesa and the interior minister also met Thursday and agreed
that the talks, aimed at restoring the Solidarity's legal status and
producing a consensus for guiding the country out of economic
turmoil, should move more quickly.
   The two sides are in general agreement on the outlines of a
national compromise: legalization of Solidarity in exchange for the
opposition's participation in early elections that would guarantee
the ruling Communist Party a continued majority in parliament.
   But several obstacles have appeared, including the authorities'
hesitation to legalize the Independent Students' Association,
disagreement over a program to index wages to inflation and how much
access the opposition is to be given to the state-controlled mass
media.
</TEXT>
