<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Violence 4thLd-Writethru a0524 03-07 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Violence, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0524,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed By Car Bomb Near West Beirut Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1, BEI2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, ``Three people ...'' to UPDATE with civilians
carrying most of the wounded to the hospital. Pickup 8th pvs ``Jumblatt
charged ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded near the American
University Hospital in Moslem west Beirut today, killing two women
and injuring 21 people, police said.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt, a staunch ally of the Syrians who
police west Beirut, blamed the blast on the Christian cabinet of
Gen. Michel Aoun.
   The explosive-laden yellow Fiat blew up in front of a fruit and
vegetable stall at an intersection off a main commercial
thoroughfare.
   One of the victims was killed as she maneuvered to park her car
near the stand, police said.
   Another woman died at the hospital, said a police spokesman, who
under standing regulations is not identified.
   The explosion started a fire involving several parked cars and
shattered glass in surrounding buildings.
   Three people were evacuated by ambulance, and the police
spokesman said ``civilians carried most of the casualties on their
backs to the American University hospital,'' several hundered yards
away.
   Jumblatt charged at a news conference that the bomb was part of a
campaign by the Christian cabinet to choke private militias in
Lebanon.
   ``Those who are trying to encircle us, today sent us a
booby-trapped message,'' Jumblatt told a news conference at his
family's ancestral palace in Mukhtara, southeast of Beirut.
   Tensions between Lebanon's rival Christian and Moslem cabinets
have increased since Monday, when Aoun ordered the army to block
merchant ships trying to dock at militia-controlled ports instead of
those run by the government.
   Aoun has said his move will cut off the main revenues of private
armies. But his Syrian-backed Moslem rivals view it as an economic
blockade of Moslem regions.
   At the scene of the blast, a witness who also spoke on condition
of anonymity said he was in a building 150 feet away when the blast
occurred. It shattered windows there.
   ``I was having my coffee. First, I felt the glass crumbling down,
then I heard the blast.''
   He said when he looked out of the window, he saw fires and a body
lying in the street.
   Gunmen fired their rifles in the air to make way for the
ambulances.
   It was the fourth car bombing in Lebanon this year.
   By police count, 11 people have been killed and 47 wounded in the
previous three car bombings since Jan. 13.
   Last year, 116 people were killed and 488 wounded in 20 car bomb
explosions across the country, plagued by a 14-year-old civil war.
   No group claimed any of the explosions, but Moslem and Christian
officials have blamed each other's militias for them.
</TEXT>
