<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-SpurnedShip     03-07 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Spurned Ship,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Nuclear-Powered Refused Three Port Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Soviet Far Eastern ports, wary of nuclear
power after the Chernobyl disaster, have refused to allow the
docking of a nuclear-powered merchant ship that a newspaper today
compared to a ``homeless child.''
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said the 858-foot-long Sevmorput has been
anchored off Vladivostok for four days because the City Council
refused it entry. The newspaper said city officials will not allow
the ship to dock until they receive additional information about its
radiation safety.
   Officials of the Pacific port of Nakhodka and the coastal Magadan
region have also rejected port calls by the ship, the newspaper said.
   The newspaper said fractures recently appeared in the $260
million ship, but that its ``atomic heart'' was not damaged. It did
not say how the damage was inflicted.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said the vessel was like a ``sea monster''
and a huge ``offended homeless child.''
   On Saturday, the newspaper Vodny Transport reported that a
nuclear reactor meltdown nearly occurred last fall aboard another
nuclear-powered ship, the icebreaker Rossiya.
   Public opposition to nuclear power has been mounting in the
Soviet Union since the April 26, 1986, explosion and fire at the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant in the Ukraine. At least 31 people
were killed in the accident, and a cloud of radiation spread
worldwide.
</TEXT>
