<FIRST>r w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0441 03-07 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's Open to Sensible Answer on Problem of Assault Weapons</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 7 grafs new with Bush comments this morning. Picks up 2rd
graf pvs, ``You've fought.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he is open to a
``sensible answer'' to the proliferation of semiautomatic assault
weapons and has asked William Bennett, his nominee for drug policy
coordinator, to work on it.
   Bush, a member of the National Rifle Association, has said he
opposes a ban on such guns. In a news conference today, he said he
talked to Bennett about the problem after Bennett was quoted as
saying he might favor curtailment of such weapons as a way to cut
down on drug-related violence.
   Bush said he told Bennett: ``I'm not so rigid that if you come to
me with a sensible answer that takes care of the concerns that I've
felt over the years, I'll take a hard look at it, and I'll work with
you to that end.''
   He said he wants to find ``what can be worked out with finality
on AK47s ... and still do what's right by the legitimate sportsman.''
   ``It isn't as easy as it seems,'' Bush said.
   Bush was to have gone to Pennsylvania today to speek on drugs,
but the trip was scrapped due to the icy and snowy weather that
battered the East Coast.
   On Monday, Bush began a week devoted to an anti-drug message,
appealing to military veterans to help combat narcotics by
encouraging drug-education programs and anti-drug legislation at the
state and local levels.
   ``You've fought for your nation once and your nation needs you
again,'' Bush said in an address Monday to several thousand people
at a Veterans of Foreign Wars conference.
   Bush has asked Congress for $5.5 billion for the battle against
drugs, with most of the money going to law enforcement efforts and
border interdiction.
   His request for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 is 21 percent
more than the $4.6 billion allocated for this year. It is $236
million more than former President Ronald Reagan had sought in his
first draft of the spending plan.
   Bush told the veterans that drugs were ``a threat no less real
than the adversaries you have battled.''
   ``The notion that America is a nation at peace is only partly
true, as long as the violence and destructive power of drugs assault
our communities,'' he said.
   Bush said he will ``mobilize all our resources, wage this war on
all fronts. We're going to combat drug abuse with education,
treatment, enforcement ... interdiction and, yes, with our nation's
armed services.''
   Speaking of involvement by the military, Bush said, ``when that
prudently can be done and when that's what it takes, we are going to
have to go all out.''
   Bush had planned to carry his anti-drug message today to
Pennsylvania and Delaware, but a storm along the East Coast caused
him to cancel the trip. White House aides said it would be
rescheduled, probably for next week.
   On another subject, Bush said Monday that he supports ``lower
levels of armaments'' in Europe but with a continued backup by
nuclear weapons.
   ``For America and its allies, a survivable nuclear force will
remain the ultimate deterrent of aggression,'' Bush said.
   His comments coincided with a proposal by the Kremlin for heavy
reductions in troops and armor in Europe. Moscow also urged
negotiations to eliminate all battlefield nuclear weapons from the
continent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
