<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--StowawayCat     03-07 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Stowaway Cat,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kitty Survives Trans-Atlantic Journey, Not Quarantine Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stowaway cat from Baltimore survived a
two-week journey by land and sea from the United States without food
or water _ only to be killed when it arrived in Britain because of
strict quarantine laws, an official said Tuesday.
   The cat apparently was locked in a container full of tires in
Baltimore, said John Mackie, Staffordshire county's emergency
planning officer.
   The container made the 3,000-mile journey to an auto factory in
Rocester, western England, by ship and truck.
   The long-haired, gray-and-white cat survived by drinking the
condensation on the inside of the sealed container, Mackie said.
   When it was discovered, however, a veterinarian decided it had to
be killed because of the rabies risk.
   ``The risk was slight, but rabies is endemic in the United States
and the import of cats and dogs is strictly controlled because of
it,'' Mackie said.
   The factory organized a collection to keep the cat in quarantine
for the required six months, but the vet declared the cat was in too
poor a condition to survive the quarantine period and he killed it
painlessly, Mackie said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
