<FIRST>r w PM-HowardProtest 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 03-07 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Howard Protest, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Howard Students Continue Atwater Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 5 grafs new with Bush comments; picks up 3rd graf pvs, From
as few.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today praised the naming of
Republican National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater to the Howard
University board of trustees as students continued to occupy the
administration building in protest.
   The students said they would stay until Atwater, who was Bush's
campaign manager, is removed from the board. Classes were suspended
today due to snow and freezing rain.
   Bush was asked if the students at the largely black campus, who
question Atwater's commitment to black concerns, had a legitimate
complaint.
   ``No. I think it's a good thing he's on the board ... I think
that'll work out just fine,'' Bush said at a news conference.
   No arrests have been made in the latest round of a protest that
began late last week. On Friday, students disrupted the university's
annual charter day convocation and prevented entertainer Bill Cosby
from giving the main address.
   From as few as 250 to more than 1,000 students were occupying the
Mordecai Wyatt Johnson Administration building after the takeover
began Monday morning, according to varying reports. Reporters were
not allowed inside.
   Michael Lewis, a junior who is serving as a spokesman for the
protesters, said in a statement that Atwater is ``regarded by
students to be opposed to the black agenda.''
   The university refused to comment last night on the students'
actions or on what steps might be taken.
   A group of students met with Howard University President James E.
Cheek and Board of Trustees Chairman John E. Jacob on Saturday to
discuss a list of demands.
   On Sunday, Atwater met with a group of students in an attempt to
allay their concerns, according to an Atwater spokeswoman. She said
he was unavailable for interviews, but he remained committed to his
seat on the Howard board.
   Although some professors and students have praised the
appointment as an intelligent move, others have attacked it as poor
symbolism.
   Some of Atwater's critics point to his use of the furlough of
convicted criminal Willie Horton to criticize the judgment of
Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
nominee, during George Bush's campaign last year.
   ``He masterminded use of the Willie Horton issue to contribute to
the rising anti-black sentiment of the American people,'' Lewis
said, during an earlier interview. ``And we feel that facilitated
the election of former (Ku Klux) Klansman David Duke to the
Louisiana state Legislature.''
   Aside from the removal of Atwater, students are demanding a more
``Afro-centric'' curriculum, a better financial aid processing
system and improved campus security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Raisa     03-07 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Raisa,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tass Gives Rare Coverage to Speech by Raisa Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet media gave Raisa Gorbachev some rare
coverage Tuesday, carrying a report on the Kremlin first lady's
comments on her husband's reforms and how the world's women have
improved prospects for peace.
   ``If people currently are more confident of a peaceful future, we
know that much of the credit goes to women actively working on all
continents for friendship, cooperation and profound mutual
understanding of nations,'' Mrs. Gorbachev said at a reception she
gave Monday in honor of International Women's Day, a Soviet holiday
that will be celebrated Wednesday.
   Her remarks were reported by Tass, the official Soviet news
agency.
   Although Mrs. Gorbachev is shown frequently on Soviet state-run
television and has been interviewed by Western reporters, her views
are rarely reported in Soviet media or heard by her fellow citizens.
   It was unusual for Tass to cover her reception for wives of
ambassadors and other diplomats in Moscow, wives of members of the
ruling Communist Party Politburo and Soviet women in various fields.
   Mrs. Gorbachev, who captures world attention on frequent trips
abroad with her husband, arouses contrary passions in Soviets.
   Some are curious about the dashing, 57-year-old woman who has
changed the role of the Soviet leader's wife into something more
resembling that of the wives of U.S. presidents.
   Until Mikhail S. Gorbachev to power four years ago, the spouses
of Kremlin figures kept a low, often invisible profile, with the
exception of Russian revolutionary Nadezhda Krupskaya, the wife of
Vladimir I. Lenin, who was a member of the party's policy-making
Central Committee.
   Many Soviets look askance at Mrs. Gorbachev, whose wardrobe is
large and glamorous by Soviet standards. Others grumble that the
former teacher of Marxist-Leninist philosophy is too involved in her
husband's work.
   Mrs. Gorbachev's recepition gave her an opportunity to share her
opinions on both domestic and international affairs.
   ``Soviet people are putting into practice plans of revolutionary
restructuring. We are connecting to it the destiny of our country,
of our nation,'' Mrs. Gorbachev said in a reference to her husband's
reforms. ``We want our public life in all aspects _ socio-economic,
political, moral, ecological, and in the sphere of human rights and
freedoms _ to be worthy of a human being.
   ``By transforming and renewing our society on a socialist basis,
on the principles of humanism and democracy, we are making our
country more open for all the nations of the world,'' she said.
   Mrs. Gorbachev greeted her guests individually and gave each of
them a bouquet, said Rebecca Matlock, the wife of U.S. ambassador
Jack Matlock.
   ``She's a very attractive, intelligent and vocal woman. If they
let her speak more often, everyone would benefit,'' Mrs. Matlock
said in an interview with The Associated Press.
   ``I hope with the example of Nancy Reagan coming here and the
television coverage she received here will make it acceptible for
the spouses of leaders to think their own thoughts and express
them,'' Mrs. Matlock said.
   Mrs. Matlock, who was referring to Mrs. Reagan's visit during the
Moscow summit meeting last summer, was one of several hundred guests
at the reception.
   The Gorbachevs later attended a celebration held in Moscow's
Bolshoi Theater to mark International Women's Day. The ceremonies,
broadcast on TV, showed Mrs. Gorbachev returning to the more
traditional protocol role of the Soviet leader's wife.
   Gorbachev sat on the dais with other Politburo members and
dignitaries, while his wife was in the audience.
   In a dispatch showing the limited political clout of women in
Soviet society, Tass also reported Tuesday that of 2,901 candidates
running to represent territorial districts in a new national
assembly, only 17 percent are women.
   Voters nationwide on March 26 will choose 1,500 deputies for the
Council of People's Deputies, a new body that will elect the Soviet
president and parliament. Organizations such as the Communist Party
and trade unions are directly electing deputies to fill 750 other
seats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
