<FIRST>u w PM-Tower 4thLd-Writethru a0572 03-07 1112</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0572,1,070</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Pentagon People Will Keep Eye on Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with further detail on Nunn provbe; picks up
at pvs 6th graf, Meanwhile today, and edits below to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that 25,000 Pentagon
employees will provide a ``fail-safe guarantee'' that John Tower
abides by his vow to abstain from drinking if he is confirmed as
secretary of defense.
   As Bush underlined his support for his nominee, Senate
Republicans accused Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., of improperly reopening
the investigation into the former Texas senator's personal fitness
to serve.
   Nunn, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, said he
had dispatched investigators from the Senate Governmental Affairs
investigations subcommittee that he also heads to Dallas to probe
new allegations against Tower. He said he did so because he
understood the FBI had ended its own work on the case and was ``out
of business.''
   As the Senate opened its fourth day of debate on the nomination,
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said he found it ``very
troubling'' that Nunn had acted on his own to reopen the Tower
investigation using Senate employees.
   ``Why are we investigating Senator Tower?'' Dole asked. ``Isn't
the FBI record adequate? When does this investigation stop?
   Nunn later told Dole that there were ``three or four new
allegations'' and said he had advised Republicans on the
investigations panel before acting.
   He said he had been told the FBI was no longer on the case so
forwarding the allegations to the bureau would have been ``an
exercise in futility.''
   ``There was no other way to check them,'' Nunn said, adding that
iot would satisfy him if the FBI took over.
   Republicans, including Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said they found
Nunn's action ``questionable'' and ``inappropriate.''
   Meanwhile today, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said that
while some other Democrats may follow the lead of Sen. Howell
Heflin, D-Ala., and announce support for Tower, there are not enough
votes to confirm the nominee.
   Mitchell said also that while some Republicans are talking of
prolonging the debate through Easter, he wants a vote soon,
``certainly this week.''
   Commenting in the aftermath of Heflin's decision to support
Tower, Mitchell, D-Maine, said it is entirely possible some other
Democrats may follow the senator's lead.
   ``I feel that when the vote is taken the nomination will be
rejected,'' Mitchell said. ``I do not believe there are sufficient
votes to result in the confirmation of Senator Tower.''
   Bush, commenting at an impromptu news conference at the White
House this morning, said: ``John Tower has said he'll never touch
another drop of liquor and he'll have 25,000 people at the Pentagon
making sure he keeps his word. I would say we have a fail-safe
guarantee.''
   Heflin's decision on Monday heartened Tower's Republican leaders,
who said they may yet ask the Senate to let the nominee defend his
battered reputation from the floor of the chamber itself.
   Mitchell told reporters today he is prepared to comment on that
possibility but will do so only if the request is actually made.
   Some senators who are not part of the GOP leadership have said
the debate may be extended through Easter. Mitchell said he will
oppose such a lengthy delay.
   ``It is my hope it can be concluded soon and certainly this
week,'' he said.
   Heflin said Monday that the FBI had not built a persuasive case
against Tower. He said he is convinced the nominee would not break
his pledge never to drink again if confirmed as the nation's defense
chief. He said Tower is qualified for the job by reason of
background and expertise in military affairs.
   But the encouragement GOP leaders drew from Heflin's announcement
was dampened when another Southern Democrat _ Sen. David Pryor of
Arkansas _ said he would vote ``no.''
   ``I feel this man is going to create rather than solve
problems,'' Pryor said.
   Pryor cited the former Texas senator's lucrative consulting ties
with leading defense contractors after leaving government service as
a U.S. arms negotiator and as chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
   Heflin and Pryor announced their decisions shortly after
President Bush called on Democrats to ``put aside partisanship'' and
support the nominee, basing their decisions on their personal
knowledge of Tower's 24-year Senate career rather than ``rumor and
innuendo.''
   Heflin is a former chief justice of the Alabama Supreme Court and
chairman of the Senate Ethics Committee. Republicans said that if
someone of Heflin's background is unconvinced by allegations against
Tower in the massive FBI report, other Democrats might be persuaded
to follow his lead.
   The most recent Associated Press survey found 47 Democrats and
one Republican _ Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D. _ either solidly
opposed or leaning against confirmation. Forty Republicans and one
Democrat were either leaning for or supporting confirmation.
   ``We have a better chance, but it's still an uphill fight,'' said
Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, after Heflin's announcement. ``We're
looking for more good men.''
   Republican leaders met with White House Chief of Staff John
Sununu and said later that the possibility of asking the Senate to
permit Tower to come to the Senate floor to answer questions remains
an option.
   Such a dramatic appearance _ if approved _ would be unique in the
Senate's 200 years of experience in judging candidates for Cabinet
positions.
   It would give Tower the chance to rebut allegations that he has
drinking problems, has indulged in indiscreet behavior toward women
and has opened the appearance of possible conflict of interest in
his relations with the defense industry.
   In making his announcement, Heflin said the president and the
American people would see to it Tower kept his word not to drink if
confirmed as secretary of defense.
   ``John Tower _ if confirmed _ will live in a glass bowl,'' Heflin
said ``No one will be more closely watched. ... His most persistent
watchdog will be the American people.
   ``I'm willing to rely on his pledge and give him a chance to
prove himself,'' Heflin said. ``Giving one a chance to redeem
himself or herself is one of the great redeeming factors of the
American way of life.''
   In addition to Heflin, the Bush administration has courted Sen.
Bennett Johnston, D-La., who has labeled the FBI report on Tower as
``unreliable.''
   Johnston says he has not made a decision even though he believes
``there needs to be more fairness put into this process.''
   Republicans said they are also looking at a short list of other
possible Democratic converts, including Sens. Chris Dodd, D-Conn.;
Charles Robb, D-Va.; Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas; and Claiborne Pell,
D-R.I.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
