<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     03-07 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milan Promises a Warm Winter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When next winter rolls around, no woman need
worry that she will be left out in the cold.
   Italian designers showing their fall-winter 1989-90 collections
here this week devote much of their creative talent to coats, from
the pratical polo to dramatic capes and elegant dusters.
   The cut is as generous as it is cozy. Ample sleeves, huge shawl
collars, and loosely pleated backs contribute to create a soft
flowing effect. Most often belted at the waist, these outer
coverings are either cropped at the hip, or so long they can double
as street sweepers.
   The favorite fabric is wool, but leather and shearling also play
heavily in the collections, not to mention fur, from fake to
extravagant mink.
   Colors are warm fall shades ranging from forest greens, to
vineyard reds and purples, to beiges and browns.
   The unpractical but dramatically stylish cape, often hooded like
a medieval friar's, also makes a comeback.
   Ferragamo and Genny, who showed Tuesday, midway through the
fashion week, count heavily on the coat for winter warmth.
   Ferragamo _ the Florentine family known for its town and country
chic and its shoes _ presented a chocolate colored duster with super
wide sleeves, tied at the waist, and a series of chic car coats with
bright gold buttons.
   On the whole, the Ferragamo collection was very smart and sporty,
with trim pants suits in black and white checkered patterns, and
patchwork leather blazers and knee-length skirts for daytime, and
sophisticated long sleeved silk jersey gowns, buttoned or unbuttoned
at the back with gold buttons for evening.
   Genny, designed by Versace but more subdued than his presentation
of micro miniskirts during his own collection Sunday night,
presented the most opulent coat wear seen thus far on the Milan
runway, in his series of lavish mink wraps.
   These unabashedly expensive creations, made up no doubt of
hundreds of skins to create the huge collar, ample sleeve and wide
swirling hemline, go against the current conservationist trend for
imitation furs in elegant styles, favored among others by Armani
(Emporio) and Moschino.
   The Genny collection was snappy and young with a wide variety of
pants ranging from man-tailored to tight-fitting jodhpurs, and
short-cropped jackets. Skirts were a mere four inches above the
knee, a conservative length for flamboyant Versace, but still had
his trademark tight derriere.
   Evening at Genny's is basically black, enriched by traditional
pearl accessories, or an enticing rhinestone embroidered bustier
peering out of a slinky chiffon gown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Immigration-Nelson     03-07 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigration-Nelson,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Said Planning to Replace Nelson at Immigration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will replace Alan C.
Nelson as head of the Immigration and Naturalization Service, an
administration source said Tuesday.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, who recently received a
department audit that criticized management and operations of INS,
is searching for someone to take over the agency, said the source,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The source confirmed a report in Tuesday's editions of the Los
Angeles Times that Nelson would be not be kept as INS commissioner
in the Bush administration.
   It has been long presumed by department watchers that Nelson,
along with most other political officeholders in the Justice
Department, would be replaced.
   Nelson, a San Francisco lawyer close to former Attorney General
Edwin Meese III, became INS commissioner in 1982.
   He was criticized by immigrant rights advocates for being slow to
implement the provisions of the 1986 immigration reform law, which
provided for massive amnesty for illegal aliens.
   INS became embroiled in a number of lawsuits charging that it was
improperly making it difficult for illegal aliens to obtain legal
status under the new law.
   The Justice Department audit, completed two weeks ago, cited INS
for its failure to conduct background checks on many applicants for
citizenship and found that 23,000 valuable naturalization
certificates had been lost by the agency's Miami regional office.
   The special audit, conducted at Thornburgh's request by the
Justice Department's management division, raised ``serious questions
which are being reviewed now at the highest levels of the
department,'' spokesman David Runkel said last week.
   Besides losing naturalization certifications, which had a street
value of up to $115 million, INS was cited in the audit for failing
to take action two years after investigators had discovered that
61,500 naturalized citizens had not surrendered their permanent
resident alien cards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-NewsConference 3rdLd-Writethru a0567 03-07 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-News Conference, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0567,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Firm In Opposition to Government Intervention in Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf with Wright reax, editing pvs 3rd graf;
subs pvs 3th graf, Bush said, to delete reference to Kennedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today urged pilots threatening a
sympathy slowdown in support of the Eastern Airlines strike not to
``make the innocent traveling public a pawn in this dispute,'' and
stood by his opposition to government intervention to stop the
walkout.
   He said that if striking machinists try to shut down rail service
he will ask Congress to ban such secondary boycotts.
   House Speaker Jim Wright responded that Bush's refusal to halt
the strike by appointing an investigative panel ``would be
unprecedented,'' noting that over the past half-century 33 such
boards have been named in transportation disputes.
   Bush said once again that he is determined to press his
nomination of John G. Tower to be secretary of defense to a showdown
vote in the Senate because ``I want him and I believe he is the best
man for the job.''
   Bush reminded a White House press conference that Tower has
pledged not to touch a drop of liquor if he gets the defense job,
and ``you'll have 25,000 people in the Pentagon making sure that's
true.''
   The president said that his backing of Tower against Democratic
opposition in the Senate ``isn't iron-willed stubbornness, it's a
question of fundamental principle here.''
   Bush quickly added the news conference to his schedule this
morning after an ice and snow storm forced cancellation of a
presidential trip to Lancaster, Pa., and Wilmington, Del.
   The president gave a preliminary welcome to the Soviet proposal,
made Monday at an East-West conference in Vienna, for a reduction in
conventional weapons and military personnel in Europe. The proposal
was outlined by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``It looks to me he is moving toward the oft-stated public
position of NATO in this regard, and that is good,'' Bush said, but
cautioned he had not yet seen Secretary of State James A. Baker
III's cabled report on the conference of foreign ministers from NATO
countries and Warsaw Pact nations.
   Bush was asked if he would pursue ``linkage'' in his relations
with the Soviet Union.
   He said issues are related, and if the Soviets cooperate with the
United States in one area, it will respond in another area. ``So
there is linkage,'' he said.
   For example, the president said he would welcome any reduction in
Soviet military aid to pro-communist forces in Central America or an
increase in the number of Soviet Jews permitted to emigrate to the
West, he will welcome that.
   ``When something good happens, give them credit,'' Bush said.
``There clearly has got to be some linkage.''
   Bush said the Tower debate has not immobilized his
administration, as some critics are saying, countering simply that
they are wrong.
   He said the administration is not adrift, ``we're on track.''
   ``I will not be stampeded by some talk that we have not come up
with bold, new foreign policy proposals in 45 days,'' Bush said.
   The president also defended his chief of staff, saying John
Sununu, the former New Hampshire governor, knows his way around
Washington and is doing his job well. Bush said he has total
confidence in Sununu.
   On other issues, he said:
   _There is not much question that the Contra rebels in Nicaragua
will need additional humanitarian aid. ``We simply cannot and I will
not leave the Contras out there with no humanitarian aid at all,''
he said.
   _He is willing to be flexible on action to limit sales of
automatic and semi-automatic weapons, but the issue is a complicated
one. ``It isn't as easy as it seems for those who are understandably
crying out to do something,,' he said.
   _He did raise the issue of human rights in China during his visit
to Beijing, but did so privately. Bush was criticized because the
topic was not on his announced agenda. But he said it was better
handled quietly and ``I confidently expect Jim Baker will continue
to raise it.''
</TEXT>
