<SECOND>PM-People-Kitty Dukakis,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis Returns Home From Treatment Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' wife waved at reporters
and held her husband tightly when she arrived home today after
spending a month in an alcohol treatment program.
   Emerging from a car driven by her father, Harry Ellis Dickson,
Kitty Dukakis smiled broadly. ``Doesn't she look terrific,'' said
the governor, his arm around her.
   Asked what was the best part of returning home, Mrs. Dukakis
said, ``Being with my husband.'' Without missing a beat, her husband
added, ``Being with my wife.''
   Mrs. Dukakis, 52, had been in Edgehill Newport, an intensive
residential facility in Rhode Island, since Feb. 5. She entered the
facility after several bouts of excessive drinking at home following
her husband's failed presidential bid.
   Following the family's wishes, the governor's staff was publicly
silent about Mrs. Dukakis' condition and her treatment. The
governor's press office has been bombarded with inquiries and
interview requests, but no plans have been made for Mrs. Dukakis to
discuss her experience.
   Mrs. Dukakis was driven home by the governor and by her father.
On the way home, she visited with her 5-week-old granddaughter.
   ``Kitty and I will never be able to thank personally the
thousands of people in Massachusetts and from throughout the country
who have written or called with kind words of encouragement and love
and support for her during her treatment,'' Dukakis said.
   A statement by his office said Mrs. Dukakis expects ``soon to
resume a full and active schedule'' but provided no details.
   One senior Dukakis administration official said he had no reason
to believe the treatment was not a success.
   ``Every indication from the governor's attitude and what he has
had to say is that it has been successful and that Kitty is going to
resume an active, independently fulfilling schedule, following up
all the plans she had been making before,'' said the source who
refused to be identified.
   ``Our feeling is it is a private matter,'' James Dorsey, the
governor's press secretary, said. But he added, ``There may come a
time when the governor and his wife decide to make it not a private
matter.''
</TEXT>
