<FIRST>r i AM-US-Mideast     03-07 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Doesn't See PLO Raids as Terrorism; Bush Wants Arafat to Speak
Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has
concluded that attacks by PLO guerrillas against Israelis in
southern Lebanon were not acts of terrorism requiring a break-off of
U.S. talks with Yasser Arafat's organization.
   A senior State Department official, aboard Baker's plane on the
way home from Vienna, said Tuesday concerning what should be labeled
terrorism, ``We make a mistake if we define that too closely.''
   In Washington, President Bush was asked at his news conference
whether Arafat, in refusing to criticize the raids, was backing down
on his condemnation of terrorism.
   ``I hope not, and I'd like to see him forthrightly condemn any
terror that might be perpetrated by the Palestinians,'' Bush
answered. ``I stop short of saying he's condoning it or that he is
furthering it; I'm not saying that. But I'd like to see him speak
out. It would do wonders, it would be very good for a future
dialogue.''
   When the questioner asked if Arafat was jeopardizing the current
dialogue, Bush replied, ``To the degree terroristic acts are
condoned, it doesn't help the dialogue.''
   Arafat's renunciation of terrorism and recognition of Israel's
right to exist prompted the United States last December to open
talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Since then PLO guerrillas have conducted at least three raids
against Israeli forces _ raids the Israeli government contends were
aimed at infiltrating Israel itself.
   Senior U.S. officials, including then-Assistant Secretary of
State Richard W. Murphy, had said at the onset of the dialogue that
it would be suspended if terrorism recurred.
   Baker subsequently warned the PLO the attacks could hurt the
talks and U.S. efforts to resolve the Arab-Israeli conflict. Last
Friday the State Department questioned Arafat's commitment and
whether he wanted to control PLO factions that carried out the raids.
   ``If the PLO leadership cannot or will not exercise such control,
it raises questions regarding the commitments undertaken in the name
of the PLO, indeed questions about the PLO's ability to carry out
their commitment,'' spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   The strong statement appeared to suggest the Bush administration
was reconsidering the dialogue.
   But as Baker flew home from Vienna, where he had met with Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, that impression dissolved.
   Baker's view ``is that the dialogue should continue,'' the
official said. ``It is important.''
   For Baker , he said, ``the real test is terrorism.'' We make a
mistake if we define that too closely.''
   The official recalled the late Supreme Court Justice Potter
Stewart's observation that he could not define pornography but would
know it when he saw it. Baker's view on terrorism was described to
reporters as similar to Stewart's on pornography.
   For instance, the official said, Baker considers the attack on
the U.S. Marine headquarters near Beirut in October 1983, in which
241 Marines and sailors were killed, as an act of terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
