<FIRST>r w AM-Lubbock-Peoria     03-07 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lubbock-Peoria,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Disarray, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Will It Play in Lubbock? ^By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lubbock may be George Bush's Peoria.
   He cited a fan from the Texas city on Tuesday in defending the
beginning of his administration, which some critics contend is
getting off to a slow start.
   Bush told a White House news conference that he had ``talked to a
fellow from Lubbock, Texas, the other day. ... And he said: `All the
people in Lubbock think things are going just great.'''
   The reference to populatiry in a smaller city in the nation's
midsection evoked memories of the phrase ``Will it play in Peoria?''
which became popular in the Nixon administration.
   If Lubbock is to replace Peoria as the standard for middle
American acceptance, let's see how the two compare, based on
statistics reported in the Census Bureau's ``County and City Data
Book: 1988.''
   Lubbock is physically bigger, with 106.3 square miles of land
compared to just 42.2 square miles in Peoria. Lubbock has more
people too, outnumbering its Illinois companion 186,400 to 110,290.
   But Peoria is a bit more crowded, at 2,614 people per square mile
compared to 1,754 in Lubbock.
   The two cities are diverging in size.
   From 1980 to 1986, the Sun Belt city of Lubbock saw its
population grow 7.2 percent. Over the same time, Peoria lost 11.2
percent of its residents.
   In racial breakdown, the cities are somewhat similar. Peoria has
a population that is 81 percent white and 17 percent black, while
Lubbock is 81 percent white and nearly 19 percent black. Peoria has
about 1 percent Asians to help make up the discrepancy.
   On the other hand, 19 percent of Lubbock's residents are
Hispanic, while this group makes up only 1.4 percent of the people
in Peoria. Hispanics can be of any race.
   Peoria is older, with 12.3 percent of its people aged 65 and
over, compared to 7.8 percent in Lubbock.
   Lubbock's birth rate is 20.1 births per 1,000 people, compared to
16.5 for Peoria, while the death rate is 9.8 per 1,000 in Peoria and
6.6 for Lubbock.
   Peoria has a narrow lead in high school graduates, 69.6 percent
of its residents compared to 69.3 percent in Lubbock. On the other
hand, Lubbock counts 22.4 percent of its people with four years of
college, compared to 16.5 percent in Peoria.
   Per capita income in Peoria in 1985 was $11,140, compared to
$10,452 for Lubbock, with 12.4 percent of the people in the Illinois
metropolis below the poverty level compared to 14.4 percent in the
Texas city.
   Peoria, in the midwestern farm belt, is twice as wet as the
semiarid high plains city in Texas. Rain averages nearly 35 inches
annually in Peoria but only 17.7 inches in Lubbock.
   Peoria is also colder, with an average January low reading of
13.3 degrees Fahrenheit, compared to a low of 24.3 degrees for
Lubbock.
   But summers are hotter in Texas, with July's high averaging 91.0
degrees for Lubbock and 85.5 degrees for Peoria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0098 </DOCNO>
