<HEAD>AM-People</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Casino owner Bob Stupak says he can beat
real estate mogul Donald Trump at his own game, and the flamboyant
bettor has wagered $1 million that he will prevail in a one-on-one
match of TRUMP, The Game.
   But Trump, whose casinos are in Atlantic City, N.J., doesn't want
to play.
   ``It's always possible to lose, even for someone who's used to
winning,'' he said.
   The owner of Bob Stupak's Vegas World hotel and casino made his
challenge in full-page ads Tuesday in the New York Post and The
Atlantic City (N.J.) Press.
   Trump said that since revenues from the board game go to charity,
he said, ``it would be foolish to possibly lose $1 million.''
   ``I'm not asking for profits of the game,'' Stupak responded. He
added, ``I can't believe with Trump's billions he can't spare a
million.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kent McCord and Martin Milner, the TV
crimefighting duo of ``Adam 12,'' are planning to reunite behind the
badge, but this time they won't be in blue, or in Los Angeles.
   The Nashville Network and NAC Productions have agreed to develop
a two-hour detective movie starring McCord and Milner under the
working title ``Nashville Beat.'' The movie is scheduled for
broadcast on the cable channel late this year.
   McCord and Milner, who starred as patrol officers in the popular
1960s series, are to fight crime on location in Nashville armed with
a script based on real cases, said Randa Handler, a publicist for
the project.
   Milner is to portray an old-fashioned chief of detectives who
recruits McCord, a hip undercover cop from Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Cronkite thinks journalists may be
better than ever, but the profession is endangered by tabloid-style
TV news programs.
   ``I am concerned about the garbage that is masquerading as
television these days,'' Cronkite said Monday. ``Most of it is real
scandal-tabloid journalism ... absolutely, totally useless stuff.''
   But, Cronkite said, ``We have a more responsible press today in
this country than we've ever had.''
   He said reporters are much more enterprising and conscientious
than in the mid-1940s and several years after, when journalists
practiced ``reporting by handout.''
   Cronkite, who lives in New York, made his remarks during a news
conference to pitch a local water pollution documentary he narrated.
He signed off for the last time as anchor of ``The CBS Evening
News'' eight years ago Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch says in a new book that his
mother underwent illegal abortions because of Depression-era poverty
and tried to induce a miscarriage while pregnant with his sister.
   In ``His Eminence and Hizzoner,'' written with Cardinal John
O'Connor, Koch describes his transformation from a Greenwich Village
liberal to a man who shares views with many conservatives.
   Koch says that a few years before his mother, Joyce Koch, died in
1961, ``she told me that during her lifetime she'd had a number of
abortions. ... Her reasons were economic.''
   When pregnant with Koch's younger sister, Pat, his mother ``tried
to induce a miscarriage by jumping off chairs and trunks. It didn't
work,'' Koch says. ``When she finally accepted that the child was
going to be born, she worried that she might have injured the fetus.
   ``Personally, I don't think abortion on demand is a good idea,''
Koch writes. Nevertheless, Koch has consistently opposed outlawing
abortion.
   The book, published by William Morrow &amp; Co., goes on sale next
week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amin Gemayel, former president of
Lebanon, will be exploring his country's role in the Middle East
peace process during a fellowship at Harvard University's Center for
International Affairs.
   Gemayel is expected to be at Harvard through the remainder of
this semester and possibly through next fall's semester, said Leslie
H. Brown, director of the center's fellows program.
   He will participate in seminars with the 25 other fellows at the
center and will supervise a translation from French to English of
his political memoirs, ``The Offense and the Pardon,'' The Boston
Globe said Tuesday.
   Gemayel, 47, became president of Lebanon in 1982 after his
brother, Bashir, was assassinated in a bomb attack by Moslem
terrorists. He resigned the presidency last year under a
constitutional deadline.
   The Globe said he plans to return to Beirut after completing his
fellowship.
