<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Andrews     03-07 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Andrews,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Character Actor Specialized in Army Roles, Had `Dynasty' Cameo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry Andrews, a craggy, jut-jawed character actor
who specialized in military roles, has died at the age of 77.
   Andrews died in his sleep Monday night at his home in the
southern village of Salehurst, said his agent, Lawrence Evans.
   Andrews made his stage debut at age 21 and had many Shakespearean
roles, including Horatio in ``Hamlet'' in New York in 1936. He
served as an artilleryman in World War II and made his first movie
in 1952, opposite Alan Ladd in ``The Red Beret.''
   He once said he was offered a Hollywood contract in his younger
days, but ``they wanted me to have my ears pinned back like Clark
Gable and the gap filled in between my front teeth. I wouldn't have
minded that, but then they said the name was too plain and would
have to go, and a bit of chin. So I said no.''
   Instead, he became a stalwart of postwar British cinema, most
memorably as the tough warden of a British army prison opposite Sean
Connery in the 1965 film ``The Hill.''
   Andrews' towering physique and growling voice made him a natural
for the part of a general in ``The Battle of Britain'' in 1969, but
he also showed a comic flair as the campy older man in 1970's
``Entertaining Mr. Sloane.''
   In 1985, he was in Hollywood appearing in a play when he was
asked to play a single-episode deathbed scene as Blake Carrington's
long-lost father in ``Dynasty.''
   Andrews told the Daily Mail he had never been a TV watcher, and
``I was startled when the Americans in my play kept saying to me,
`Gosh, an episode of `Dynasty.' What an accolade!'''
   Actress Sylvia Syms, who starred with Andrews in the 1958 war
movie ``Ice Cold in Alex,'' remembered him as ``the gentle giant.''
   ``He was a perfect gentleman and a lovely, soft-spoken man... I
can't think of anything nasty to say about him, except that he had
bony knees.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
