<FIRST>r a AM-EasternShuttle     03-07 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Shuttle,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Struggles to Restore Shuttle from Pan Am Incursion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines struggled to restore its
Northeast shuttle Tuesday, throwing its strike-diminished work force
into an intense battle with competitor Pan Am for the lucrative line.
   ``Fly Us With No Reservations,'' Eastern declared in full-page
newspaper advertisements, pledging routine service between
Washington, New York and Boston. ``Our No. 1 priority is to keep the
shuttle flying.''
   But ridership was low at Eastern, while Pan Am, moving
aggressively to capture Eastern regulars, reported strong shuttle
business. Since the strike Saturday, Pan Am has doubled its
rush-hour service, added a bigger airplane and aggressively promoted
its frequent-flier program to shuttle passengers.
   ``We don't look at this as extra capacity for a few days. We look
at it as an opportunity to win long-term allegiance,'' said Pan Am
spokesman Jeff Kriendler. ``We are trying to take advantage of the
special opportunity.''
   ``It's fair,'' said Tim Cook, a spokesman for Eastern, which is
selling its shuttle to developer Donald Trump. If the tables were
turned, he said, ``We'd be doing the same thing.''
   Eastern, which has operated its shuttle for 27 years, held just
over half the business before the strike, for a profit of about $30
million last year. The rest _ roughly 5,000 passengers each weekday
_ had been gradually wrested away by Pan Am since it opened its
shuttle in 1986.
   Cook said Eastern operated 60 percent of its shuttle flights
Monday _ the others canceled by snow, not strikers _ and hoped to
fly them all Tuesday, despite continued bad weather. Crews were
mainly management employees.
   Patronage was low. A source at Eastern, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said it had been averaging 15 or 20 passengers per
shuttle flight. Ronnet Anderson, a New Yorker on the 9 a.m. shuttle
from Washington, said it carried just four passengers.
   ``A lot of people went over to Pan Am just to avoid the hassle,''
Cook conceded. ``But we're routine today and expect to be routine
from here on out.''
   The problem may not be Eastern's for long, with a pending $365
million sale to Trump. Some Wall Street analysts suggested the
strike, if it led to bankruptcy, could endanger the sale; others
said Trump will be getting a somewhat tarnished property.
   ``The hardest thing in any marketing business is to get somebody
to try your product,'' said Louis Marckesano, airline analyst at the
Philadelphia brokerage house Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. ``If Pan
Am indeed is able to provide a good product, there's a good chance
they'll be able to keep at least some of the additional traffic
they've taken from Eastern.''
   But Bruce Nobles, president of Trump Shuttle Inc., said he was
``not the least bit worried.''
   ``I think when we start operating it's going to be big news,''
Nobles said. ``I think the Trump name is a very powerful name. We
are not worried about whether we're starting from one market share
or another market share.''
   Pan Am _ which has gone so far as to laminate shuttle travelers'
business cards into free luggage tags at its terminals this week _
had another view.
   ``This just gives us a golden opportunity to get those Eastern
diehard passengers,'' said Perette Ross, shuttle marketing director
for Pan Am. ``Hopefully they'll become loyalists to the Pan Am
shuttle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
