<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     03-07 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills Two; Jumblatt blames Christians</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb hidden in a car exploded during the
Tuesday morning rush hour near the American University hospital in
Moslem west Beirut, killing two women and wounding 21, police said.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt blamed the bomb on Gen. Michel
Aoun's Christian Cabinet, charging its was part of the Lebanese
leader's efforts to neutralize the war-torn nation's private armies.
   ``I looked out of the window and saw fire blazing in several
cars, a corpse in the middle of the street and people running in all
directions,'' said a man who watched the blast form a nearby
building. He refused to give his name.
   The fourth car bomb in Lebanon this year was placed in a yellow
Fiat that exploded in front of a fruit and vegetable stall off the
main Hamra commercial thoroughfare.
   A woman maneuvering to park her car near the yellow Fiat was
killed when the bomb went off, a police spokesman said. The blast
threw her body from the car.
   He said the second woman, a passer-by, suffered serious head
wounds and died later in the hospital.
   The bomb triggered fires in nine cars parked near the stall and
shattered windows in surrounding buildings.
   Panicking motorists caused several accidents as the tried to flee
the scene, said a woman who identified herself only as a telephone
operator from the nearby Cavalier Hotel.
   Ambulances were slowed by rush-hour traffic, the police spokesman
said.
   Accountant Jamal Hamoud said he watched as ``gunmen fired their
rifles in the air to make way for the ambulances.''
   Ambulances evacuated only three of the wounded.
   ``Civilians carried most of the casualties on their backs to the
American University hospital,'' a few hundred yards away, the police
spokesman said.
   Most of those injured suffered minor cuts from glass shards, he
said.
   Jumblatt, whose Progressive Socialist Party militia is allied
with the Syrians who police west Beirut, said the bomb was a warning
from Aoun.
   ``Those who are trying to encircle us, today sent us a
booby-trapped message,'' Jumblatt claimed.
   He was referring to efforts by Aoun's helicopter gunships and
gunboats to prevent merchant ships from docking at illegal port
facilities run by his and other militias along Lebanon's coastline.
   The air-and-sea patrols started Monday, ignoring rocket fire by
Jumblatt's militia based near Jiye port, south of Beirut.
   Aoun's aim to choke off the main revenues of private armies has
provoked objections from Syrian-backed Moslem leaders who consider
it an attempt to restrict their operations.
   Moslems refuse to recognize Aoun's military Cabinet, appointed by
outgoing President Amin Gemayel in September after parliament failed
to elect his successor. They pledge allegiance to the Moslem Cabinet
of Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who governed under Gemayel.
   By police count, 11 people were killed and 47 wounded in three
January car bombings.
   Twenty car bombs exploded in 1988, killing 116 people and
wounding 488.
</TEXT>
