<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Budget     03-07 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Budget,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Justices Plead for Budget Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Tuesday asked Congress for
a budget increase of $1.4 million to ease what one justice said is
such a severe money pinch the court is having trouble paying for
typewriter repairs.
   ``We're hurting,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor told a House
Appropriations subcommittee. ``We have a real strain on our budget.
We can't keep our typewriters operating.''
   The court is asking for $17.3 million for the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1, an increase of a little more than $1.4 million
over the current budget.
   Rep. Joseph D. Early, D-Mass., gave a mixed reception to O'Connor
and Justice Antonin Scalia, who also spoke in support of the budget
request.
   ``I'm really not that sympathetic,'' he said. ``We can't be all
things to all people.''
   But later Early expressed support and urged the justices to speak
out more forcefully to attract attention to the court's plight.
   ``It's ludicrous to treat you the same way as anyone else,'' he
said. ``We've got to spend more money.''
   ``I don't know waht you should be doing, all threatening to
resign or something,'' Early said.
   Adding that the entire federal court system needs more money, he
said, ``There's not one federal judge who couldn't leave and
increase his salary by 20 to 25 percent.''
   Underscoring the point, O'Connor said she knew of one former
clerk to a Supreme Court justice who recently left for private law
practice and ``is earning more than the justices.''
   The annual salary of a Supreme Court justice is $110,000.
   Included in the court's budget request are $110,000 for library
shelves and $160,000 to improve its computer system.
   O'Connor said 18 staff positions at the court have not been
filled because of a hiring freeze imposed to meet budget restraints.
   ``Every (justice's) chambers and office of the court has been
affected by the hiring freeze,'' she said. It ``is having a negative
impact on the efficiency and morale of remaining employees who must
take on extra work when positions become vacant.''
   Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, the subcommittee chairman, said, ``You
shouldn't have to put up with it. We'll see what we can do.''
</TEXT>
