<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-HumanRights     03-07 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Human Rights,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's as Committed to Human Rights as Reagan Had Been</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush asserted Tuesday that he is as
committed to human rights as former President Reagan had been, even
though Bush didn't publicly focus on the issue during his recent
trip to China.
   ``I think quiet discussion is a good approach to try to effect
the human rights objectives that I feel very strongly about,'' Bush
told a White House news conference.
   The president defended his conduct in not making a big issue of
an incident in which Chinese police prevented dissident Fang Lizhi
from attending a barbecue in Beijing last week hosted by Bush.
   Fang had been on Bush's invitation list.
   ``The very invitation to that dissident that they thoroughly
disapproved of shows our public commitment to it (human rights),''
Bush said.
   Reagan raised human rights issues in each of his meetings with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and once invited a group of
Soviet dissidents to meet with him in the U.S. Embassy in Moscow.
   On a trip to China in 1984, Reagan protested angrily when Chinese
authorities censored parts of his nationally televised address,
including a portion dealing with religion.
   Still, Bush sought to draw a parallel between his own
presentation of human-rights concerns in meetings with foreign
leaders and Reagan's approach.
   ``You know, there's two schools of how you do the human rights
agenda,'' he said. ``I think that President Reagan was correct when
he raised the human rights agenda with the Soviets privately rather
than beating his breast and doing it publicly.''
   ``And I think the results have been rather penetrating, still a
long way to go with the Soviets,'' Bush said.
   During his China trip, Bush's press secretary, Marlin Fitzwater,
said that Bush had not raised the issues of human rights with
Chinese leaders _ presumably including the key issue of human rights
in Tibet, scene of recent clashes between police and rioters seeking
independence from Beijing.
   China on Tuesday imposed martial law in the Tibetan capital of
Lhasa after three days of anti-Chinese rioting.
   Bush on Tuesday said that the press secretary's statement was
true up the point that Fitzwater spoke, but that he later raised the
general issue in a private meeting with Chinese senior leader Deng
Xiaopeng.
   ``It was raised by me personally,'' he said.
   On the subject of linking economic concessions to the Soviets to
human-rights progress, including an easing of emigration
restrictions on Soviet Jews, Bush said: ``There's clearly got to be
some linkage.''
   ``When Soviets come out of Afghanistan, which happened here not
so long ago, give them credit for that. When you get some lightening
up a little bit on the question of Soviet Jews or something of that
nature, give some credit,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
