<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Bishops 1stLd-Writethru a0644 03-07 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Bishops, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0644,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Bishops Leader Expects Differences, But No Confrontation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE extraneous ``be'' in quote, add long
dash.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top U.S. Roman Catholic church official
says he expects ``points of difference'' to emerge between the
Vatican and American bishops but no confrontation in an
extraordinary meeting beginning Wednesday.
   ``There will be probably, in any free-flowing discussion, points
of difference _ points of difference that will be discussed and
faced,'' said Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis, president of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
   He didn't go into specifics, but there have been differences over
the right of Catholics to dissent from church teaching to how much
weight bishops' conferences should have.
   Thirty-five U.S. prelates gathered Tuesday in Rome on the eve of
the four-day meeting with Pope John Paul II and top Vatican
officials.
   The U.S. bishops originally had requested the meeting in 1986,
when tensions with the Vatican were high over its disciplining of
several clergy members considered too permissive on such issues as
ministering to homosexual groups and artificial birth control, which
the church bans.
   As tensions eased in recent years, the bishops considered
dropping the request. However, the pope wanted the meeting held,
according to Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro.
   In his speeches to American Catholics, the pontiff has expressed
concern about people who disagree with church teaching and practice
what Vatican officials call ``cafeteria Catholicism'' _ obeying some
doctrines and ignoring others.
   In this week's meetings, he and other Vatican officials are
expected to encourage the bishops to be ardent proponents of church
teaching in a secular society.
   Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, the West German who heads the powerful
Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, will deliver a major
address Wednesday that is expected to set the Vatican's tone for the
meeting. A Vatican source described it as a ``thought-provoking''
talk.
   Vatican officials stress the meeting won't be confrontational.
   May said the bishops hoped to bring to Rome a better
understanding of the 52 million-member American Catholic Church.
   ``There's been a lack of understanding on the part of some people
(in the Vatican),'' he said in an interview Tuesday. ``Some of these
men have not been in the United States, or not very much ... some of
them haven't been as fully conversant with our ways of doing things
in a cultural contest.''
   He said he hoped for a ``deeper understanding of separation of
church and state, a deeper understanding of the freedom of thought
in the United States ... a deeper understanding of the democratic
process that we're used to, which is not always the way things are
done in the church.''
   He added that the pope ``seems to have gotten a new vision'' of
the United States from his trips there and meetings with American
bishops last year.
   ``I think it (the meeting) will be significant in the life of the
church,'' said May. ``It will probably build a stronger sense of
unity between the Vatican and the bishops, a better understanding
and realization of how we're all try to do the same thing in
different contexts.''
   The pope has held extraordinary meetings with bishops from
Brazil, to discuss liberation theology, and bishops from Holland,
where the church was split into conservative and liberal factions
over issues such as celibacy and the role of women in the church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Baker Bjt   03-07 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker, Bjt,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Closer on Bush-Gorbachev Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III met
with the Soviet foreign minister Tuesday and agreed to visit Moscow
in May, where they will discuss prospects for a Bush-Gorbachev
summit.
   His two-hour meeting with Eduard A. Shevardnadze in Vienna took
place the day after they outlined their governments' positions at a
35-nation conference on reducing conventional military forces in
Europe. Baker's plane made a refueling stop in Shannon on the flight
home.
   Baker resisted a Soviet overture to reopen negotiations in April
or May on reducing long-range _ or strategic _ nuclear missiles. He
said the Bush administration wants to complete parallel reviews of
its arms control policy and nuclear force structure before resuming
the talks.
   Reopening the talks on long-range bombers, nuclear submarines and
missiles will be discussed during the visit to Moscow in the first
half of May, after the parallel studies are completed in April, he
said.
   In Vienna after the meeting, Baker told reporters the United
States ``is not ready to set a date'' at this point for a summit
between President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The secretary criticized the Soviets about Iran and military aid
to the leftist Sandinista government of Nicaragua. He said Moscow
was ``posturing'' on Iran, which Shevardnadze visited recently, and
had helped arm Nicaragua in a ``way out of proportions'' manner that
threatens its Central American neighbors.
   A senior State Department official traveling with Baker said the
Soviet offer to mediate the furor over British writer Salman
Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic Verses'' interferes with a U.S.
campaign to isolate Iran.
   Iran's fundamentalist Shiite Moslem regime believes the novel
blasphemes Islam and its patriarch, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, has
ordered his followers to kill the author. Iran broke relations with
Britain on Tuesday because it did not condemn the book and prosecute
Rushdie.
   Despite clear differences on those and other issues, the
get-acquainted session between Baker and Shevardnadze appeared to go
well. Baker said it was held ``in a very positive atmosphere,
reflecting a determination to cooperate.''
   As they parted at the residence of Henry Grunwald, the U.S.
ambassador to Austria, Shevardnadze ``told me it was a very good
beginning, and I would agree with that,'' Baker said.
   Baker objected to the Soviet attempt in Vienna to seek reductions
in combat aircraft and naval forces and also eliminate short-range,
or battlefield, nuclear weapons. He said the mandate for
negotiations that begin Thursday excludes missiles and ships.
   Shevardnadze's proposal for separate negotiations on the nuclear
weapons with ranges of up to 300 miles conflicts with U.S.
determination to keep Lance missiles in West Germany and triple
their current range of about 70 miles.
   On Monday night, a senior State Department official briefing
reporters under rules of anonymity said the Soviets were looking for
``fissures'' in the Western alliance.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany has proposed delaying the
Lance modernization for two or three years.
   On the trip home, Baker said Soviet suggestions for conventional
force reduction were ``remarkably close to the NATO proposal.''
   NATO has called for sharp reductions in Warsaw Pact tanks,
artillery and armored personnel carriers to Western levels, followed
by additional cuts of 5-10 percent on both sides.
   Shevardnadze proposed a first-phase reduction of 15 percent by
1992 and 40 percent by 1995.
   U.S.-Soviet negotiations to reduce long-range arms have been
suspended for three months. In mid-February, Bush postponed a
resumption until the policy review was completed.
   Shevardnadze told a news conference in Vienna he suggested to
Baker the talks resume in April or May but the secretary said the
United States ``will need more time.''
   On the plane, Baker said he told Shevardnadze it was ``premature
to lock in on a date now,'' with the review in process. He added to
reporters: ``It is our strong desire to build on the progress that
has been made to date.''
   When the talks were suspended, negotiators had reached tentative
agreement on several weapon ceilings but were having trouble on ways
to guard against cheating.
</TEXT>
