<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Ship     03-07 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ship,0471</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Soviet Pacific Ports Rebuff Attempts by Nuclear-Powered Ship to
Dock ^By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviet Far East ports and a nearby region have
refused entry to a nuclear-powered Soviet merchant ship for fear it
is radioactive, and a newspaper likened the vessel Tuesday to a
``homeless child.''
   The 860-foot Sevmorput, launched only months ago, had been
anchored off Vladivostok for four days because the city council
refused entry, the newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya said. It said city
officials decided March 2 not to let the ship dock until they
receive additional information about its radiation safeguards.
   Officials of Nakhodka and the nearby Magadan region also refused
port calls after tens of thousands of residents protested to a radio
station, the newspaper said.
   Izvestia, the government daily, reported on opposition to the
Sevmorput on March 2. A report in a third newspaper Saturday said
said a meltdown in a nuclear reactor on another Soviet ship was
narrowly averted.
   The Sovietskaya Rossiya article indicated residents became
fearful of the Sevmorput because they had not been given details
about problems with it.
   Fractures appeared in the $260 million barge carrier soon after
it began its maiden voyage Dec. 31 from the Crimean port of Kerch to
the Far East, the newspaper said.
   Experts rushed in to check whether radiation was released and
found the ship clean, confirming its ``atomic heart'' was not
damaged, the article said. It did not say how the damage occurred or
precisely when the incident occurred.
   According to the newspaper, the ship has good safeguards and
could even withstand the crash of a jetliner or a collision with a
huge icebreaker, but it added:
   ``A deficit of information, piled on top of the invisible shadow
of the Chernobyl tragedy and the most complex ecological situation
in the region, detonated a powerful explosion of public
indignation.''
   Public opposition to nuclear power has grown since the explosion
and fire April 26, 1986, at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in the
Ukraine. At least 31 people were killed and the plant spewed
radioactivity that eventually spread around the world.
   Authorities are closing a nuclear power plant in Armenia, a
region prone to earthquakes, and have canceled plans to expand other
plants.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said the Sevmorput was like a ``sea
monster,'' uneconomical because of its size. It said the ship would
lose $19.3 million this year and $22.9 million in 1990.
   It described the vessel to an ``offended homeless child'' and
said every day it is idle costs $88,525.
   On Saturday, the newspaper Vodny Transport said a reactor
meltdown nearly occurred Nov. 11 on the icebreaker Rossiya while it
was docked at the northern port of Murmansk. It said operator error
was responsible.
</TEXT>
