<FIRST>r w AM-Coins-Debt     03-07 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coins-Debt,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annunzio Says Commemorative Coin-Sales Law Cuts National Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., says the national
debt has been reduced by about $750 million through sales of U.S.
commemorative coins and related programs but more must be done ``to
get this terrible debt under control.''
   Annunzio, a former chairman of the House Banking, Finance and
Urban Affairs Committee's subcommittee on consumer affairs and
coinage, says a law earmarking profits from sales of commemorative
coins to reduce the national debt has been ``a step in the right
direction, but we need to take a lot of steps to pay off this
debt,'' which now stands at about $2.7 trillion.
   ``We've got to earmark tax money or even have a surtax. I know
some people won't like to hear that talk about a surtax, but we've
got to get this terrible debt under control. It's the biggest, most
serious problem facing this country today,'' Annunzio said Monday.
   A law passed in 1982 authorizing the U.S. Mint to sell gold and
silver coins and use proceeds for debt retirement and other special
purposes ``is my own small way of dealing with the problem,''
Annunzio said.
   According to the subcomittee, which Annunzio headed for a decade,
profits from the sales are approaching $960 million.
   Of that, it said $742 million is money to reduce the debt and
$214 million is for special programs _ support of U.S. Olympic
athletes and restoration of the Statue of Liberty and Ellis Island.
   The debt-reduction figure includes $409 million from profits on
commemorative coins, $200 million from sales of gold and silver
coins, $25 million last year from special collector coin sets and a
projected profit of $108 million from the 1988 Olympic coin program.
   ``There was no coin program before I became chairman,'' Annunzio
said. ``Now, we have this clicking on all cylinders. ... I just hope
to God it doesn't go down the drain.''
   He said private marketers of coins and precious metals opposed
the legislation when Congress first considered it, ``and they'll
never give up, especially now that I'm gone.''
   ``I don't think there's all that much support for private
enterprise to take over,'' said Greg De Niro, a dealer at the
Maryland Coin Exchange in Silver Spring, Md.
   ``Personally, as both a dealer and a collector, I'm very happy
with the way things are now,'' he said Tuesday. ``The government
makes a profit. So do we. ... It's been a good for everyone
involved.''
   Annunzio left the coinage panel chairmanship this year to become
chairman of the subcommittee on financial institutions supervision,
regulations and insurance.
</TEXT>
