<FIRST>r i AM-MissingSoldier     03-07 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Soldier,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Won't Reveal Where it Believes Missing Soldier Was</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army said Tuesday it
believes it knows where a young soldier was during an 11-day
disappearance near the East German border, but it declined to
elaborate.
   Electronics specialist Michael A. Peri, 21, of Laguna Niguel,
Calif., had been missing from the 11th Armored Cavalry Regiment in
Fulda since Feb. 21, but returned voluntarily Saturday.
   The Army said he has been charged with being absent without leave
and with violating military regulations by coming within a little
more than a half-mile of the East German border.
   ``We have an idea where he was, but we have no additional
information to release pending completion of the investigation
surrounding the circumstances of his absense,'' said Maj. Dennis
Pinkham.
   In an interview from the U.S. military's European Command
headquarters in Stuttgart, Pinkham said it was ``routine procedure,
not to reveal details about such an investigation until it is
completed.''
   Peri, who worked in a military intelligence office in Fulda,
about 65 miles northeast of Frankfurt, had in his possession a
portable computer missing from his office when he returned.
   In addition, a military vehicle Peri had signed out was found
Feb. 23 abandoned undamaged near the town of Obersuhl, in the
restricted zone along the East German border, prompting initial
speculation that he may have defected.
   Peri has been confined to a military detention center in
Mannheim, said Lt. Col. Jake Dye, spokesman for the U.S. Army 5th
Corps.
   Theft charges also filed against Peri applied to the vehicle and
other items, including the portable computer Peri took from the
office where he worked, Dye said.
   Peri's disappearance baffled military officials, who said he had
been a model soldier.
   Peri had worked as an electronics warfare signal specialist and
was responsible for monitoring radar and other military signals. He
has been stationed in West Germany for a year.
</TEXT>
