<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ChannelTunnel     03-07 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Channel Tunnel,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Claim Major Concession by Rail Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters fighting a high-speed rail link between
London and the Channel Tunnel said Tuesday they had won major
concessions from British Rail, including slower trains and tunnels
over one-third of the route.
   The council of the London borough of Lewisham said it obtained
the information from a leaked copy of a British Rail document. The
state-owned rail company declined to comment, saying it would
publish its proposals Wednesday.
   Lewisham is campaigning with residents of southeast England
against plans to cut a new high-speed rail route through London and
the countryside to the rail tunnel under the English Channel that
will link England and France. The channel tunnel is to open in 1993.
   The London-Folkestone route is a hot political issue for Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher. It is also a serious ecological issue
that comes at a time when Mrs. Thatcher needs to demonstrate concern
for the environment.
   Council spokesman Graham Taylor said that according to the
document, 24.6 miles of the 68-mile route would run underground, and
maximum rail speeds would be 140 mph instead of the previously
suggested 180 mph.
