<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-CentralAmerica     03-07 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Central America,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Stresses Linkage with Soviets on Central America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday there ``clearly has
to be some linkage'' between U.S. policy toward the Soviet Union and
the Soviets' behavior in Central America.
   U.S. officials have long complained that the Soviets give
military aid to the leftist Nicaraguan government that the
administration-backed Contras are trying to oust.
   Bush administration officials have said they are hopeful the
Soviets might change that approach, a change that might be
encouraged by U.S. willingness to deal in other areas such as trade
and technology with economic benefit to the Soviets.
   The president said Tuesday in a news conference, ``The more help
we can get towards that end by the Soviets, with pulling back their
large amount of military support, the better it would be between
relations. So there is linkage.''
   He said of the Soviets that the United States should ``give them
credit'' when ``something good happens,'' such as their military
pullout from Afghanistan and the easing of restrictions on Soviet
Jews.
   ``I don't know exactly how to help you in terms of how much
linkage there is, but there's clearly got to be some linkage,'' Bush
told a reporter who questioned him on the Nicaraguan issue.
   He declined to give specifics, saying the matter is still under
policy review by his young administration.
   The State Department's preliminary estimates are that Soviet
weapons deliveries to Nicaragua last year totaled $515 million, the
highest total since 1980 when the Soviets first started aid to
Nicaragua.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III had been expected to bring
up the subject of U.S.-Soviet cooperation in the Central American
peace effort during his talks this week with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze in Vienna, sources said.
   Baker has indicated he might entertain the idea of U.S.
concessions to the Soviets in certain areas if they show what the
U.S. government considers good faith in dealing with Nicaragua.
   Bush on Tuesday reiterated his support for keeping the Contras
going with non-military aid while the Nicaraguan government is made
to prove it will live up to democratization promises it makes in a
peace agreement being worked out by the Central American presidents.
   `I hope there is some understanding on the (Capitol) Hill that
these people must not be left without humanitarian aid. ... We
simply cannot and I will not leave the Contras out there with no
humanitarian aid at all,'' the president said.
   Asked about the possibility of military aid, which would have dim
prospects in Congress, Bush said, ``We are talking ... about how
best to move the process of democratization forward.''
   He said he would look for ``clear statements'' on democratization
in the agreement being worked out by Nicaragua's President Daniel
Ortega and the presidents of Central America's four democracies. The
document also would include disbanding the Contras.
   When Baker visited Capitol Hill last week to consult with members
of Congress on a Contra aid package, he carried proposals that also
would offer the Sandinistas economic incentives if they show what
the administration considers progress in such areas as press and
political freedoms.
</TEXT>
