<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenians     03-07 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenians,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian Refugees Protest at Government Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 70 Armenians who fled the southern republic
of Azerbaijan because of ethnic violence massed in a government
office Tuesday to demand a meeting with Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov,
a dissident said.
   Sergei Grigoryants, a dissident journalist who is half Armenian
and half Russian, said the refugees wanted to talk to Ryzhkov about
what they see as government attempts to force them to return to
Azerbaijan.
   At least 141,000 Azerbaijanis have fled Armenia, and 159,000
Armenians left Azerbaijan, most of them since violence erupted in
the region in the Caucasus Mountains in November. The violence,
sparked by a territorial dispute between Armenians and Azerbaijanis,
has claimed 91 lives, the government says.
   Grigoryants said the government has been all but forcing the
Armenian refugees to return to Azerbaijan by evicting them from
hotels and not giving them permanent places to live or new jobs. The
refugees fear they will become targets of the ethnic hatred if they
return to Azerbaijan.
   The government contends the refugees would be safe if they
returned, and says it is trying to find new jobs and homes for those
who wish to stay away.
   A group of the refugees showed up Friday at the offices of the
Council of Ministers, the Soviet Cabinet, to demand a meeting with
Ryzhkov, Grigoryants said. An aide promised that Ryzhkov would meet
the refugees in a few days and try to help.
   On Monday, the refugees received word that Ryzhkov had refused a
meeting because the issue was resolved, so 70 of them returned to
the office Tuesday to protest, and seven announced a hunger strike,
according to the dissident.
   The predominantly Moslem Azerbaijanis and mostly Christian
Armenians have been at odds since February 1988 in a dispute over
the Nagorno-Karabakh district of Azerbaijan. Armenians, who make up
the majority of the district's population, complained of
discrimination under Azerbaijani control, and demanded annexation
with the Armenian republic. They have staged huge demonstrations and
strikes in Armenia.
</TEXT>
