<FIRST>r w AM-VegetableOutlook     03-07 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vegetable Outlook,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>1988 Receipts Likely Up Slightly from 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher prices for last year's drought-reduced
vegetable harvests probably boosted growers' receipts slightly from
the record level of $9.2 billion in 1987, the Agriculture Department
said Tuesday.
   ``Total output of vegetables probably fell about 4 percent in
1988 because of declines in potato, dry bean and processing
vegetable production,'' the department's Economic Research Service
said in an outlook report. ``Assuming normal weather, output should
rebound in 1989.''
   While projecting higher overall income for vegetable farmers last
year, the department's report _ a summary of another report, not yet
released _ did not have a figure for projected 1988 income.
   The report released Tuesday also said that per capita use of
vegetables, which probably declined in 1988 because of smaller
production, is expected to return to pre-drought levels this year.
   ``Utilization probably will continue to be enhanced by general
economic conditions in the United States,'' the report said. ``With
real disposable incomes and employment remaining relatively strong,
domestic demand for all types of vegetables should continue robust.''
   Exports of fresh vegetables, which soared in 1988, are expected
to continue rising this year, reflecting the decline in the dollar
and growth in the Japanese market, the report said.
   One reason for the export increase is a rise in french fry
shipments to Pacific Rim countries.
   Potato prices paid to growers are projected to average even
higher than the department's initial forecast of $5.49 per
hundredweight, the report said. Last year's average was $4.35 per
100 pounds. As a result, potato farmers are expected to expand their
1989 acreage.
</TEXT>
