<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     03-07 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Reported Planning Plebiscite to Amend Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FEDERICO QUILODRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet plans to call a
plebiscite in the next three months to propose changes in the
military-drafted Constitution, a government official and a newspaper
said Tuesday.
   Changes to be ratified by a popular vote in May or June may
include one that allows Pinochet to seek re-election in a December
presidential vote, according to the El Diario newspaper.
   The newspaper quoted unidentifed government sources as saying
Pinochet is expected to announce the plebiscite Saturday as part of
his annual state-of-the nation address.
   When asked at a news conference Saturday about reports of a
second referendum, Pinochet said only, ``Everything is possible,''
and refused to elaborate.
   But Jaime Guzman, one of Pinochet's closest political allies,
said Tuesday: ``I have firm indications that the president will
announce a plebiscite to amend the constitution.''
   In October, voters rejected a proposal to extend Pinochet's term
until 1997 and set the Dec. 14 election date. The Constitution bars
Pinochet from running again.
   However, a number of right-wing groups have repeatedly asked that
the Constitution be changed to allow the 73-year-old president and
army commander to seek re-election.
   Last week, Pinochet refused to rule out a new presidential
candidacy.
   ``It's too early to talk about that,'' said Pinochet, who has
ruled since a bloody 1973 coup.
   The opposition has demanded constitutional changes since the
campaign for the October referendum. However, the specific changes
they want such as the elimination of one article that bars Marxist
parties and another that appoints one-third of the 35-member senate,
have been flatly rejected by Pinochet.
   Consequently, opposition leaders have shown little enthusiasm for
a second plebiscite.
   ``The only constitutional change we want is the one that restores
popular sovereignty,'' said Ricardo Lagos, who heads a moderate
socialist party.
</TEXT>
