<FIRST>u a AM-FlagArt Bjt   03-07 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art, Bjt,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flag's Use in Artwork: Desecration, Celebration, Cause for Reflection?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American flag is still on the floor at the
School of the Art Institute despite a museum-goer's arrest, a
lawsuit, threats of economic reprisals and protests from veterans,
who vowed Tuesday to step up their opposition.
   ``I had 2,500 people here (Sunday) and I'm going to have 25,000
people here (protesting) next Sunday,'' said Republican state Sen.
Walter Dudycz, a Vietnam veteran.
   School officials haven't been swayed by the furor over a student
artwork featuring a flag spread on the ground.
   ``We feel .. that the First Amendment is at stake in a very big
way here,'' said Tony Brown, vice president of the school of 1,700,
which is affiliated with the Art Institute of Chicago, one of the
nation's most respected museums.
   ``You almost have a charge from the public, if you're going to be
a great institution to take a very serious look at freedom of
expression,'' he said.
   The work that caused the uproar is ``What is the Proper Way to
Display the U.S. Flag?'' by Scott Tyler, 24, of Chicago, who calls
himself ``Dread'' Scott.
   The exhibit consists of the flag; a photographic montage on the
wall with pictures of flag-draped caskets, South Koreans burning the
flag and a ``Yankees go home'' sign; and a ledger for comments on a
shelf below the photos.
   Veterans contend the work invites viewers to trample the flag as
they go to the ledger, and on Saturday, Susan Willhofft, an art
teacher from Arlington, Va., was charged with felony desecration of
the flag for stepping on it.
   Protests began a week after the exhibit opened Feb. 17 for a
five-week run.
   Veterans said they consider the flag's placement a desecration,
and they were joined by several politicians, including Republican
mayoral candidate Ed Vrdolyak.
   ``I personally shed a lot of blood defending the flag. ... We
defended it in Vietnam, we're going to defend it here in our city,''
said Robert Kolling, who lost a leg in Vietnam and was among the
throngs demonstrating Sunday.
   Dudycz and Vrdolyak urged a boycott of the school's corporate
sponsors and also said they would try to cut off state funds from
the institution.
   The school gets its money from federal, state and corporate
sources, said spokeswoman Beth Sullivan, but she said she did not
have exact figures.
   ``I'm getting phone calls from all over the country. People are
asking what they can do,'' Dudycz said Monday.
   Brown had no comment on the threat to cut off funds.
   The school closed the exhibit Feb. 25 after threats to students
and the building, but it was reopened on Friday.
   The same day, Circuit Judge Kenneth Gillis dismissed a lawsuit
from veterans seeking to take the flag off the floor. ``This exhibit
is as much an invitation to think about the flag as ... to step on
the flag,'' he said.
   Veterans of Foreign Wars spokesman Robert Jones said Tuesday his
group would abide by Gillis' ruling. But he said the VFW would
petition members of Congress and others to complain about the
desecration.
   Ms. Willhofft's attorney, David Steinberg, called her an
``innocent out-of-town tourist who was entrapped,'' and said the
Supreme Court has overturned three flag-desecration prosecutions
since 1969 and is considering a 1984 flag-burning that occurred
during the GOP National Convention.
   Another work at the school stirred controversy last spring when
black aldermen stormed the halls to remove a painting of the late
Harold Washington that depicted the city's first black mayor wearing
women's underwear.
   School officials have refused to disclose Tyler's whereabouts.
The works in the exhibit were selected by faculty members.
</TEXT>
