<HEAD>Inmates on Hunger Strike to Protest Beatings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 57 political prisoners at a
high-security prison have gone on a hunger strike to protest an
alleged beating by soldiers and demand a government investigation, a
lawyer said Tuesday.
   Ersan Sansal, a defense lawyer, said the inmates told him they
began the hunger strike March 1 after more than 100 special commando
soldiers entered the cell blocks and kicked and beat prisoners.
   The lawyer said one inmate was hospitalized with broken ribs and
that four others suffered concussions and were taken to the prison
infirmary.
   Hilmi Baykal, a prosecutor investigating the incident, confirmed
the prisoners were on a hunger strike but declined to give any other
details.
   Prison authorities also placed 19 inmates in isolation cells
after the incident, the lawyer said.
   Sansal said fasting inmates want a fair investigation of the
incident and the release of prisoners from isolation cells.
   The inmates are accused of belonging to leftist organizations
that were active before the 1980 military takeover. They are being
tried under accusations of trying to overthrow the government.
