<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-China     03-07 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-China,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>400,000 More Tons of Wheat Sold to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporters have sold China an additional
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the
Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was part of 2 million
tons authorized Feb. 27 for China under the Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in
selected overseas markets and then collect free government surpluses
of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   The latest sale boosted to more than 7.8 million tons the amount
of wheat sold to China for 1988-89 delivery under the EEP.
   Sims said the latest sales were handled by Cargill Inc., 150,000
tons; and Louis Dreyfus Corp., 250,000 tons.
   The wheat was sold for shipment in April and May and will carry
an average subsidy rate of $22.19 per ton, or about 60 cents a
bushel, he said. Slightly more than 1.6 million tons are still
available under the current authorization.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The 400,000 tons would be about 14.7 million bushels and,
at recent prices of about $4.1l per bushel, would have a farm value
of around $60 million.
</TEXT>
