<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Malaise     03-07 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Malaise,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Insists His Programs Are Moving Forward Despite Tower Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday dismissed suggestions
that the fight to salvage John Tower's nomination as defense
secretary has paralyzed his administration.
   ``I think we're on track,'' Bush said in answer to a host of
recent stories depicting an administration in disarray and without
momentum.
   He ticked off a number of initiatives, such as foreign policy
talks with world leaders, saying, ``I would simply resist the clamor
that nothing seems to be bubbling around, that nothing is
happening.''
   Several political figures, including some Republicans, have said
they believe the long Tower confirmation battle has sapped White
House energy and held up other important business, such as key
decisions about national defense strategy and the appointments of
top-level government officials.
   But during a White House news conference, Bush said there were
``plenty of substantive things'' taking place in the seventh full
week of his presidency.
   ``If you would just write down all those wonderful things I told
you that are happening, and get it out to that wide readership,'' he
told reporters, ``it would be very helpful to me.''
   Although Bush said he wants to see the pace of nominations and
appointments move more quickly, he cited statistics he said show
more key nominations made at this juncture than were announced after
six weeks by the Reagan administration in 1981.
   David Gergen, a White House communications director during the
first two years of the Reagan administration and now editor at large
of U.S. News &amp; World Report, harshly criticized Bush in an article
written for the editorial section of Sunday's Washington Post.
   ``Win or lose on the Tower fight, President Bush now stands
perilously close to the edge of a cliff,'' Gergen wrote. `` ...
There is deepening sense in Washington that something is badly amiss
in his administration.''
   Asked about Gergen's criticism, Bush said, ``Well, I think he's
wrong.''
   Questioned about Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy's statement
that Democrats in Congress should seize the national policy
initiative, Bush replied, ``Ted Kennedy? Enough said.''
   Bush conceded, however, that ``that's one of the allegations _
disarray.''
   But he said ``I don't think the American people make up their
minds on perceptions,'' and he said he has ``total confidence'' in
former New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, White House chief of staff.
   ``Every chief of staff goes through this drill where he gets
saluted for his brilliance and, a month later, gets attacked for his
something else,'' Bush said.
   Bush defended time-consuming reviews he has ordered in areas of
foreign policy, strategic defense and Pentagon budget management,
saying ``it is a prudent thing to do.''
   He acknowledged that not having a secretary of defense in place
at the Pentagon was ``an inhibiting factor'' in getting the
strategic review completed in 90 days, but said ``I hope there's not
going to be any slippage'' in meeting the May 10 deadline. ``I don't
want to be foot-dragging.''
   Bush maintained he has provided Congress with more details on his
budget thinking than had either former presidents Ronald Reagan and
Jimmy Carter.
   He said moved quickly on the savings-and-loan crisis, that he is
pushing ahead with a reassessment of America's drug problem, with a
host of environmental initiatives and with a system of national
service for the young.
   ``Go back and look at history,'' Bush urged reporters. ``It kind
of goes in cycles. But I'm not deterred at all.''
</TEXT>
