<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Philippines-Corruption     03-07 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Philippines-Corruption,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ramos Says 500 Troops Under Investigation For Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 500 soldiers, including
colonels and generals, are under investigation for corruption as
part of the military's attempt to cleanse its image, according to
Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos.
   The list included 140 officers with the rank of colonel or above,
Ramos said after a Senate hearing Monday. Most of the alleged
offenses took place under Ferdinand Marcos' administration, he said.
   Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa said most senior officers
under investigation have retired. But he said those in active
service include Lt. Gen. Antonio Sotelo, the vice chief of staff.
   Documents released by the Anti-Graft Board of the Armed Forces of
the Philippines showed 744 people were charged with graft, including
580 soldiers, 19 police officers and 145 civilians working in
military agencies. They showed 146 military officials have been
cleared of graft charges.
   Ramos also said the military is to implement major changes in the
armed forces, but he denied it was connected with the investigation
of graft charges.
