<FIRST>r w AM-SteelDumping     03-07 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Dumping,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Steel Rails from Canada Being Sold Below Fair-Market
Value</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday it has
made a preliminary determination that steel rails from Canada are
being sold in the United States at less than fair-market value.
   In an investigation that began last September with a petition
from Bethlehem Steel Corp. on behalf of the U.S. steel industry, the
department found dumping of rails by Algoma Steel Corp. Ltd. and
other unspecified companies in Canada.
   The department is expected to make a final ruling by May 22. If
the agency's initial determination stands, the U.S. International
Trade Commission would decide within 45 days whether the imports
threaten injury to the U.S. steel industry.
   If the ITC finds that imports with an unfair price advantage over
comparable domestic products are harming U.S. industry, anti-dumping
duties are imposed.
   Imports of steel rails from Canada in 1987 were valued at about
$10 million. The rails are used in the railroad industry, rapid
transit lines, subways and mines.
</TEXT>
