<DOCNO> AP890307-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FCCSpending     03-07 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC Spending,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget-Caused Cutbacks Will Cost Eventually, Patrick Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick told a House panel
Tuesday that budget-caused cutbacks in staff and computer equipment
this year could cost the Treasury $48 million in future revenues.
   Patrick said the Federal Communications Commission needs
additional funds in fiscal 1990 to hire more staff and buy more
computers to relieve a backlog of license and telecommunications
service applications that increased about 20 percent from 1988 to
1989.
   ``Delays in licensing caused by staff shortages or lack of
automatiion affect not only applicants, but adversely impact the
(gross national product) and reduce tax revenues,'' Patrick told the
House Appropriations subcommittee on commerce, justice and state,
the judiciary and related agencies.
   The subcommittee is considering the White House Office of
Management and Budget's request for $109.8 million in funds for the
FCC for fiscal 1990. That would be an increase of $10.2 million over
the fiscal 1989 appropriation of $99.6 million. The FCC had sought
$111.9 million.
   Patrick said the FCC's appropriation in fiscal 1988 was the same
as fiscal 1989 and that the agency began fiscal 1989 on Oct. 1,
1988, with a $5 million deficit because of pay raises and health
benefit increases.
   To cover that shortage, Patrick said he imposed a hiring freeze
and did not replace workers who retired or quit. Other cuts included
a 75 percent reduction in automated data processing equipment
purchases, he said.
   He said his staff estimated that a one-year reduction of $5
million in its fiscal 1989 appropriation, if continued beyond fiscal
1990, could reduce the present value of federal tax revenues by
roughly $53 million, producing a net revenue loss of about $48
million.
   Rep. Joseph D. Early, D-Mass., criticized the cutback in
automated equipment purchases.
   ``I don't think that's good management,'' he told Patrick.
   But Patrick said the agency had gotten to the point it couldn't
cut staff any further. He said in the first quarter of fiscal 1988
the agency had a backlog of 10,322 applications for new services in
the telephone industry. By the first quarter of fiscal 1989 the
backlog had grown to 12,317 applications or a 19 percent increase.
The backlog in radio applications was 20 percent, he said.
</TEXT>
