<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     03-07 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC First in Ratings, But Who's on Second?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC won the ratings for the 37th week in a
row, but which network is second for the season depends on whose
compilation of the Nielsen ratings you use.
   All three networks agree that ABC and CBS tied for second place
for the week ended March 5. But, with the season due to end April
23, the networks disagree on second place for the season-to-date.
NBC's wins go back to last season.
   NBC was the unquestioned winner for the week ended March 5 with a
16.1 rating and a share of 26 in the A.C. Nielsen Co. listing.
   ABC and CBS tied for the past week with 12.6 and a 20 share. Each
ratings point represents 904,000 homes with television. The share is
a percentage of the sets in use.
   The past week offered no surprises in the listings, with NBC's
``The Cosby Show'' still in first place. ABC's ``The Wonder Years''
was in eighth place after its move to Tuesday night between ``Who's
the Boss?'' in seventh place, and ``Roseanne,'' in third place.
   NBC, which lists the beginning of the season as Sept. 19, put ABC
in second place after 24 weeks. Its season-to-date ratings are ABC
12.9 with a 21 percent share and CBS 12.6 with a 20 share. NBC leads
season-to-date with a rating of 16.0 and a 26 share.
   CBS, counting the season from Oct. 24, lists itself in second
place with a 12.9 rating and a 21 share. It gives ABC 12.8 and a 21
share.
   ABC's Nielsen listings put ABC and CBS in a tie with 12.8 each.
It also counts the season from Oct. 24.
   The difference in the season beginning is due to the writers
strike last summer, which caused a delay in the premieres of many
series.
   NBC set the season opening at the traditional start time because
it had the Summer Olympics from Seoul, Korea. Differences may also
result from interpretations by the networks of the raw data from
Nielsen.
   It appeared that ABC would finish in second place for the second
year, but CBS became a contender with the miniseries ``Lonesome
Dove.''
   The Top 10 this past week was dominated by two nights, NBC's
Thursday comedies and ABC's Tuesday comedies. All four NBC Thursday
shows were at the top, as were three ABC shows.
   ABC's new comedy ``Coach,'' which had a special preview following
``Roseanne'' on Tuesday, placed 11th. But for its premiere in its
regular Wednesday time slot the show dropped to 46th place.
   Here are the Top 10: NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``A
Different World,'' ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' NBC's
``Golden Girls,'' ABC's ``Who's the Boss?,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes,''
ABC's ``The Wonder Years,'' NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and NBC's ``Dear
John.''
   The CBS special movie ``Day One'' was 29th in the ratings. The
premiere of the CBS series ``Hard Time on Planet Earth'' was in 65th
place.
   ``Married ... With Children,'' the Fox Broadcasting Co. comedy
that came under attack last week from a Michigan mother who said the
show was ``lewd and anti-family,'' was 54th.
   The lowest-rated show of the week was Fox's ``Beyond Tomorrow.''
Here are the four other lowest shows of the week: Fox's ``The
Reporters,'' Fox's ``The Tracey Ullman Show,'' ABC's ``a Fine
Romance'' and Fox's ``Duet.''
   ABC said ``A Fine Romance'' had its last telecast last week and
would be replaced temporarily by a two-part movie special.
   Among the evening news shows, CBS was the winner with a rating of
11.5. ABC was second with 11.2 and NBC was third with 10.5.
</TEXT>
