<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Medicaid-NursingHomes     03-07 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicaid-Nursing Homes,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Backs Plan to Recover Costs from Estates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal and state governments could save as
much as $500 million a year if efforts were made to recover some of
the costs of nursing home care from the estates of Medicaid
recipients and their spouses, a congressional report said Tuesday.
   The report by the General Accounting Office recommends that
Congress require states to establish asset-recovery programs similar
to one run by the state of Oregon, which recovers about $10 for
every $1 spent on its Medicaid program.
   ``If implemented carefully, estate recovery programs can achieve
savings, while treating the elderly equitably and humanely,'' the
report said.
   However, ``it's a sensitive issue whenever you talk about
someone's right to leave an inheritance,'' said Jim Linz, assistant
director of Medicare and Medicaid issues for the GAO.
   Linz estimated total federal and state Medicaid savings at $400
million to $500 million if all states had an estate recovery program
such as Oregon's.
   Medicaid is a more than $50 billion federal-state health
assistance program for the poor. The federal government sets broad
guidelines for the programs and provides the bulk of the money, but
the states set eligibilty criteria and administer the programs.
   Most of the elderly who become eligible for Medicaid's nursing
home benefit do so by ``spending down'' their assets to meet the
income and asset limits for the program, the GAO said. However, the
program allows a Medicaid recipient to retain his home _ usually a
person's primary asset _ as long as a family member is living there
or the recipient expects to return to the home.
   Unless a state has an estate recovery program, however, it cannot
recover assets that remain at the time the recipient dies, or if
their spouse is living, at the time the spouse dies, the GAO said.
Often, the only remaining asset is the recipient's home.
   Twenty-one states and the District of Columbia have programs
allowing recovery of Medicaid benefits from recipients estates, with
annual recoveries totaling about $42 million, according to a June
report by the inspector general for the Department of Health and
Human Resources.
   None of the programs approaches the effectiveness of the Oregon
program, which recovers an average of $327 per Medicaid nursing home
resident, which totals about $4 million annually, the GAO said. The
next highest recovery rates are $160 per Medicaid nursing home
resident in New Hampshire and $109 in Massachusetts.
   The key elements of Oregon's program, according to the GAO, are
procedures for identifying a Medicaid applicant's assets, tracking
and preserving assets while Medicaid assistance is provided, and
recovering from the recipient's estate. The law also allows for
recovery from the spouse's estate if the state didn't recover from
the recipient's estate.
   The GAO said advocacy groups for the elderly in Oregon say that
the state's program incorporates enough flexibility so that estate
recoveries don't create undue hardships on the recipient's heirs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0153 </DOCNO>
