<FIRST>r a AM-PhiladelphiaSlayings     03-07 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philadelphia Slayings,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>South-to-North Caravan to Renew Civil Rights Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five years after the slayings of
three young men drew the nation's attention to the civil rights
movement, a new Freedom Summer caravan is being planned to
commemorate the deaths, organizers said Tuesday.
   Civil rights leaders from Mississippi and across the nation were
joined by Gov. Ray Mabus at the announcement of the caravan, which
will leave Philadelphia, Miss., on June 21 and travel to Washington
and New York.
   ``It will be kind of a prayer pilgrimage of reconcilation where
the spirit of good will which Mississippi has recaptured will come
alive again,'' said James Farmer, the former chairman of the
Congress of Racial Equality.
   Farmer, who played a major role in the original Freedom Summer
demonstrations in 1964, said Mississippi has shed its ``ugly image
of hatred'' and can be a model for the rest of the nation.
   He said he realized that when he Mabus greeted him in the
governor's office once held by the late Theodore Bilbo, a strident
segregationist.
   ``I knew then that in this great land of ours, all things are
possible,'' Farmer said.
   Mabus also spoke of change in Mississippi. ``Today, once more,
the officials of Mississippi are standing in the schoolhouse door,
but this time we are standing in that door to open it wider and to
make sure that everybody gets in,'' he said.
   The caravan will commemorate the slayings of Andrew Goodman,
James Earl Chaney and Michael Henry Schwerner, whose bodies were
found in an earthen dam near Philadelphia six weeks after their
deaths on June 21, 1964.
   Chaney was a 21-year-old black from Meridian; Goodman, 20, and
Schwerner, 24, were white New Yorkers who were among the young
people from around the nation who flocked to the South to protest
racial discrimination during Freedom Summer.
   Julia Chaney Moss, the sister of James Chaney, said the caravan
would ``recreate that moment in time in 1964 to educate the youth
and re-educate those older of us who maybe have become complacent in
our lives, and to re-dedicate ourselves to human rights, civil
rights and voter registration.''
   State Rep. Aaron Henry, president of the Mississippi branch of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said
the caravan would begin with rallies in Jackson and Meridian and
then head on to Philadelphia.
   Later stops are planned in Selma, Ala.; Washington, and New York,
where a rally will be held on June 24 near where Chaney is buried.
   Chaney, Goodman and Schwerner vanished after being arrested and
jailed in Philadelphia on a traffic violation. No one was tried for
murder, but eight men were convicted on federal charges of denying
the three their civil rights.
   The incident was fictionalized in the Oscar-nominated movie
``Mississippi Burning,'' which has won critical acclaim but also has
been widely accused of minimizing the role of black Mississippians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
