<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Pickering     03-07 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Pickering,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickering Confirmed U.N. Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 99-0 on Tuesday to confirm
career diplomat Thomas Pickering to be U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations.
   Pickering, who will succeed retired Army Lt. Gen. Vernon Walters,
most recently served as U.S. ambassador to Israel.
   During his 30-year career as a Foreign Service officer he also
has been ambassador to Jordan, Nigeria and El Salvador.
   No opposition to the nomination was voiced during a brief debate
on the Senate floor, and senators of both parties hailed Pickering
as an experienced and talented diplomat.
   Several said that he begins his duties at the U.N. with
opportunities for breakthroughs in settling conflicts in many parts
of the world.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the senior GOP member of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, said Pickering will confront
anti-American, anti-Israeli and pro-Soviet attitudes from many U.N.
members.
   ``He is wading into a real quagmire ... of anti-American and
pro-communist bias,'' Helms said.
   In the roll call, only Sen. Quentin Burdick, D-N.D., did not vote.
   No mention was made in the brief Senate debate of the controversy
that developed when, during his service as ambassador to El
Salvador, Pickering accepted a private document from a Central
American official and delivered it to Oliver North, then a staff
member of the National Security Council.
   The document _ apparently later delivered by North to leaders of
the Contra rebels in Nicaragua _ was an offer to provide $1 million
in military equipment.
   During his confirmation hearing Pickering said that although he
delivered the letter to North, he did not believe he had violated a
congressional ban in effect at the time which barred direct or
indirect aid to the Contras.
   He said he delivered the letter to North outside of normal State
Department channels only because he knew North was the Reagan
administration's liaison with the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
