<DOCNO> AP890307-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     03-07 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Says Talks Clear Obstacles, Accord Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and the opposition have
overcome barriers to a compromise, and an accord on political and
social reforms should be signed April 3, Lech Walesa said Tuesday.
   ``I am very satisfied,'' the founder of Solidarity said after an
eight-hour meeting with the interior minister, Gen. Czeslaw
Kiszczak, and other government and Communist Party officials.
   Opposition spokesmen said agreement was reached on legalizing the
banned Independent Students Association, known by its initials NZS,
which had become a sticking point in the month-old ``round table''
negotiations.
   The news came on the eve of the anniversary of student riots
March 8, 1968. On Tuesday, city officials in Warsaw took the unusual
step of issuing permits for two commemorative marches by students.
   ``We are finalizing the round table,'' Walesa said. ``All basic
problems, like (union) pluralism ... will be achieved in time, in
line with our commitments.''
   Authorities proposed negotiations with the opposition, led by
Walesa's union, because of strikes in 1988 and fears of further
social problems due to shortages, low wages and inflation running at
an annual rate of about 60 percent.
   Among the goals Walesa and other opposition leaders set were
restoration of legal status to Solidarity, the independent farmers'
union Rural Solidarity and the student association.
   All were formed in the labor turmoil of 1980, when Solidarity
became the first free union in the Soviet bloc. They were outlawed
after martial law was imposed in December 1981 but have continued to
function.
   Officials indicated soon after the talks began Feb. 6 that
Solidarity and Rural Solidarity would be legalized, but the student
group's fate remained in doubt.
   A joint communique carried by the official news agency PAP after
Tuesday's meeting said ``there were conditions for a further
rapprochement of stances on the key issues of dialogue and
directions of proposed political, economic and social reforms,
including the registration of the NZS student union.''
   Piotr Konopka, a Solicarity spokesman, said: ``It seems that this
is an unequivocal decision on registration of NZS. This is good news
for the students, but it's also good news for us because all the
people taking part in the talks on our side have emphasized that
registering NZS was one of the key problems.''
   No other agreements were mentioned in the joint statement. It
also said nothing of such issues as the form for parliamentary
elections in which the opposition would participate and an
opposition demand that wages be indexed to the cost of living.
   Walesa said he and Kiszczak might have to meet again but the
working groups on specific topics should finish by March 20. The
period between then and April 3 would allow each side to study the
tentative agreement, he said.
   About his meeting with Kiszczak, who leads the government
delegation, Walesa said: ``We are removing obstacles that have
appeared here and there, but we are only removing them politically
and the rest must be worked out at the tables because the experts
are there.''
   Janusz Onyszkiewicz, national spokesman for Solidarity, said: ``I
imagine the final agreement will be in the form of a resolution
including general declarations, maybe accompanied by annexes with
details, signed by all the participants at the round table.''
   Walesa spoke to reporters outside the Roman Catholic episcopate
in Warsaw after returning from the meeting accompanied by advisers.
He boarded a train soon afterward for Gdansk, the Baltic port where
he works as a shipyard electrician and founded Solidarity during a
strike in August 1980.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said the Walesa-Kiszczak meeting
included ``attempts to separate out subjects on which we can reach
agreement in order to leave for the future subjects on which we
haven't reached agreement.''
   At a news conference, he listed requirements for an accord as
``working out a document about what links Poles, an agreement on
non-confrontational elections and practical implementation of trade
union pluralism.''
</TEXT>
