<DOCNO> AP890307-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     03-07 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Says Major Deficit Reduction Would Mean Tax Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Rostenkowski, chairman of the House Ways
and Means Committee, told President Bush's budget director on
Tuesday that any major reduction in the federal deficit would
require a tax increase.
   ``I don't want to raise taxes, but I can't see how we can achieve
a significant amount of deficit reduction on the spending side
only,'' Rostenkowski said as his committee heard testimony from
Richard Darman, director of the Office of Management and Budget.
   Rostenkowski also told Darman that there was little chance of
enacting two administration tax-increasing proposals, broadening the
Medicare tax to all state and local employees and blocking an
automatic reduction in the airport excise tax. Those ``simply do not
have the votes to pass,'' he said.
   The White House refuses to consider those levies as tax boosts.
In response to questions by the committee, Darman said he might
consider other revenue-raising measures as something other than tax
increases.
   For example, applying the telephone excise tax to wire services,
now exempt, might be considered ``loophole closing,'' he said. Other
changes might be considered user fees.
   But he said Bush had shown no indication that he was softening
his opposition to new taxes.
   ``If someone were going to change his (Bush's) mind, it would
take a major effort,'' he said.
   At a hearing of the Senate Appropriations Committee, Sen. J.
Bennett Johnston, D-La., complained to Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady that the administration was using rosy economic assumptions
and other gimmicks to make its budget proposal fall within the
Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction targets.
   Johnston said the administration hadn't offered a realistic plan
that could serve as ``a starting point'' for serious negotiations
and that the Gramm-Rudman targets might have to be relaxed even if a
credible plan were advanced.
   He said it was doubtful that ``enough taxes and real budget cuts
with real economic assumptions'' could be enacted to meet the
Gramm-Rudman targets for fiscal 1990.
   Brady defended the administration's economic assumptions as
realistic and said that while Gramm-Rudman was imperfect, ``it is a
form of sanity'' that has been reassuring to financial markets
anxious to see progress toward deficit-reduction.
   Like Darman, Brady said he would oppose changing the Gramm-Rudman
law and its $100 billion deficit limit for fiscal 1990. The
administration claims it has met the target without increasing taxes.
   ``I feel very strongly that we should not move the goal lines,''
he said. ``... I think we do have a starting point. I have optimism
that we're going to reach the goal line without moving it.''
   Darman and Brady plan to resume discussions this week with
congressional budget writers. The administration's goal is
full-scale negotiations on the budget for fiscal 1990, which begins
Oct. 1.
   Congressional Democrats complained that the administration has
been slow to provide information on policies it would favor in a
deficit-reduction plan, especially the cuts required in domestic
programs.
   Bush, in a news conference Tuesday, repeated his assertion that
he has provided Capitol Hill with more detail than other presidents
did at the beginning of their administrations.
   ``More detail has been sent to the hill at this time in our
administration _ let me clarify that _ than at any time for either
the Reagan administration, 1981, or the Carter administration in
'77,'' he said. ``They hadn't gone up with near this amount of
detail to the hill.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
