<FIRST>u a AM-WifeSlain     03-07 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wife Slain,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dead Woman Had Feared Ex-Husband Would Kill Her, Co-Worker Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MISHAWAKA, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lisa M. Bianco tried to put her past as an
abused wife behind her by working at a women's shelter but always
feared her ex-husband would return from prison to kill her.
   ``She said her choice at that time would be to run, change her
identity and hope he wouldn't identify her, or stay and fight,''
said Michalyn Chilcote, director of the Elkhart County Women's
Shelter. ``She wasn't quite sure what was going to happen.''
   On Saturday, her ex-husband, Alan L. Matheney, 38, did return and
bludgeoned the 29-year-old Ms. Bianco to death outside her home with
the butt of a shotgun, police said.
   Matheney had been freed hours earlier on an eight-hour furlough
from an Indiana prison, where he was serving time for beating his
wife and confining the couple's two children, authorities said.
   Within hours of the woman's death, Matheney surrendered to police
and was taken into custody. Murder charges were filed Tuesday.
   Matheney's arrest ``didn't faze him in the least,'' said South
Bend police Sgt. Norval Williams.
   ``He had, you might say, completed a mission he set out to
achieve,'' Williams said, ``and now that he had done what he wanted
to do he was ready turn himself in, and more or less ready to pay
his dues.''
   Protests mounted over the decision to grant Matheney a furlough
from the Correctional Industrial Complex near the Indiana State
Reformatory at Pendleton, and Gov. Evan Bayh over the weekend
suspended the program.
   ``There are a lot of women who are very, very angry, and angry at
the system,'' said Bonnie Bailey, president of the Mishawaka
Commission on the Status of Women.
   ``Lisa did everything she could to legally get into the system
and get her husband locked up and the system failed,'' she said
Tuesday after an emotional commission meeting.
   Ms. Bianco had become a counselor at the women's shelter in
August and rose quickly into the $14,000-a-year job as program
director, said Ms. Chilcote.
   ``We chose her mainly because she had been an abused woman and
knew what it felt like,'' said Ms. Chilcote. ``She could look at
them and say, `Yeah, I was at the bottom of the pit, too, and I
climbed out.'''
   In December, she asked for and received a volunteer appointment
to the Mishawaka women's commission. ``That was her way of trying to
get her life back together and possibly contributing, helping
others,'' said Ms. Bailey.
   Two state Department of Correction employees were suspended
without pay Monday for issuing the pass and failing to notify Ms.
Bianco that Matheney had been granted the furlough, said department
spokesman Vaughn Overstreet.
</TEXT>
