<FIRST>u i AM-ChemicalWeapons     03-07 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Weapons,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Calls On Soviets To Withdraw Chemical Weapons From Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Baker, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday urged the
Soviet Union to remove its chemical weapons from Eastern Europe and
destroy them.
   The appeal followed a U.S. proposal to speed the removal of
chemical weapons from West Germany.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl, in a news release, said the Soviets and
United States have a unique opportunity to make significant progress
in ending the threat of chemical warfare.
   ``The United States has taken a step that the Soviet Union and
its allies should now follow without delay,'' Kohl said.
   Referring to the U.S. proposal, he said, ``I call on the Soviet
Union in turn to pull out its chemical weapons stationed in Eastern
Europe and to destroy them.''
   West German opposition leaders have said the U.S. proposal was
vague and disappointing.
   On Monday, Secretary of State James A. Baker said President Bush
wanted to explore ways to accelerate the removal of U.S. chemical
weapons from West Germany.
   ``The United States is prepared to lead in dealing with this
problem,'' Baker said, but the early removal of the chemical weapons
will require ``safe storage and the development of practical plans
to destroy them.''
   He also said the Soviet Union has enormous stocks of such weapons
threatening Western Europeand he urged Soviet leaders to join in the
mutual destruction of ``these frightening weapons.''
   In Canberra, Australia, Foreign Minister Gareth Evans said
Tuesday that Australia will be the host of an international
conference to halt the proliferation of chemical weapons.
   The meeting is tentatively scheduled for the latter half of the
year but Evans did not say how many countries might attend. A
government spokesman said ``all the major players are expected.''
   ``The momentum is there in terms of the will to get these
horrifying weapons out of ... business once and for all,'' Evans
said.
   He said the conference initiative followed talks with Baker about
how to build on the momentum generated by the Paris Conference on
Chemical Weapons attended by 149 countries in January.
   Kohl said he was hopeful chemical weapons could be withdrawn from
West Germany and Eastern Europe ahead of a 1992 deadline agreed upon
by both sides in 1986.
   He said he assumed that only technical matters had to be dealt
with in securing the early removal of chemical weapons from West
German soil.
   Horst Ehmke, a leader of the opposition Social Democratic Party,
questioned the U.S. plan.
   He said the removal of aging chemical weapons meant nothing if
they might someday be replaced by a new generation of binary
chemical weapons.
   ``The only event to celebrate will be an agreement in Geneva for
the world-wide destruction of chemical weapons,'' Ehmke said.
   Binary chemical weapons use two chemicals that when combined
produce a deadly gas.
   Government spokesman Friedhelm Ost said Monday that West Germany
agreed to allow the United States to deploy the new binary chemical
weapons if there should be a threat of war.
   Kohl, in a television interview, said he would oppose replacing
the aging weapons in West Germany in an era of declining tensions.
   ``We will do everything in our power to ensure that these weapons
disappear,'' he said. ``We don't need them.''
</TEXT>
