<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Iditarod     03-07 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iditarod,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Mushers Battle for Lead in Dog Sled Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susan Butcher, who won the last two
Iditarod dog-sled races with Rick Swenson on her heels, chased
Swenson on Tuesday as the two winningest mushers in race history
fought for the early lead in the 1,100-mile trek.
   Joe Runyan of Nenana actually was farthest along the trail early
Tuesday. But he had not yet taken his mandatory 24-hour rest stop,
while Swenson, Butcher and five others declared theirs at Rohn,
which is 266 miles from the start in Anchorage and 902 miles from
the finish line in Nome.
   Swenson, Butcher and DeeDee Jonrowe of Willow were expected to
start racing about noon AST Tuesday.
   Historically, Iditarod front-runners have faded badly by the time
they reached Nome, more than 1,100 miles from the start.
   In past years, Butcher, who has won the last three races, and
Swenson, the only four-time winner, have been content to bide their
time, making their moves much later in the race.
   But this year Swenson and Butcher went straight to the front. He
led Butcher into Rohn by 13 minutes.
   ``It just worked out that way,'' Swenson said of their quick
start. ``The thing is there was no one else that was going to go.''
   The two intense, outspoken competitors used to be neighbors in
Manley, but Swenson has moved to Two Rivers. Their rivalry has grown
to epic proportions throughout the state.
   ``I think I can beat her ... but she's got a good team, and she
might beat us all,'' Swenson said. He said his team this year is
better than the one that was runner-up to Butcher last year.
   On Monday, three people escaped serious injury when a
single-engine airplane chartered by an Anchorage TV station crashed
while covering the race.
   The field of mushers dwindled to 46 Monday night when 83-year-old
Norman Vaughan called it quits at Skwentna, just 151 miles into the
race. Two other mushers dropped out earlier at Big Lake, only 71
miles along the way.
   Inpired by a dog-sled relay of serum to Nome for a diphtheria
outbreak in 1925, the Iditarod was founded in 1973. The winner this
year is to get $50,000 of the $250,000 purse. The remainder will be
shared by the next 19 finishers.
   Most of the Iditarod mushers are from Alaska. Others are from
Montana, Minnesota, Wyoming, New York, France and Japan.
</TEXT>
