<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Lubbock     03-07 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Lubbock,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Disarray</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lubbock Friend Gives Bush Vote of Confidence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush should be given more time to
organize his administration and put together his policies and
programs, a longtime Bush friend from Texas said Tuesday.
   Robert W. Blake said he was pleased and surprised to hear that
Bush, at a news conference earlier in the day, had cited ``a fellow
from Lubbock'' as ``an objective spokesman'' on the Bush presidency.
   When asked at the outset of the news conference about
commentaries that his administration is in disarray in part because
of the protracted fight with the Senate over Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower, Bush said, ``My response is that
it's not adrift and there isn't malaise.''
   ``And I talked to a fellow from Lubbock, Texas, the other day,
which is the best phone call I've made,'' the president said. ``And
he said all the people in Lubbock think things are going just
great.''
   Blake, who is involved in the oil and gas industry, said in a
telephone interview from Lubbock that Bush had called Sunday.
   ``He's only had 45 days,'' Blake said Tuesday, saying he has
known Bush since 1951 and came to know him better during Bush's
ill-fated 1964 Senate campaign against Democrat Ralph Yarborough.
   ``All they do is criticize him,'' Blake said. ``But he's upbeat.
You will not find George Bush when he's down. He just called; we
talked back and forth, like friends do. I just feel like they ought
to give him a year to 18 months to get things done.''
   Blake, who served on Bush's national campaign finance committee
last year and has made several donations to Bush's campaigns, said
he knows no one ``would would work any harder than George Bush.''
   He said he told Bush not to worry about the Tower problem.
   ``I said, `You pick him, and then you have no more control over
it,''' Blake related.
</TEXT>
