<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Pelat     03-07 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Pelat,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friend of President Charged In Trading Scandal Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger-Patrice Pelat, a longtime friend of President
Francois Mitterrand, died Tuesday in a hospital three weeks after he
was charged in an insider trading scandal that has embarrassed
France's Socialist government. He was 70.
   Pelat was admitted to the American Hospital in the Paris suburb
of Neuilly on Feb. 27 suffering a pulmonary embolism and died of a
heart attack Tuesday, a spokeswoman said. She spoke on condition of
anonymity in keeping with hospital policy.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse said Mitterrand went
to the hospital after hearing of Pelat's death.
   Pelat and Mitterrand met in a German prisoner-of-war camp in 1940
and later fought together in the French Resistance.
   Over national television on Feb. 12, Mitterrand defended Pelat as
a man of courage and integrity, but said if Pelat were found guilty
of an offense, ``then in my role as president I would not be able to
maintain the same kind of friendship I have had with him for so
long.''
   Four days later, Pelat was charged with receiving insider
information that allowed him to buy shares of the U.S. company
Triangle Industries Inc. shortly before the French state-owned
aluminum manufacturer Picheney SA offered a much higher price last
year in a successful takeover.
   Pelat and his family sold their shares after the price soared,
making a profit of about $350,000.
   Five others also were charged by an investigating magsitrate with
receiving insider information or with insider trading. Either charge
carries the same maximum penalty of two years in prison and a fine
of up to four times the amount of illegal profits.
</TEXT>
