<FIRST>r w AM-Somalia-Prisoners     03-07 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Somalia-Prisoners,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ridge Says Somalia Grants Amnesty for Architect, 20 Other Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Somalia has granted amnesty to 21 people and
released them from prison, including an architect whose jailing had
prompted protests by lawmakers and his former American classmates,
Rep. Thomas Ridge, R-Pa., said Tuesday.
   Ridge released a copy of a letter dated Monday to Frank Light, of
the State Department, from Abdullahi A. Addou, Somali ambassador to
the United States.
   The letter said that the Somali president ``has granted amnesty
to the following people and they are free from prison,'' and listed
21 prisoners, including Sulieman Nuh Ali. Ali's case has been
investigated by Amnesty International, the London-based human rights
group that had classified him as a ``prisoner of conscience.''
   According to Ridge, Ali was held without charges since 1982 and
then was found guilty of treason last year.
   Ali, 45, attended Pennsylvania's Allegheny College in the
mid-1960s before transferring to Howard University and earning a
degree in architecture and urban planning.
   He took a job with the Somalia Ministry of Public Works building
low-cost housing for workers, then went into business for himself.
   A former classmate helped launch a student petition drive at the
Pennsylvania school, and 28 House and Senate members recently sent a
telegram of protest to the Somali president.
