<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1851EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     03-07 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Banker Says He will be Free in 24-48 Hours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Lebanese banker who was
reported to have been kidnapped called his office Tuesday and said
he would return within 48 hours.
   Roger Tamraz told his Paris office: ``Tell everyone not to panic.
It's finished now. I will be with you in 24 to 48 hours,'' a
colleague said.
   The colleague, who spoke by telephone from Paris on condition of
anonymity, said Tamraz did not disclose his location.
   On Monday, another associate said Tamraz had been kidnapped Feb.
19 and was being held for ransom. He said he believed those holding
Tamraz were acting for people who suffered losses in the recent
collapse of Lebanon's second-largest bank, Bank Al-Mashrek, which
Tamraz headed until December.
   Bank Al-Mashrek is involved in a liquidity crisis with several
subsidiaries, including banks in Switzerland, France, Jordan and
Qatar.
   The colleague in Paris said Tamraz, 48, asked him to tell the
press that he had been ``in retreat to prepare my case.''
   The Beirut daily As-Safir reported Tuesday that Tamraz had called
to say he was ``not the victim of a kidnap operation.''
   Asked Tuesday about the report, the associate said: ``What does
one mean by kidnap? He is a guest but he is not free to move before
he settles certain accounts.''
   The associate said Tamraz was seized when he went to a meeting in
Chtaura, a town in Lebanon's eastern Bekaa Valley Feb. 19.
   He said a $1.5 million payment was made several days later after
Tamraz contacted family and friends.
   Tamraz was not released after the first payment and a second
payment was demended, the associate said.
   Tamraz, a Maronite Catholic, was educated at Cambridge University
in England and at the Harvard Business School.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
