<FIRST>u i AM-Irish 1stLd-Writethru a0648 03-07 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed in Shooting in Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE identities and police report of
stolen car. Pick up 9th pvs, `Also on...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked gunmen killed three men
Tuesday as they chatted at a village gas station and then escaped in
a car that had been stolen about 15 minutes before the attack,
police reported.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army asserted responsility and in a
statment to the local news media claimed the service station was a
stronghold of the Ulster Volunteer Force, a Protestant paramilitary
group that also is banned.
   Police said the three men were slain in Coagh, 50 miles west of
Belfast, and none had any connection with Northern Ireland's
security forces.
   The victims were identified by local residents as Leslie Dallas,
in his early 40s and owner of the station; Ernest Rankin, 72, who
was retired, and Austin Nelson, in his 60s, a retired truck driver
and violin maker who appeared on a television program Monday to
discuss music in Northern Ireland, a British province.
   During the program Nelson said, ``Whenever I pass on _ hopefully
not for a while yet _ nobody will remember Austin Nelson.''
   Police said two of the men were killed instantly and the third
died on his way to a hospital.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said children
leaving a school bus saw the shootings and reported the killers
cheered as they drove away.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force,
issued a statement saying, ``The murders occurred at the corner
where local people congregate to chat. The brutality of these
murders and their open sectarianism must be condemned.''
   Adrian Ringland, the chief superintendent of the local RUC unit,
told Britain's Independent Television News: ``This is total anarchy
... when in a quiet village in the middle of Tyrone you get a
situation where people come in with high-powered rifles and just
spray bullets indiscriminately around a business premises in the
village _ absolute horror.''
   The Rev. William McCrea, a Protestant minister and a member of
Parliament from the area, visited the scene and said: ``The gunmen
opened fire from a passing car. They came down the street, opened up
on the garage and brutally did to death these men.''
   Denis Haughey, the local representative for the Social Democratic
and Labor Party, the province's largest Roman Catholic party, called
the killings ``a foul and brutal act.''
   Police said the car used by the killers was stolen about 15
minutes before the shootings by two armed men a few miles away in
the Catholic stronghold of Ballinderry near Ardboe.
   The Ulster Volunteer Force claimed responsibility last month for
killing John Joe Davey, a town councilor in the area for Sinn Fein,
the legal political wing of the predominantly Catholic IRA.
   Also on Tuesday police announced they discovered a cache of guns,
ammunition and Czechoslovak-made Semtex explosives buried in a wood
in northern England, near the seaside town of Scarborough where
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher is to attend a conference of her
Conservative Party in April.
   Semtex is often used for IRA bombings. In 1984, Mrs. Thatcher
narrowly escaped injury when an IRA bomb exploded in the hotel where
she was staying for a party conference in Brighton, southern
England. Five people died in the blast.
   More than 2,720 people have been slain in Northern Ireland in
nearly 20 years of political and sectarian conflict, 15 of them this
year.
   The IRA is fighting to unite the province, where Protestants
outnumber Catholics 3-2, with the mainly Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
