<FIRST>r a AM-Lubbock-Everytown     03-07 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lubbock-Everytown,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lubbock's Locals Says Bush Is Doing Just Swell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This stands for AM-Bush-Lubbock listed on the digest.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Disarray, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city took some of the wind out of
Peoria, Ill.'s perennial bluster of being Everytown U.S.A. when
President Bush said the people of Lubbock think he's doing a fine
job.
   When reporters questioned Bush Tuesday about criticism that his
administration was adrift, he replied:
   ``I talked to a fellow from Lubbock, Texas, the other day which
was the best phone call I've made. And he said, `All the people in
Lubbock think things are going just great.'''
   So what do Lubbockites really think about that Texan in the White
House?
   ``I really haven't been paying that much attention,'' said
Shirley Hubbard, a convenience store clerk.
   ``They're (Congress) giving him a hard time about (John) Tower,
but I say stick with it,'' said retiree William Berns. ``He knows
what he's doing.''
   While the majority of people questioned about Bush by a reporter
outside the post office approved of his leadership thus far, most
wouldn't give their names.
   ``He's a Texan and he understands us,'' said one man.
   Matt Malouf, who wrote a letter to the Lubbock Avalanche-Journal
last week, defended Bush and blasted the Senate for its handling of
Tower's confirmation as defense secretary: ``I would rather be ruled
by the first 100 names in the Lubbock phone book than these clowns
who now reign in the Senate.''
   In choosing Lubbock as his example of middle America, Bush picked
an easy sell.
   This city on the South Plains has a population of 186,400 and
more than 150 churches, many of them large and conservative.
Residents of Lubbock County gave the GOP ticket 69 percent of the
vote in November.
   Here, the agrigulture-based economy rises or falls on the
strength of the annual cotton crop. Two consecutive strong harvests
gave this city the lowest unemployment rate in the state at 5.2
percent.
   Lubbock is also the home of one of Bush's dearest friends,
independent oil investor Robert W. Blake, who was the caller Bush
was referring to when he said Lubbockites were behind him.
   Blake said Tuesday he was surprised and pleased to hear Bush
citing him as ``an objective spokesman'' on the Bush presidency. The
two had spoken on Sunday.
   ``He's only had 45 days,'' Blake said, saying he has known Bush
since 1951 and got to know him better during Bush's unsuccessful
1964 Senate campaign against Democrat Ralph Yarborough.
   ``All they do is criticize him,'' Blake said. ``But he's upbeat.
You will not find George Bush when he's down. He just called, we
talked back and forth, like friends do. I just feel like they ought
to give him a year to 18 months to get things done.''
   Lubbock Mayor B.C. ``Peck'' McMinn said people here are ``pretty
representative of how the run-of-the-mill people feel across the
country. Not the political hype or anything, but the rock-solid
thinkers are pretty representative of how the situation is going.''
</TEXT>
