<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Sullivan     03-07 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Sees No Reason to Change Catastrophic Care Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan told Congress on Tuesday that he sees no reason to change
the new catastrophic care program financed by a surtax on elderly
Americans.
   ``We're aware of a number of concerns that have been expressed
(about the financing provision) but ... we are also concerned about
the many examples of our elderly citizens being wiped out
financially by the tremendous costs of illness,'' Sullivan said.
   ``We feel that because this legislation has just been enacted we
don't have much experience with it yet. We'd like to follow this and
see if adjustments need to be made,'' he told the House Ways and
Means Committee.
   Leaders in the House and Senate also have been generally
unsympathetic to the complaints from senior citizens who oppose the
financing provision of the program, which helps the elderly and
disabled bear the cost of illness that otherwise would threaten
their financial stability.
   For Medicare-eligible Americans _ those who are over 65 or
disabled _ whose incomes are high enough that they pay at least $150
a year in federal income taxes, the surtax is 15 percent of their
income tax this year. Next year it is 25 percent and it could rise
by as much as 1 percentage point a year after that.
   Sullivan's testimony to the House panel was his first before a
congressional committee since his confirmation to the Bush Cabinet
by the Senate last week.
   ``We welcome you to the reality of budget deficits,'' said Rep.
Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the committee. ``You'll find
us as agreeable as the budget permits.''
   The secretary was asked many of the same questions he had been
asked at his confirmation hearing before the Senate Finance
Committee and a subsequent hearing before the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee. At those hearings, he deferred on many of the
budget questions that were raised, saying he had not participated in
detailed budget discussions with Bush administration officials.
   Rostenkowski said President Bush's proposal to reduce Medicare
spending in fiscal 1990 by $5 billion is unacceptable and the
effects of the deficit-reducing Gramm-Rudman law are preferable. If
Gramm-Rudman cuts were made, Medicare spending in 1990 would be
reduced by about $2 billion.
   Sullivan, however, said the across-the-board cuts of the
Gramm-Rudman law would ``tie our hands to utilize funds that are
available in the most productive way.''
   The secretary also assured the panel that the administration's
proposed cutbacks _ chiefly freezing and scaling back increases in
payments to hospitals and physicians _ were designed not to affect
benefit levels.
</TEXT>
