<DOCNO> AP890307-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-07 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the Cathedral of Chartres' soaring Gothic
vaults to Picasso's weightless Desmoiselles d'Avignon, works of art
have long been associated with flight.
   Now, Boston artist Lowry Burgess' sculpture ``Boundless
Aperture'' is scheduled to take off with the space shuttle Discovery
and give art a lift, quite literally, out of this world.
   The 7-pound cubic sculpture, part of the artist's 20-year effort
to stretch the human imagination, is the nation's first and possibly
last interstellar art offering.
   ``If any art went up previously it was done without our knowledge
and we certainly don't approve of it,'' said Tony Maull, who was
staff director for the NASA committee that approved Burgess's work
for flight. ``And there is no intention to send any other objects up
at this time.''
   Burgess conceived his ``Boundless Aperture'' sculpture more than
two decades ago as part of a larger project entitled ``The Quiet
Axis,'' that includes one sculpture embedded in the Pacific Ocean
floor off Easter Island and another placed in the Hindu Kush
mountains in central Afghanistan.
   ``Boundless Aperture'' consists of a 6-inch cube inside of which
floats another cube bearing colorful holographic plates inscribed
with poetry. On its return it will be placed inside a rock
outcropping on the DeCordova Museum's grounds in Lincoln, Mass.
   The artist allows that his latest sculpture is fairly esoteric,
but insists that anyone can appreciate space art.
   ``There are more art enthusiasts out there than the people at the
museums,'' he said. ``A lot of people are very eager to see a
cultural dimension to the space effort. It's humanizing.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big Stan is losing his marbles.
   Big Stan is the 80-story, marble-sheathed headquarters of Amoco
Corp., nicknamed back when the company was known as Standard Oil of
Indiana. At 1,136 feet, it is the tallest marble-faced building in
the world.
   But not for long.
   Amoco officials say Big Stan's 43,000 marble panels are coming
loose and must go.
   The panels will be replaced with granite during a facelift that
begins next month and could cost up to $80 million before its
completion in three years, said Shelby C. Pierce, manager of
engineering for Amoco.
   ``We decided to bite the bullet rather than continue forever on a
maintenance program,'' Pierce said Monday of the replacement
project. ``We decided to get it over with.''
   Many Chicago artists and architects are ready for the change.
   ``Carrara marble, which is what's on the building, is
beautiful,'' says architect Walter Netsch. ``Michelangelo used it.
But Michelangelo didn't leave his work outside.''
   The used marble is too weak for buildings and too warped for
countertops. Until a buyer is found, the marble will be piled up
outside the headquarters, said Pierce.
   ``This granite is very strong and stable,'' he said. ``I wanted
to make sure that 15 years from now someone doesn't have to go
through what I'm going through.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
