<FIRST>u i AM-Bolivia-US-Drugs     03-07 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia-US-Drugs,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Gives Conditions for Using US Soldiers in Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. soldiers will be used against the
narcotics trade in drug-producing nations only in support roles and
at the request of those countries, U.S. Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh said Tuesday.
   Thornburgh commented near the end of a visit to Bolivia during
which he met with government officials, including President Victor
Paz Estenssoro, and addressed a conference on drug abuse.
   ``It is important to reaffirm this administration's position with
regard to the use of military forces outside the United States,'' he
told a news conference.
   ``These forces will never be mobilized except at the request of
the host country and only in ways that would provide logistical and
law enforcement support to these countries.''
   About 50 U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency, border patrol, Coast Guard
and military training and advisory personnel now are assigned to
Bolivia in those capacities.
   The United States sent 195 soldiers to Bolivia for three months
in 1986 to provide logistical support for raids on labs that process
coca leaves, the basis of cocaine.
   Since the soldiers left, Washington has increased its support to
Bolivia's anti-drug campaign, training and equipping 600 narcotics
police permanently assigned to coca-producing regions.
   Thornburgh is visiting Bolivia, Peru and Colombia to meet with
leaders about how to stem the flow of drugs. Traveling with him is
Jack Lawn, chief of the Drug Enforcement Administration.
   In his speech to a meeting of the U.N. Fund for Drug Abuse and
Control in La Paz, the attorney general said Bolivia's
``accomplishments in securing democratic principles and overseeing
an important economic recovery have earned President Paz Estenssoro
great acclaim in the United States.''
   He said the Bush administration is preparing a strategy against
drug abuse and production.
   ``We recognize the relationship between demand and consumption of
drugs is equally important as interdiction and crop reduction,''
Thornburgh declared.
   The U.S. Embassy said $15 million had been budgeted for drug
interdiction in Bolivia for fiscal 1989 but it had been cut to $9.5
million.
   This impoverished nation of 7 million people produces the raw
material for at least one-third of the cocaine that reaches U.S. And
European markets, theDEA says.
   At least 350,000 Bolivians make their livings growing coca
leaves. The leaves are processed into cocaine paste, which is
refined into cocaine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
