<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Venezuela     03-07 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Venezuela,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spain Arranges $350 Million Loan To Venezuela</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bank of Spain on Tuesday approved a $35O
million loan to provide Venezuela with temporary economic relief
after rioting over austerity measures killed at least 300 people
there last week.
   The bank said in a statement that it arranged an immediate loan
of $200 million with the Central Bank of Venezuela to be be paid off
by the end of the year once Venezuela begins to receive emergency
financing from the International Monetary Fund.
   The Bank of Spain will make available $150 million more after
Venezuela and the IMF sign an economic adjustment program.
   The announcement, which gave no further details, had been
expected since Spain announced March 3 that a bridge loan was being
put together.
   Venezuela's reserves are depleted as a result of the country's
$33 billion foreign debt, the fourth-largest in Latin America.
   Venezuela, a founding member of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, saw its fortunes sag greatly after oil prices
plunged in 1981.
</TEXT>
