<FIRST>r a AM-Thrift-Painting     03-07 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thrift-Painting,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money-Losing Thrift Ordered to Sell $12 Million Rubens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A savings and loan which lost $10 million lost
quarter has been ordered by the state to sell a $12 million painting
bought as office ``furniture'' and hung in the chairman's home.
   CenTrust Savings Bank recently bought ``Portrait of a Man as
Mars,'' by Flemish master Peter Paul Rubens from Sotheby's auction
house, paying a $1.2 million commission in addition to the $12
million purchase price.
   In a March 3 letter, the Florida Office of Comptroller expressed
its displeasure with the purchase and ordered the Miami-based bank
to sell the painting within 30 days.
   The state has not yet heard what CenTrust plans to do about the
order, Wendy Mitchler, a spokeswoman in the thrift supervising
office in Tallahassee, said Tuesday.
   However, she said it was rare for savings institutions to oppose
the comptroller because the office supervises all state-chartered
thrifts.
   Bank Chairman David Paul said neither he nor his thrift did
anything wrong, and called the dispute a ``tempest in a teapot.''
   Alex Hager, the chief of the thrift supervision office, said that
for the bank to hold the masterpiece ``creates the likelihood of an
abnormal risk or loss,'' and called the purchase ``inherently
speculative.''
   Hager's letter said the comptroller's office did not understand
how CenTrust, which has lost money for the past two quarters, could
justify buying the painting.
   He questioned why Paul, who is active in Miami's art circles, was
keeping the painting in his home.
   ``Your letter indicates that the painting, although currently
displayed in your personal residence, was acquired as `furniture and
fixtures of CenTrust and is reflected on the balance sheet as an
asset of the institution,''' Hager wrote.
   Paul said the Rubens is in his home only because new executive
offices in CenTrust Towers have not yet been completed.
   He said the purchase was part of a wise pattern of investing,
noting that the average painting has appreciated 15 percent a year
recently.
   CenTrust, which has assets of $10.2 billion and 68 offices around
Florida, valued its entire art collection at about $20 million. The
comptroller's office has a higher estimate of $30 million.
   ``We have been very careful to put together, with the help of the
curator of Sotheby's, a museum-quality art collection,'' Paul said.
``We're no different than the major banks.''
</TEXT>
