<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Mongolia     03-07 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Mongolia,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Begin Troop Withdrawal from Mongolia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has begun withdrawing
three-quarters of its troops from Mongolia as promised, including
the entire Soviet air force there, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Gennady I. Gerasimov announced Tuesday.
   He did not tell reporters when the pullout would be completed or
how many troops were involved.
   Mongolia lies between China and the Soviet Union. Beijing says
removal of Soviet troops from the region is a necessary step to
improving relations between the two communist giants. President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev is to travel to Beijing on May 15 for the first
Chinese-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   Gorbachev announced the withdrawals from Mongolia on Jan. 18.
   Moscow began withdrawing its troops from Mongolia in 1987, but
did not say how many were there. Western analysts estimated the size
of the Soviet force at 40,000 to 60,000 troops before withdrawals.
   The Soviet Union also is withdrawing troops from Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
