<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Kossman     03-07 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Kossman,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jacob Kossman, Lawyer For Bruno, Hoffa, Dead at 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacob Kossman, a lawyer regarded by court
friends as a legal genius whose list of clients included prominent
mob figures Angelo Bruno and Albert Anastasia, has died at age 79.
   Kossman died Sunday at the Fox Chase Cancer Center.
   Among those he represented were James Hoffa, the late president
of the Teamsters Union; Anastasia, the former head of what was known
as Murder Inc.; and Bruno, the Philadelphia mob boss who dined with
Kossman the night Bruno was gunned down in front of his home.
   Kossman ``was the Albert Einstein of the courtroom,'' said
Jeffrey Miller, a former assistant U.S. attorney who rented office
space from the lawyer. ``He didn't dress like a lawyer, didn't talk
down to juries.''
   Friends said Kossman never argued about the innocence of his
clients, but he insisted they were entitled to the best defense
possible under the Constitution.
   ``If he didn't win his verdict with the jury, he'd win it on
appeal,'' said Carmen Nasuti, a former assistant U.S. attorney who
worked against Kossman as a prosecutor and later with him as a
defense attorney.
   ``He had a way of analyzing things that was phenomenal,'' said
Nasuti. ``His mind could analyze through the toughest problem.''
   Survivors include his wife, Dr. Estelle Gold; a stepdaughter and
stepson, and two sisters.
</TEXT>
