<DOCNO> AP890307-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Katyn     03-07 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Katyn,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokesman Says Evidence `Indicates' Soviets Killed Polish Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has concluded that
``everything indicates'' that more than 4,000 Polish army officers
massacred at Katyn were killed not by the Nazis but by Soviet secret
police, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   Chief government spokesman Jerzy Urban said, however, the
evidence is circumstantial, and Poland continues to press for speed
in the Soviet review of one of the most emotional blank spots in
Soviet-Polish history.
   It was the strongest government statement yet pointing to Soviet
culpability, although an official newspaper last month published a
wartime Polish Red Cross report indicating the officers were killed
on Soviet territory well before the 1941 Nazi invasion of the Soviet
Union.
   Urban has said the inscription on a monument in Warsaw blaming
the Nazis will be changed.
   ``We think that everything indicates that the crime was committed
by the Stalinist NKVD,'' the secret police force that preceded the
KGB, Urban said.
   ``The Soviet historians are analyzing this material and are right
to state that it's only circumstantial evidence.''
   The officers had been deported to the Soviet Union. Hitler's army
uncovered their bodies in spring 1943 in the Katyn forest, 12 miles
west of Smolensk in the western Soviet Union.
   Official Soviet and Polish histories long held the officers were
killed by the Nazis in 1941, but many Poles and Western historians
blamed the Soviets.
   Poland and the Soviet Union formed a joint commission in 1987 to
consider the evidence on Katyn and other historical questions. The
Polish side has submitted its material and indications have emerged
of growing impatience with the Soviet review.
   Urban said Poland understands the Soviets want to review material
in their own archives but ``we are for speeding up the process of
looking for them.''
   Poland was attacked first by the Nazis from the west and then
from the east by the Soviet Union in September 1939. Many Poles and
Western historians say the Soviets killed the Polish officers in the
spring of 1940, when the Soviet Union and Nazi Germany were still
observing a non-aggression pact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
