<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-MentalIllness     03-07 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Mental Illness,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vereen, Wynette, Landers Honored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Ben Vereen, honored Tuesday with
columnist Ann Landers and country music singer Tammy Wynette,
pledged to continue the fight ``to free America from its chains of
drugs and mental illness.''
   The three celebrities were honored by mental health groups for
their efforts to build public awareness on the issues of mental
illness and addictions and remove the social stigma from these
disorders.
   ``I'm not proud of the fact that I once had a drug problem, but I
am proud I did something about it,'' Ms. Wynette, who overcame
dependency on prescription drugs, said at an awards reception on
Capitol Hill.
   Vereen, a national spokesman for the campaign for ``A Drug Free
America,'' said programs must use education to reach parents, school
leaders and teachers about how to spot mental illnesses such as
depression that can lead to drug abuse. Then, they must reach out
with compassion to those afflicted.
   ``What we have to do is ... open our arms and say we know how
what you're feeling and tell them there are people who care,''
Vereen said.
   Ms. Landers urged: ``Let's be sympathetic, let's be kind, let's
be caring and let's recognize the burden these people who have
mental illness are carrying. I can't tell you how much pain, how
much suffering is out there.''
   The ``From Shame to Hope'' awards were co-sponsored by the Mental
Health Liaison Group, the Alcohol and Drug Problems Association of
North America and the Mental Illness Research Advocacy Coalition _
Learning and Educating.
   The groups stressed the need for more information on mental
illnesses and drug and alcohol addictions, and praised the Alcohol,
Drug Abuse and Mental Illness Administration, which leads the
federal government's research efforts on mental and addictive
disorders.
</TEXT>
