<FIRST>u a AM-CollegeDesegregation 1stLd-Writethru a0597 03-07 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-College Desegregation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing Put Off While Lawyers Talk Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with hearing postponed indefinitely;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `Thomas Todd ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to Gov. Buddy Roemer raised hopes
Tuesday for a compromise in a 15-year-old federal desegregation
lawsuit against Louisiana's colleges and universities.
   The court-appointed special master overseeing the integration
effort had scheduled a morning hearing but called off the session
after meeting with lawyers. Attorneys were to meet with him
Wednesday in private, a secretary said.
   John Kennedy, counsel to Roemer, and state Sen. William
Jefferson, attorney for the Southern University System, said earlier
Tuesday that lawyers in the case were getting closer to a
settlement. But neither would give details or predict that a
settlement would be reached.
   Nor could they be reached later for comment. Calls to their
offices and hotels were not returned.
   Asked about speculation that a proposed settlement had been drawn
up, John Keller, chairman of the Board of Regents, said, ``I would
be pretty sure they've gotten pretty far. But not sure they have
gotten that far.''
   Thomas Todd, a lawyer representing Grambling State University
alumni, said the delay did not mean that settlement was imminent.
   ``There's nothing to be read into this. Negotiations are always
continuing. They never stop. But there are a lot of technical things
that have got to be done in conjunction with a hearing like this,''
said Todd. ``One of those is negotiation.''
   The U.S. Justice Department filed the lawsuit against the
Lousiana system in 1974.
   Louisiana, the Justice Department, Southern University and the
Grambling State University Alumni Association all have proposals
before special master Paul Verkuil, appointed by a three-judge
federal panel to supervise desegregation of Louisiana's 13 state
universities and six two-year colleges.
   Grambling, as one of the nine schools run by the Board of
Trustees for State Colleges and Universities, backs the state's
plan. But its alumni association, like Southern, objects to what it
sees as moves that would eliminate traditionally black schools and
deprive underprivileged black youngsters of the help they need to
adapt to college life and courses.
   Those moves include a keystone of the state's plan: consolidating
the boards that govern Southern, the Louisiana State University
system and nine regional colleges _ and the board that oversees
those three boards _ into one ``superboard.''
   Roemer said he would not budge on the superboard issue but might
accept the establishment of weaker, advisory boards without the
power to hire, fire or set budgets.
   The state's plan also calls for a statewide community college
system, which Southern and the Grambling alumni contend would keep
many blacks from ever making it into a four-year university.
   The Justice, Southern and Grambling alumni plans depend heavily
on moving programs from predominantly white schools to schools that
are predominantly black, an arrangement Kennedy says failed in other
states that tried it.
   Verkuil is president of the College of William &amp; Mary in Virginia
and a former dean of Tulane University's law school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
