<FIRST>u w AM-Airlines-Smoking     03-07 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airlines-Smoking,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0807 to fix category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senators Propose Permanent Airline Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of senators introduced legislation
Tuesday to permanently ban cigarette smoking on all domestic
flights, a bill that immediately received the endorsement of Surgeon
General C. Everett Koop.
   The measure would expand the current prohibition against smoking,
which covers flights of two hours or less and is due to expire in
April 1990.
   ``The time has come to protect the health and safety of all
airline passengers,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., who
co-sponsored the bill with Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   At the senators' news conference to announce the proposal, Koop
said such a ban is ``long overdue.''
   He cited a recent study by the National Cancer Institute which
found that passengers in non-smoking sections of airliners had
similar levels of nicotine in their saliva and urine to travelers in
smoking areas.
   The bill would leave intact the $1,000 fine that can be levied
against those violating the smoking ban, and the $2,000 penalty for
people caught tampering with smoke detectors in airline restrooms.
</TEXT>
