<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Teachers 1stLd-Writethru a0783 03-07 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Teachers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0783,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Teachers March, Millions Of Students Stay Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 3rd pvs, `An estimated...' UPDATING with
government condemning strike. Picks up 4th pvs, `Virtually all...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident teachers staged another one-day
walkout Tuesday, and the government news agency Notimex said about 5
million children were affected and stayed home from school.
   It was the third walkout in a month by the dissidents, who are
demanding pay increases and the removal of the head of the National
Teachers Union, Carlos Jongitud Barrios.
   An estimated 50,000 teachers joined a march in downtown Mexico
City that snarled traffic.
   The government condemned the strike late Tuesday in a statement
released by the Education Department, saying the walkouts
``constitute illegal actions that are contrary to the public
interest.''
   ``The damage suffered by students is irreversible and no one has
the right to injure youth,'' it added.
   The government offered to consider teachers' grievances through
dialogue.
   Virtually all public schools in Mexico City were closed. Notimex
reported scattered walkouts at schools nationwide, with dissident
teachers from at least 17 states participating in the march in the
capital. Mexico has 32 states and the federal district of Mexico
City.
   Many of the teachers in the march had pay stubs pinned to their
clothing. Teachers make an average $170 a month, and the dissidents
are seeking a 100 per cent pay raise. Mexico's minimum monthly wage
is about $75.
   ``We barely earn more than common laborers, those who sweep
floors, but we have to have a lot more education'' secondary-school
teacher Ricardo Pena told The Associated Press.
   Marching were members of the National Schoolteachers Coordinate,
a faction opposed to the National Teachers Union, which represents
about 1.2 million teachers and education workers.
   The dissidents claim Jongitud has used his 17 years as union
leader to gain power and wealth while ignoring the plight of the
teachers.
   ``A E I O U! Out With Jongitud!'' the marchers chanted .
   One large banner showed Jongitud riding a stick horse labeled
``PRI,'' the initials of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, which counts on organized labor as one of it strongest
supporters.
   Jongitud is closely allied with the PRI and is now the senator
from San Luis Potosi state.
   The dissidents claim leaders of the national union sell teaching
jobs for about $2,100 each.
   The government does not recognize the National Schoolteachers
Coordinate.
</TEXT>
