<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal     03-07 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Government Official Arrested In Recruit Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors on Wednesday arrested a former vice
labor minister on charges of bribery in connection with a widening
stock-profiteering scandal involving top government leaders.
   Takashi Kato, 58, became the highest-ranking public official to
be arrested in the unfolding scandal after Shigeru Kano, former head
of the Labor Ministry's employment service division, who was taken
in Feb. 17.
   Also Wednesday, Masao Tatsumi, former executive of Recruit Co.,
an employment-information conglomerate, was apprehended by
prosecutors on charges of bribing Kato. That brought to 11 the total
number of scandal-related arrests to date.
   Two Recruit officials who were arrested Feb. 15 were freed
Tuesday by the Tokyo District Prosecutor's Office. The office has
yet to decide whether they will be indicted.
   Recruit is at the center of the scandal in which a select number
of individuals, particularly politicians, were offered the
opportunity to purchase bargain-priced shares of a real estate
subsidiary up until September 1986.
   When the shares were offered for over-the-counter trading in
October 1986, their value rose substantially and holders were able
to earn hefty profits.
   Kato's arrest had been expected for weeks. Prosecutors had been
questioning him over the past few days over his ties to Recruit.
   Kato allegedly purchased 3,000 unlisted shares in a
Recruit-Cosmos subsidiary in September 1986 and earned a windfall of
about $53,000 a month later, Kyodo News Service quoted prosecutors
as saying.
   The former vice labor minister, who retired voluntarily in
January 1988, has been accused of providing special favors to
Recruit during his 1983-85 tenure as director general of the
ministry's Employment Services Bureau, Kyodo said.
   On Monday, Higashi Shinto, former head of Japan's largest
corporation, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, was arrested on charges
of accepting bribes from Recruit.
   The Recruit scandal has severely damaged the reputation of Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, whose support rating has dwindled to 21.3
percent in the latest poll by the mass circulation daily Yomiuri
Shimbun.
   Three Cabinet ministers resigned after reports that they directly
or indirectly purchased Recruit stock. Takeshita has denied personal
involvement in the scandal but has acknowledged his own aide bought
2,000 shares of Recruit stock.
</TEXT>
