<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-WonderfulDogs ADV08   03-07 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Wonderful Dogs, ADV 08,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, March 8, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Wonderful Dogs' on National Geographic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's probably the first time during the course of
an interview that the star has been told, ``Get out of the trash!''
   No, the star is not Geraldo Rivera. She is Cinnamon, a red
Doberman pinscher, a rescue dog whose job it is to search through
forests, lakes or earthquake rubble to find people.
   ``The only thing Cinnamon loves more than people is doughnuts,''
notes Cinnamon's owner and trainer, Shirley Hammond, explaining why
Cinnamon keeps dipping her nose into the conference room trash can
seeking the discarded remains of a pastry.
   Cinnamon is one of the dogs taken to Mexico City to help find
victims buried beneath the massive 1985 earthquake.
   And she is among the remarkable working dogs featured in the
National Geographic special, ``Those Wonderful Dogs,'' airing
tonight on PBS.
   ``Those Wonderful Dogs'' is a fascinating and lovingly
photographed film that will please dog-lovers enormously but doesn't
get overly sentimental. It was written and produced by Barbara
Jampel. Richard Kiley provides the narration. The special is
dedicated to the memory of film editor John Dabney, who did such an
excellent job of putting it all together.
   Other dogs featured in the special include sheepdogs, combat
dogs, dogs who assist the disabled and sled dogs.
   The special ranged as far as New Zealand to observe a team of 10
sheepdogs who help one couple manage a huge, remote sheep farm.
``Without the dogs,'' says farmer Grant Calder, ``we'd be broke in
12 months.'' He observes that his dogs are willing to work till they
drop, and all they seek in return is approval from their master.
   There are two different kinds of sheepdogs, the ones who nip at
the heels of the sheep and ``headers,'' who control the sheep from
in front by staring into their eyes. Once the sheep are in the pens,
the dogs run across the backs of the packed herd to move them along.
   The special moves on to Alaska, where Susan Butcher takes the
filmmakers through the training regimen that has produced her
champion sled teams, regular winners of the 1,100-mile Iditarod sled
race.
   One of the most touching segments is set in a more mundane
environment, a typical American home, where lives 17-year-old Mike
Knowlton, a victim of spina bifida who uses a wheelchair, and his
yellow Labrador retriever, Zest.
   Zest is a product of California-based Canine Companions for
Independence. Similar to a Seeing Eye dog, she helps her owner by
pulling his wheelchair, turning off light switches, picking up
dropped objects _ and serving as an ice-breaker. Mike says he used
to be too shy to approach other students at his school, but now they
come up to him to pet the dog.
   If you grew up on ``Lassie,'' Hammond will disappoint you when
she insists that rescue dogs like Cinnamon aren't aware that they
are saving people's lives, but are only playing a hide-and-seek game.
   Hammond is a founder of the California Rescue Dogs Association,
whose members found dozens of survivors beneath the rubble of the
Mexico earthquake. Cinnamon herself was responsible for finding
eight people, Hammond says.
   Cinnamon also searches for people who have wandered into
wilderness areas and become lost. She even locates drowning victims,
riding in a boat and detecting the gases emitted by a body beneath
the water.
   Maybe Cinnamon doesn't know she's saving lives, but she does have
a different signal when she finds a live person _ ``she wags her
behind'' _ than the more subdued scratching at the surface when she
finds a dead person.
   Rescue dogs have to be trained to ignore their natural instinct
to jump off unstable surfaces. They are taught to walk a horizontal
ladder so they become more aware of the position of their hind feet.
   Rescue dogs are selected for their love of all people. Hammond
said many dogs will search all day for their beloved owner, but
don't care about strangers. Hammond said she picked Cinnamon, now
8{, out of litter of pups because she was the one most eager for
human contact. Sure enough, though she had only just met her
``interviewer,'' she happily administered a face-washing.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   YOUR MOTHER WEARS COMBAT BOOTS _ NBC hopes these are not fighting
words, simply the title of a new comedy movie to air later this
season. Barbara Eden stars as an overly protective mother who
follows her son into airborne training with the U.S. Army. It was
filmed in part at the U.S. Army Infantry Center at Fort Benning, Ga.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, March 8</NOTE>
