<FIRST>s a BC-NoChildren Adv12   03-07 1188</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-No Children, Adv 12,1220</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Landmark Housing Measure Spurs Debate, Bodes Wide-ranging Effects</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note that law goes into effect Sunday, March 12.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing discrimination against families with
children is illegal starting Sunday, but no-kids communities are
fighting to protect their lifestyles even as experts laud the new
law for addressing a national crisis.
   ``There will be resistance (and) claims of reverse
discrimination, but the fact of the matter is Congress has decided
families with children have a great need for housing and this law is
designed to help them,'' said Jim Morales, staff attorney for the
San Francisco-based National Center for Youth Law.
   A 1980 Department of Housing and Urban Development study found
that 75 percent of rental units nationwide banned or restricted
children. Other surveys found 90 percent of apartment complexes in
some communities closed to children.
   ``We just found an epidemic of discrimination against families
with children all over the United States. It was really tragic,''
said U.S. Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., a co-sponsor of the Fair
Housing Amendments Act of 1988 signed into law by President Reagan
in September.
   The act bans discrimination against families with children, with
some exemptions, and adds the handicapped to housing law prohibiting
discrimination on the basis of sex, religion, national origin, color
and race.
   ``Blatant and legal cases of discrimination against families with
children ... (are) happening all over the country and in all types
of communities,'' said Lisa Mihaly of the Washington-based
Children's Defense Fund.
   _In Zephyrhills, Fla., Beverly and Thomas Elmer were forced in
January to evict their 14-year-old daughter Staci rather than go to
jail for contempt of court in a dispute over deed restrictions. She
can visit their mobile home in a subdivision of 17 families north of
Tampa, but must live with a married brother until she turns 15 next
month. Pets are allowed, but not children under 15.
   ``I'm not surprised. The Constitution isn't made for kids,''
Staci said.
   _In Margate, Fla., Jamie Swartz, 9, was threatened with eviction
when she moved in with her father and stepmother after her mother
died. After months of uncertainty, Jamie got a reprieve in January
when the condominium board decided not to take action while the new
federal housing act was researched.
   _A Portland, Ore., couple were forced to send their 3-year-old
son to live with friends because of a dispute with neighbors at
apartments that had been converted into condominiums with a
no-children rule.
   ``Of course we couldn't just banish him into a black hole'' and
he returned for clothes and toys, said his mother, Linda Benyahich.
After neighbors saw him she got a call from the board's lawyer, who
said if he came again ``for any reason they were going to send the
sheriff out to remove him.''
   _In Monroe, N.J., a judge mediated an agreement allowing
46-year-old Ann Romer to be a guest for 60 days in the condo she and
her husband Theodore, 60, bought at the Rossmoor Condominiums. The
condo association had not allowed the couple, who live in New York
City, to buy property because Mrs. Romer wasn't 48. The judge's
Sept. 15 agreement allowed them to buy the weekend home.
   The new housing rules allow age restrictions in retirement
communities if all residents are over 62, or if at least 80 percent
of the households have at least one member over 55 and special
services are offered for older people, or in housing sponsored by
state and federal programs for the elderly.
   Under a transition provision, those who are under the minimum age
and were living in an elderly development as of Sept. 13, 1988, will
not have to give up their residence nor will the community
jeapordize its exemption.
   Leon Rubin defends the child-free lifestyle he enjoys at a
Margate condominium that is changing its documents to remain exempt.
His sentiments are widely shared, especially among mostly elderly
developments.
   Rubin, president of the Oriole Gardens Condominium Association,
said many of his neighbors are infirm and under nurses' care, and
besides, ``No one would like to have a squirrely kid next door
crying in the middle of the night.
   ``This is our lifestyle. I'm satisfied with what we have now.''
   While retirement communities are essentially exempted,
adults-only developments around the country will be affected by the
act.
   Attorney Gary Poliakoff of Fort Lauderdale contends the act
encourages discrimination against the 18- to 55-year-olds who live
in adult communities, and probably won't open much existing housing
to children.
   Poliakoff, whose firm represents 1,700 Florida communities, says
most of those affected have smaller units, recreational facilities
designed for adults and a surrounding social infrastructure that's
not oriented to families.
   Mobile home parks also present a special situation.
   ``The people who make up our membership are not elderly in the
usual sense. They're active retirees, social and don't want to live
next door to children,'' said Federation of Mobile Homeowners of
Florida spokeswoman Kathleen Conture.
   Some may have to under the new law. Mobile-home-park owners and
apartment managers now face having to make developments kid-friendly
with playgrounds and safety fences or figure out if they qualify for
exemption as retirement havens.
   In areas with age restrictions, reaction to the act has been
mixed, but some people are clearly upset they may have to give up
adult-only living.
   ``We don't think that you can just take a whole neighborhood and
say we don't want to live with children,'' said Edwards. ``Children
have rights too.''
   Sixteen states have barred housing discrimination on the basis of
familial status, but experts say the laws are generally weak and
contain huge loopholes.
   The California Supreme Court in 1982 prohibited discrimination
against families with children in apartment rentals and later
extended that to condos. Mobile home parks have been exempt, a
provision the federal law will override.
   But families still face subtler discrimination, such as limits on
the number of occupants, complexes with segregated areas for adults
and families with children, and other restrictive rules, said
Morales. About a third of the housing complaints received by
California's Department of Fair Employment and Housing involve
children, he said.
   Enforcement of the 1988 act will rest with the states, if their
housing law is substantially equivalent to federal law and
enforcement mechanisms already in place are recertified by HUD. The
federal housing agency will handle cases in those states that aren't
equipped to deal with housing complaints.
   The period to file a complaint has been extended from 180 days to
a year, and an administrative law judge will now be able to hear a
case and award actual damages, injunctive relief or top civil
penalties of $50,000.
   At the federal court level, a $100,000 cap on punitive damages
has been eliminated. And the federal government, previously only
able to seek injunctive relief, will be able to seek civil penalties
up to $100,000 against violators.
   ``Everybody needs to be educated about what the law says,'' said
Mihaly. ``I think we'll begin to see fairly dramatic changes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 12</NOTE>
