<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     03-07 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0908</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-crippled Eastern Airlines shut down nearly all operations
and idled 5,000 workers, saying it could not afford to maintain its
business while pilots honored a 3-day-old Machinists walkout.
   ``We can cannot run an airline with unpredictability,'' Eastern
spokesman Robin Matell said Monday in Miami. ``We cannot continue to
inconvenience passengers. We cannot afford the steady financial
drain.''
   Matell said Eastern would run only its most profitable routes,
including its shuttle service between Washington, New York and
Boston.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush won't push yet for a bill
banning secondary picketing but is ready to move quickly if the
strike against Eastern Airlines spreads, a White House spokesman
said.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday that as long
as Eastern's striking members of the Machinists union refrain from
picketing other airlines or railways, ``we wouldn't find it
necessary to send up the legislation'' barring such secondary action.
   The machinists said they would picket other airlines and railways
but called off the secondary actions after a New York court ruled
other workers must not honor such picket lines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's economy grew in February at the
slowest rate in two years, according to a survey of purchasing
executives.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management, which tracks
the economy through its monthly survey of its members, said in a
report Monday its Purchasing Managers Index fell slightly last
month, to 53.0 from 53.2.
   The February level was the lowest for the index since February
1987, when it was 52.6 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court refused to require the
federal government to crack down on interstate air polluters.
   The court's action Monday involves a long-running controversy
between Northeastern states and the industrial Midwest over
responsibility for acid rain, which is caused by pollutants _
primarily sulfur and nitrogen oxides _ from coal-burning power
plants and factories.
   The justices Monday also enhanced the power of states to regulate
natural gas production, and, in a case stemming from Delta Air
Lines' takeover of Western Air Lines, refused to let Delta force the
retirement of a group of flight engineers over age 60.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices of media companies soared as
investors, dazzled by the $18 billion merger planned between Time
Inc. and Warner Communications Inc., showed they were convinced the
trend toward the creation of media giants would continue.
   Securities analysts said Monday they also expected to see more
consolidations in the media business, although not of the magnitude
of the deal announced Saturday that will create Time Warner Inc.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A buyout specialist offered to buy Ohio Mattress
Co., the world's largest bedding maker and producer of Sealy
Posturepedic and Stearns &amp; Foster mattresses, in a deal valuing the
company at nearly $1 billion.
   ``This is a great day for all our stockholders,'' said Ernest M.
Wuliger, chairman and chief executive of Ohio Mattress, which
announced Nov. 18 it had hired an investment banking firm to review
a possible sale.
   Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen said it was offering $25.50 a share
for Ohio Mattress.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC nations produced about 19.4 million
barrels of oil a day in February, less than in the previous month
but still above their new production goal, according to new
estimates.
   The International Energy Agency in its Monthly Oil Market Report
on Monday estimated that production by the 13-nation Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries dipped last month from 20.2 million
barrels a day in January.
   The oil-producing nations agreed in November to slash output
starting Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested two former senior officials of
Japan's largest corporation on suspicion of bribery in a spreading
stock scandal.
   Prosecutors said Monday they arrested Hisashi Shinto, former
chairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., and a senior aide,
Kozo Murata.
   Investigators alleged the two officals were bribed with 10,000
shares of unlisted stock that Murata was offered by Recruit Co., an
information conglomerate.
   The arrests followed the bribery indictments Saturday of four
other businessmen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said it needs more evidence that
certain chemical compounds destroy the ozone layer before it joins
plans by the United States and other countries to ban them by the
end of the century.
   ``If we take a decision which is not well grounded, we can
interfere and destroy the economies of the developing countries,''
said Vladimir Zhakarov, head of the Soviet delegation attending a
120-nation conference on the ozone layer.
   Western scientists agree that chlorofluorocarbons, commonly used
in refrigerators, aerosols and fast-food packaging, are gradually
depleting the ozone shield that protects the Earth from the sun's
cancer-causing ultraviolet rays.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainment and communications issues set the pace as the stock
market staged a broad advance Monday. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 20.53 points to 2,294.82.
   The dollar rose against most foreign currencies.
   Bond prices strengthened, helped by a rising dollar.
   Platinum futures prices gained strongly; gold and silver futures
advanced; copper futures declined; energy futures gained; grains and
soybeans were mostly higher; and livestock and meat futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
