<HEAD>Businessman To Buy Wire Rope Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. says it has signed a
letter of intent to sell its Williamsport wire rope plant to a
businessman who operates a former USX plant. The price was not
disclosed.
   Last month, Bethlehem Steel said the wire rope plant would close
in April because of the Federal Trade Commission's failure to
approve an earlier agreement to sell the plant to Bridon American
Corp., a division of Bridon PLC of Great Britain.
   The agreement with Johnstown businessman John Sheehan is subject
to FTC approval.
   Bethlehem Steel said Monday the sale includes all of the
Williamsport plant's wire rope and wire rope products manufacturing
facilities, and about 40 acres. About 200 people work at the plant.
   Sheehan has indicated he will continue plant operations. He
specializes in revitalizing troubled manufacturing operations and
owns The Johnstown Corp., formerly USX Steel Corp.'s Johnstown Works.
</TEXT>
