<DOCNO> AP890307-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Warner Bjt   03-07 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner, Bjt,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Creation Of Time-Warner Conglomerate Part Of An International Trend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media firms basked in limelight borrowed from the
$18 billion merger planned by Time Inc. and Warner Communications
Inc. as investors _ apparently expecting further consolidations in
the industry _ bid up stock in media companies.
   The biggest winner in Monday's trading was CBS Inc., whose shares
soared $6 to close at $172.12{ on the New York Stock Exchange. Gulf
and Western Corp., owner of Paramount Pictures Corp., rose $2.50 to
close at $45.87{, while Walt Disney Co. rose $1.12{ to $77.62{ a
share.
   Securities analysts said they expected more consolidations in the
media business, although not as big as the deal announced Saturday
to create Time Warner Inc., the largest media concern in the world.
   ``It's a unique opportunity and I can't see that you're able to
replicate it,'' said John Reidy, an analyst with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Time and Warner said the new company would have projected annual
revenues of $10 billion _ surpassing the current world
communications leader, West Germany's Bertelsmann AG, which reported
$6 billion in 1987 revenue.
   That is exactly what Time Chairman J. Richard Munro had in mind
as he and Warner Chairman Steven Ross discussed a merger over the
past two years.
   ``We believe that by the mid-1990s the media and entertainment
industry will be composed of a limited number of global giants,''
Munro told securities analysts last November. ``Time intends to be
one of these companies.''
   Who are the others? Mainly foreign publishing and broadcasting
giants such Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. and Maxwell Communication
Corp., and electronics behemoth Sony Corp., that have scooped up
U.S. media concerns in a torrent of deals made possible over the
past several years by their own riches and the weak U.S. dollar.
   In his speech to analysts, Munro said the spurt of acquisitions,
mergers and join ventures among media companies in recent years has
given these businesses ``the sheer size required to compete
efficiently on a global basis.''
   For example, Ross said in an interview, his company's deal with
Time would give Warner better access to foreign markets for its
video business. He predicted the greatest impact of the deal would
come in Time and Warner overseas operations.
   Analysts said they expected foreigners to continue buying U.S.
companies.
   Reidy, of Drexel Burnham Lambert, noted that Sony _ which bought
CBS Records last year _ has expressed interest in owning a motion
picture company, including Columbia Pictures.
   Bertelsmann is not as well known in this country as some other
big media names, such as Murdoch or Robert Maxwell, but it owns the
publisher Doubleday &amp; Co. and RCA records. Reidy suggested
Bertelsmann might also move into the film business.
   News Corp. owns newspaper, magazine and book publishing
operations in Australia, Britain and the United States. His American
holdings include Triangle Publications Inc., the publisher of TV
Guide; Harper &amp; Row Publishers Inc.; 20th Century Fox Film Corp.;
and Fox Broadcasting Network.
   Murdoch has no plans to slow down although News Corp., which had
$4.3 billion in 1988 revenue, has become burdened by debt because of
its many acquisitions. Murdoch also plans to raise $1 billion or
more for buying other communications companies around the world.
   London-based Maxwell Communication Corp. had $2.6 billion in
revenue in 1987. Robert Maxwell _ motivated partly by a rivalry with
Murdoch _ wants to see that figure swell to $5 billion to $9
billion, and he has said he intends to keep acquiring businesses
until he reaches that goal.
   Last year he won a long battle for Macmillan Inc. and also agreed
to buy Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp.'s Official Airline Guides.
   American companies expect to join the consolidation.
   Francine Blum, an analyst with Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co., said Gulf
&amp; Western and Walt Disney are candidates for consolidations among
U.S. firms.
   She also said she expected to see alliances between movie studios
and the major television networks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
