<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-07 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices bounced back on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange today after a plunge in early trading, while the dollar
rose sharply against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which shed 9.63 points
Monday, rose 61.08 points, or 0.19 percent, today to close at
31,937.94. After a drop in early trading, the Nikkei started upward
at midmorning.
   The index's early decline followed news that Hisashi Shinto,
former chairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, Japan's largest
company, and his former secretary were arrested Monday on bribery
charges in connection with a major stock scandal involving top
politicians, dealers said.
   ``But the Nikkei started to recover from its setback following
Finance Minister (Tatsuo) Murayama's comment that the yen's weak
performance had nothing to do with the stock scandal,'' said Kenji
Ishizuka, a trader at Daiwa Securities.
   Murayama told reporters today that the yen's decline ``did not
have anything to do (with Shinto's arrest) .... It's a market after
all, and who knows why it moves.''
   Ishizuka said investors' interest in steel and construction
issues contributed to the index's rise. Volume traded on the first
section was estimated at 1 billion shares.
   In currency dealings, the dollar finished at 129.03 yen, up 1.40
yen from Monday's 127.63-yen close. The currency started opened at
129.25 yen and ranged between 128.87 yen and 129.28 yen.
   After gaining 2.12 yen over four days last week, the dollar had
declined by 0.49 yen on Monday.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's higher opening in Tokyo today to
its gains on overseas markets overnight. But the rate did not move
much once trading started in Tokyo, said Minori Takeuchi of Chemical
Bank in Tokyo.
   ``Hardly anybody was participating in the afternoon session after
failing to lead the market anywhere, because buying and selling were
equally mixed,'' she said.
   Only speculative investors were trading, adjusting their dollar
positions, Ms. Takeuchi added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
