<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against all major currencies except
the British pound and Japanese yen in cautious European trading
today. Gold prices also were higher in Europe.
   Dealers said the dollar, which slipped back in profit-taking from
early highs, had been buoyed by a drop in West German money market
rates and by a Japanese official's remark that the dollar had
bottomed out.
   The dollar has been gaining against the West German mark since
the West German central bank, the Bundesbank, decided last week
against raising interest rates, dealers in Frankfurt said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.40 Japanese yen to a closing 129.03 yen. Later, in
London, it edged down to 128.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8575 West German marks, up from 1.8531; 1.5865
Swiss francs, up from 1.5830; 6.3080 French francs, up from 6.2955;
2.0965 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0855; 1,363.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,359.25; 1.1955 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1928.
   In London, the British pound opened lower against the dollar,
then rose to $1.7215 from $1.7210 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $386.90 a troy ounce, up
from the $386.25 bid late Monday. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $386.30.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $386.40, up from the $386.30
bid late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.26 to close at a bid of
$388.21.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $5.80 a troy
ounce, down from $5.81 late Monday.
</TEXT>
