<FIRST>r f PM-RockwellFine     03-07 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rockwell Fine,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockwell Fined $5.5 Million for Defense Procurement Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp. has been fined
$5.5 million for double-billing the Pentagon, and the punishment
will serve as a warning to other defense contractors, U.S. Attorney
Robert C. Bonner says.
   ``We're quite pleased, and we hope that a fine of that magnitude
will send out a message to the defense industry that the federal
courts are taking defense procurement fraud very seriously,'' Bonner
said.
   U.S. District Judge Consuelo B. Marshall on Monday fined the
aerospace giant for overbilling the Pentagon for a navigation
satellite system. The judge also ordered Rockwell to pay restitution
of $446,248 and placed the company on probation for five years.
   Rockwell had pleaded guilty to conspiracy and contempt of court
but maintained that two high-level employees, not the company, were
responsible for the overcharges and a subsequent coverup. The
company said it would appeal the fine.
   The El Segundo-based company was fined for conspiring with some
of its managers to overbill the Air Force by nearly $500,000 on the
$1.2 billion NAVSTAR navigation satellite system between 1982 and
1984.
   Rockwell issued a statement reiterating its contention that the
overbilling was the responsibility of renegade employees acting in
what they perceived to be the company's benefit.
   ``Rockwell was sentenced today because of our responsibility
under the law for the acts of our employees,'' it said. ``We accept
that responsibility but we continue to believe that the company
itself should not have been indicted.''
   A Rockwell manager, Robert Zavodnik, 47, has pleaded guilty to
lying to the government and conspiracy in the case. He was sentenced
last month to a year of probation. His supervisor, Donald Carter,
60, was acquitted of the charges by a federal jury.
   The largest fine imposed on a defense contractor was $115 million
in 1988 against Sundstrand Corp.
   The Rockford, Ill., manufacturer of electronic, mechanical and
hydraulic systems for aircraft, was fined for its guilty plea to
four counts of defrauding the Defense Department by overbilling on
aircraft parts. The company admitted it had billed the department
for things like babysitting, country clubs and servants for its
executives.
</TEXT>
