<FIRST>r f PM-LandsatShutdown     03-07 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Landsat Shutdown,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Backs Satellite Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle has come up with
enough government money to keep the Landsat earth-watching
satellites operating at least until a review of the program can be
completed, his spokesman says.
   The earth-sensing satellites were due to be turned off March 31,
when the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration would run
out of money to keep them going.
   NOAA needed $9.4 million to operate the satellites until the
fiscal year ends on Sept. 30.
   But emergency funding will come from departments that use Landsat
images _ State, Defense, Agriculture and Commerce _ as well as the
Office of Management and Budget, said Quayle spokesman David
Beckwith. Landsats scan the Earth with seven kinds of instruments,
giving detailed images of the land and vegetation.
   Beckwith said a review is being made of the satellite system.
   ``The plug won't be pulled before the review is completed,''
Beckwith said. ``The review will be completed prior to
(congressional) oversight of the FY 1990 NASA budget.''
   A House Science, Space and Technology subcommittee was conducting
a hearing this afternoon on the Landsat.
   Quayle is the new chairman of the National Space Council, which
studies the national space programs.
   Beckwith said he did not know how much money would be necessary
to keep the system operating until the end of the fiscal year, but
``it could be less (than $9.4 million) if we can implement some cost
economies.''
   The Reagan administration proposed no money for the current and
future fiscal years, but Congress restored enough to keep the
satellites operating until the end of the month.
   The Earth Observation Satellite Company, known as EOSAT,
currently operates two satellites, Landsats 4 and 5, which provide
photos for mineral exploration, checking soil conditions and
vegetation, urban and rural planning, monitoring volcanoes and
tracing ocean currents. Both satellites are well past their expected
lifetimes and are not fully operational, but they are providing
useful information.
   An improved satellite, Landsat 6, is under construction. That
project will continue because money was provided to complete and
launch that satellite.
</TEXT>
