<HEAD>Strike Grounds Italian Air Travelers in Rome and Naples</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by airline flight attendents forced
Alitalia, Italy's national airline, to cancel most national and
international flights from Rome and Naples Tuesday.
   The 24-hour strike was called by union chapters in the two cities
only. Flights were departing as scheduled from other Italian
airports.
   Strikers were protesting stalled contract renewal negotiations
centered on salary and schedule disputes. Only some flights to the
islands of Sicily and Sardinia flew from Rome and Naples.
   Pilots have threatened a 48-hour work stoppage after the Easter
holidays if negotiations fail to resolve the contract dispute.
