<FIRST>r f PM-AccusedBanker     03-07 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Accused Banker,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Bank Chairman Free To Return To Banking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Michigan National Corp. Chairman
Stanford Stoddard is free to re-enter the banking business under a
federal appeals court opinion lifting a ban by the Federal Reserve
Board.
   The decision was a victory for the 58-year-old Birmingham banker
in his four-year struggle to fight civil charges that he misused
bank funds.
   ``This should have ended four years ago. ... It should never have
started,'' Stoddard said Monday. ``I think my honesty ranks with
that of any officer who has ever served a bank in Michigan or the
U.S. I am guilty of mistakes in judgement, but I am not guilty of
dishonesty.''
   An attorney for the Federal Reserve said Monday that the opinion
overturning its ban on Stoddard would hinder efforts to clean up
abuses in banking.
   The Federal Reserve Board in January 1988 removed Stoddard from
his position as officer and director of the Detroit-area
bank-holding company and forbade him from engaging in future banking
activities.
   Stoddard, however, had resigned in July 1984 from his position as
the head of the bank his father founded. He left the banking company
nearly a year before the comptroller of the currency began
proceedings to remove him in an investigation of misuse of bank
funds.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, in an
opinion issued Friday, vacated the Federal Reserve Board's order,
saying the board's decision to dismiss Stoddard after his
resignation ``presents a linguistic _ and metaphysical _
impossibility.''
   ``One cannot remove what isn't there,'' said the opinion written
by Judge James Buckley.
   A Federal Reserve attorney, Douglas Jordan, said from an
enforcement standpoint, ``it creates a certain problem when someone
can resign and therefore elude jurisdiction.''
   The board had argued that Congress intended the removal provision
as a way of barring people who engaged in misconduct from returning
to the banking business.
   Stoddard's attorney, Keith Fisher, said his client ``seriously
wants to get back into the banking business.''
   ``In the current climate of troubled institutions all over the
country, someone of his enormous experience and talents would be
quite useful to any number of institutions,'' Fisher said.
   The comptroller of the currency, in recommending action against
Stoddard, said the bank officer used $167,385 of the institution's
funds for improper purposes.
   The agency said Stoddard used the money for renovation of
buildings that were or were to become Mormon churches; improvements
to his residence, vacation home and Florida condominium; payment of
bills for a wedding reception for his children and friends; and
extensive personal secretarial and errand services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
