<DOCNO> AP890307-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ozone 1stLd-Writethru f0034 03-07 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ozone, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0034,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says Developing Nations Must Help Curb CFCs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to UPDATE with closing comments of Mrs. Thatcher,
U.S. comment. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said today that
all countries, including poor Third World nations, must curb
ozone-destroying chemicals that she said threaten life on Earth.
   ``Simply to carry on as we are is not an option,'' said Mrs.
Thatcher at the end of a 120-nation conference on phasing out the
use of chlorofluorocarbons. The chemical compounds are used in
aerosol products, refrigerators and air conditioners.
   Her speech came after Prince Charles on Monday called for a
complete ban by century's end of the synthetic chemicals.
   The meeting began Sunday and 20 countries have since joined the
31 that signed the 1987 Montreal Protocol requiring that production
of the compounds chemicals be cut in half by the turn of the century.
   Mrs. Thatcher acknowledged that action on the compounds was
likely to begin in industrial nations.
   However, she added, ``It is not a case of some countries asking
other countries to act. It is a case of every country taking
action.''
   She said the world's people must ``change their customs and
habits in what they buy and what they do'' in order to ``overcome
one of the greatest challenges to life on Earth.''
   The compounds are stable and non-toxic when released into the
atmosphere, but when they rise 15-25 miles to the stratosphere, 10
to 100 years later, they break apart and their chlorine atoms
destroy the ozone shield that protects the Earth from the sun's
cancer-causing ultraviolet rays.
   The compounds also trap heat and warm global temperatures,
causing potentially major climate changes in a process known as the
greenhouse effect.
   In other remarks today, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
chief William Reilly told reporters: ``I think we are all in this
together. We are all going to have to find ways to collaborate and
clear this mess up. It affects us all.''
   Delegates from China and India on Monday urged the industrial
nations to create a fund to help developing nations replace the
compounds with safe substitutes.
   Vladimir Zhakarov, head of the Soviet delegation, told the
conference Monday that his country needs more scientific evidence
that CFCs destroy the ozone layer before it will agree to speed up
its phaseout of such chemicals.
   ``If we take a decision which is not well-grounded, we can
interfere and destroy the economies of the developing countries,''
he said.
   The United States and the 12-nation European Economic Community
have said they will press for a total ban on the compounds by the
end of the century.
   Prince Charles said Monday that, ``There is surely an
overwhelming scientific case to change the (Montreal) treaty from a
reduction to complete elimination.''
   The heir to the British throne, who banned aerosols with the
compounds from his households last year, urged a consumer boycott of
products containing the chemicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AppleComputer     03-07 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apple Computer,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Unveils Macintosh IIcx And New Monitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc., hoping to get back on
track after recent pricing blunders and a projected drop in earnings
this quarter, is unveiling a more compact but equally powerful
Macintosh computer and two large, extra-sharp monitors.
   The Macintosh IIcx was scheduled to make its debut today in a
glitzy teleconference broadcast from a San Francisco hotel to
customers, resellers, reporters and analysts in Chicago, New York,
Los Angeles, Dallas, Atlanta, Washington, Toronto, Sydney and
Hannover, West Germany.
   The Macintosh IIcx, the third member of the Macintosh family
announced in the last six months, features the Motorola 68030 and
68882 microprocessors, takes up less desk space than the earlier II
and IIx models and can be serviced and reconfigured more easily.
   ``I think the IIcx is a product that should have been in the
marketplace sooner,'' said Bruce Lupatkin, an analyst with Hambrecht
&amp; Quist Inc. in San Francisco. ``It's probably the most appealing
offering in the Mac family and should do well.''
   He said sales of the Macintosh IIcx should begin making an impact
on Apple's earnings in the next quarter, since the company is set to
ship the computers immediately.
   Lupatkin had some reservations about the new computer's price.
   ``The product is priced a little bit expensively,'' he said.
``But I think it would have sported a much higher price had Apple
not had the difficulty it had'' when the company raised prices last
fall in response to a memory chip shortage. The result of that price
hike was a sharp drop in Mac II sales that is expected to hurt the
company this quarter.
   Apple said in January it expects its second quarter, ending March
30, will see earnings in the range of 35 cents to 45 cents per
share, compared with 61 cents per share for the same period last
year. In the first quarter, ended Dec. 30, the company earned $140.5
million, or $1.10 per share.
   The IIcx, which may eventually make the Mac II obsolete, is just
over 12 inches wide, compared with 18 inches for other Mac II
computers.
   It will be available in four configurations:
   _With one megabyte of memory and one floppy disk, selling for
$4,669.
   _With one megabyte of internal memory and a 40 megabyte hard disk
drive, selling for $5,369.
   _With four megabytes of memory and an 80 megabyte hard disk, for
$7,069.
   _A similar computer with four megabytes of memory, an 80 megabyte
hard disk and A-UX, Apple's version of the AT&amp;T Unix operating
system, for $7,552.
   One of the new high-resolution monitors Apple will show off has a
21-inch, two-page monochrome screen that measures 15 inches
horizontally by 11.3 inches vertically. It allows user to display
two pages side-by-side along with menus and scroll bars. The monitor
carries a suggested retail price of $2,149. Its companion video card
is priced at $599.
   The new Portrait Display, priced at $1,099, has a 15-inch
diagonal flat screen that can show an entire page of text and
graphics, including menus and scroll bars.
</TEXT>
