<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Heinz     03-07 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Heinz,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>H.J. Heinz Profits Increase In Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.J. Heinz Co. said Tuesday it posted a 13.1
percent gain in third-quarter profit due to higher sales volume,
price increases and acquisitions.
   The Pittsburgh-based food giant said that for the three-month
period ended Jan. 25, net income totaled $103 million, or 78 cents a
share, up from $91.1 million, or 69 cents a share, for the year ago
period.
   Third-quarter sales increased 9.1 percent to $1.37 billion
compared with $1.25 billion for 1987.
   ``Higher volume, particularly in the domestic market, led our
sales growth,'' said Heinz President Anthony J.F. O'Reilly.
   ``In addition, we benefited from the acquisitions we made during
the last 12 months and from price increases, mainly in our overseas
markets,'' he said.
   Heinz packs and sells an extensive line of canned foods under
Heinz, Star-Kist, 9-Lives and Ore-Ida labels.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Heinz said its net
earnings increased 13.6 percent to $323 million, or $2.45 a share,
from $284.3 million, or $2.14 a share, in 1987.
   Sales for the first nine months increased 10.5 percent to $4.1
billion compared with $3.7 billion for the same period in 1987.
   Operating income increased 16.5 percent during the first nine
months to $587.1 million compared with $504.1 million in the same
1987 period. O'Reilly said the increase was attributable to higher
sales as well as the company's cost improvement programs.
   ``We are very pleased with our performance to this point, and we
believe that we are well on our way to our 25th consecutive year of
uninterrupted financial growth,'' O'Reilly said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
