<DOCNO> AP890307-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Beef     03-07 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Beef,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fair Trade Commission Raids Beef Importers in Pricing Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fair Trade Commission raided trading companies
and their beef trade association Tuesday to investigate an alleged
cartel to push up prices of imported beef, officials said.
   Inspectors went to 29 trading companies, including Mitsubishi
Corp., Mitsui and Co., and C. Itoh and Co. Ltd., and to the Japan
Beef Importers' Association, said FTC spokesman Mitsuru Suzuki. All
29 companies belong to the 36-member semi-governmental Livestock
Industry Promotion Corp.
   ``We have kept our eyes on them for almost four years,'' he said,
adding that the FTC suspected the traders since 1984 had been fixing
the share of imported beef each would sell to the LIPC before actual
bidding took place.
   ``By fixing each company's share, the cartel prevents free
competition in the market and raises beef prices,'' Suzuki said.
   The illegal practice no longer exists, but investigations under
the anti-cartel law can go into past actions, Suzuki said.
   A group of 36 beef importers arranges imports, pays tariffs and
sells their imported beef to the LIPC, which controls some 90
percent of beef imports.
   Japan imported 214,000 tons of beef in 1987 and 175,000 tons were
sold through the LIPC.
   When the issue of a suspected illegal cartel was raised last
August, the LIPC conducted its own investigation of member companies
at government order, said Shinzo Nakatani of the LIPC.
   ``We couldn't find anything that indicated the existence of
preliminary arrangements to fix shares,'' he added.
   An official at the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and
Fisheries said officials in the ministry's livestock department were
surprised to learn of the FTC raid.
   The ministry said in a statement that it would take strict
measures based on results of the FTC's investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
