<HEAD>Crop Futures Turn Lower After Mixed Openeing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were trading mostly
lower this morning, against expectations, after a mixed opening on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Much of the selling pressure was coming from the soybean complex,
where some large speculators were cashing out after bidding soybean
meal prices up sharply late in Monday's session.
   But the soybean market's early losses were limited by buying
linked to a trade journal's report that the Soviet Union's imports
of soybean meal halfway through the current marketing year were
nearly double those of the same period a year ago.
   Wheat futures were nearly unchanged in early trading following
reports that the Agriculture Department, as expected, had accepted
China's bid for 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to } cent higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.35 a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.78} a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1 cent higher with March at $2.09} a bushel; soybeans
were \ cent to 2} cents lower with March at $7.69 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .08 cent lower with April at 77.75
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27 cent lower to .08 cent higher
with March at 82.02 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent lower to
.23 cent higher with April at 43.77 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .47 cent lower to .75 cent higher with March at 39.05
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures finished mostly lower on Monday while pork futures
were mixed.
