<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-PilotsReax     03-07 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Pilots Reax,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots' Action Doesn't Wash With Passengers on Rival Carrier</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ABOARD DELTA FLIGHT 839 (AP) _ Passengers and flight attendants
on one Delta Air Lines flight expressed exasperation today over a
potentially time-consuming job action implemented by pilots
nationwide in support of strikers at rival Eastern Airlines.
   The pilots union covering most U.S. carriers ordered members to
take enhanced safety procedures starting today because of safety
concerns it said have arisen out of the 4-day-old strike at the
troubled Miami-based Eastern.
   But if the views of people aboard a Delta flight from Miami to
Atlanta were any indication, that wasn't the pilots' only motive.
   ``I think they are doing it more out of sympathy,'' said
passenger Franco Licenzi, an engineer from Miami, after the cockpit
crew delayed takeoff for nearly a half an hour on the three-quarter
full flight because of what the captain called ``cargo loading.''
   A Delta flight attendant, who did not wish to be quoted by name,
said the same cargo loading delay had waylaid the flight for 20
minutes on an earlier Atlanta-to Miami run. The pilots declined to
talk with an Associated Press reporter aboard and made no
announcement to other passengers regarding the job action.
   ``It's just going to aggravate people all day long,'' said the
flight attendant, a 10-year Delta veteran. ``What's the point of
it?''
   She said ``I think it's solidarity for their union. It's just
they're little way of getting even.''
   Passenger Melton Johnston, a merchant marine ship captain en
route to Bermuda, said of the Eastern strike and the pilots'
sympathy action: ``I think it's in poor taste. Nobody wins.''
   The Eastern strike has been a boon to Atlanta-based Delta, which
in ordinary times is a highly profitable carrier that gets good
marks from passengers for service. Thousands of erstwhile Eastern
passengers have been re-booked on Delta flights since the strike
began Saturday.
   Despite the delay today, at least some passengers appeared not to
mind and directed their criticism toward Eastern, which has been
reeling from financial losses and chronic complaints about service.
   ``I hope Eastern goes out of business and Delta can buy their
routes,'' said a plastics company sales manager from Chicago who was
aboard the Miami-Atlanta flight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GM-BuickCity     03-07 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM-Buick City,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Workers Return To Night Shift At Flint Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 General Motors Corp. employees at
the company's huge Buick City complex, some laid off since October
1987, are back at work after the automaker cranked up a second shift
on an assembly line.
   The workers, who returned to their night shift jobs Monday, were
met at the plant gate by Mayor Matthew S. Collier and some United
Auto Workers union officials.
   ``It makes me feel good that we'll be back for a while,'' said
welder Fay Deason of Flint, who had been laid off for about 13
months. ``Everybody seems to be happy to be back. I know I am.''
   The plant assembles full-size Buick LeSabres and Oldsmobile 88
Royale automobiles.
   GM spokeswoman Julie Hamp said the employee recall was spurred by
improving LeSabre sales. However, LeSabre sales are 13.4 percent
lower this model year compared with last and 43.4 percent lower for
the calendar year.
   In January, the factory began assembling Oldsmobile 88 Royale
automobiles. Production of that car was moved to Buick City from
GM's Willow Run assembly plant in Ypsilanti, Hamp said.
   LeSabres will make up about two-thirds with 88 Royales making up
the rest of the expected 1,040 cars a day produced by both shifts,
Hamp said. Production at the plant was idled between Dec. 23 and
Jan. 19 to retool for Oldsmobile production.
   The employee recall will bring to about 4,500 the number of
workers at the Buick City assembly plant.
   In October 1987, GM laid off about 2,000 workers because of
sagging LeSabre sales, Hamp said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
