<FIRST>r f BC-Italy-Fiat-Ford     03-07 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Italy-Fiat-Ford,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Fiat Executive Won't Begin With Ford Before July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. on Tuesday agreed not to use
Vittorio Ghidella's consulting services before July 1, following
consultations with Fiat, the Italian auto executive's former
employer.
   A Fiat spokesman said the decision was taken after talks in Turin
between representatives of the two auto giants in line with their
``good and correct relations.''
   Ghidella, who resigned late last year as operative head of Fiat's
auto sector, was expected to have started his relationship with Ford
by mid-February.
   Fiat objected to this arrangement because Ghidella, who formally
quit the Italian group on Dec. 31, had a contractual obligation not
to work for the competition for six months following the end of his
relationship with the Turin-based auto maker.
   Ghidella, who had played a key role in the impressive turnaround
of Fiat's auto sector in the 1980s, resigned following a dispute
over Fiat's strategy with Cesare Romiti, the managing director of
the Fiat group, which is controlled by the Agnelli family.
   Ghidella had emphasized Fiat's need to put more emphasis on the
auto sector to overcome growing competition from Japanese
manufacturers. Ford hired him to advise it on a wide range of
automotive initiatives, particularly in Europe.
   Three years ago the Italian and the U.S. company battled for the
takeover of Alfa Romeo, the Italian maker of luxury and sports cars.
Fiat prevailed following several months of tense negotiations.
</TEXT>
