<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today,
hesitating after Monday's strong gain.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 20.53 points on
Monday, inched up another 1.25 to 2,296.07 by 2 p.m. today on Wall
Street.
   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered declines in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 689 up, 667
down and 532 unchanged.
   Monday's advance was prompted in part by a monthly report from a
group of corporate purchasing executives that pointed to a slowing
of economic growth in February.
   That was interpreted as a positive portent for the inflation
outlook and possibly a sign that upward pressure on interest rates
might ease.
   But analysts said some traders were fearful that the market might
get some contradictory evidence later this week when the Labor
Department issues its statistics on the employment situation for
February.
   Those worries were cited as a primary force behind a modest rise
in open-market interest rates today.
   Advance estimates call for the report, due out Friday, to show an
increase of about 250,000 in nonfarm payroll employment.
   Time Inc. jumped 8 to 115{. Analysts cited speculation that the
company, in reaching its weekend agreement to merge with Warner
Communications, might have opened itself up to a takeover bid from
some other direction.
   Microsoft tumbled 8{ to 53{ as the most active issue in the
over-the-counter market. The company said it expects to report lower
earnings for its fiscal third quarter ending March 31.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .06 to 165.57. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .64 at 328.63.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 121.77 million shares with two
hours to go.
