<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-07 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Fall On Brazilian Supply Prospects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed moderately lower
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting concerns about the
imminent arrival of new supplies from the record-large Brazilian
soybean crop.
   Grain futures finished narrowly mixed as spillover selling from
the soybean complex was offset by bullish forecasts for relatively
dry weather in the Plains and Midwest, analysts said.
   The soybean harvest in Brazil, the world's second-largest
producer after the United States, is expected to be the largest
ever, despite a spate of unusually hot, dry weather early in the
growing season.
   Analysts said the first soybeans from the new Brazilian crop
could move into processing channels this week, partially alleviating
the tight-supply situation caused by last summer's drought in the
United States.
   The Agriculture Department said Tuesday that cool temperatures in
portions of the central and southern Plains last week had slowed
winter wheat growth, which added to the bullish outlook for the
wheat market.
   At the close, wheat was 2} cents lower to 2{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.34 a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to 2 cents higher with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1{ cents higher with March at $2.10 a bushel;
soybeans were unchanged to 6\ cents lower with March at $7.64{ a
bushel.
