<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Gulf&amp;Western     03-07 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Gulf &amp; Western,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf &amp; Western Reports First Quarter Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf &amp; Western Inc. Tuesday reported a 7 percent
gain in first-quarter profit compared with the previous year,
although earnings would have fallen except for unusual items.
   For the three-month period ended Jan. 31, Gulf &amp; Western said its
net earnings totaled $69.2 million, or 58 cents a share, up from
$64.7 million, or 54 cents a share, in the 1988 quarter. Revenue
totaled $1.35 billion, up 14 percent from $1.18 billion in the
year-earlier period.
   New York-based Gulf &amp; Western's three operating segments are
publishing, consumer and commercial lending, and entertainment,
including Paramount Pictures, Madison Square Garden and theater
circuits.
   The company said first-quarter results included $5.1 million
stemming from an accounting change related to the recognition of
finance income and a one-time gain of $5.6 million from the sale of
a 50 percent interest in the company's domestic theater operations.
   The accounting change related to finance income should continue
to add about $5 million a quarter to earnings over the next two to
three years, the company said. Without that gain and the gain on the
sale, earnings would have dropped.
   Gulf &amp; Western said total receivables in its consumer-commercial
finance unit exceeded $13 billion for the first time, led by healthy
advances in consumer real estate lending.
   Motion picture operating income was strong but television
operations posted the largest percentage gains due in part to the
popularity of ``Webster'' and ``Star Trek: The Next Generation,''
Gulf &amp; Western said.
   However, the company's Simon &amp; Schuster publishing unit recorded
a loss in consumer operations despite strong sales of some hardcover
bestsellers. The losses reflected higher product support expenses,
the company said.
</TEXT>
