<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices headed lower in moderate
trading Tuesday, reversing the previous session's modest gains.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled 37 cents lower
at $18.30 a barrel, after rising 11 cents on Monday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
April contract for wholesale home heating oil settled 0.35 cent
lower at 51.08 cents a gallon, following a 0.63 cent gain the
previous session.
   April unleaded gasoline, which rose 0.60 cent Monday, ended down
0.18 cent at 51.41 cents a gallon.
   Peter Beutel, an energy analyst with Elder Futures Inc.,
attributed Tuesday's decline largely to technical factors prior to
the release of the latest American Petroleum Institute report.
   The report, put out after the market closed, showed a sharp
increase in crude oil supplies but a decline in supplies of heating
oil and gasoline.
