<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Community 1stLd-Writethru   03-07 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Community, 1st Ld-Writethru,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Employees Stunned, Bedroom Community Slowed by Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to DELETE erroneous reference to city losing money.
INSERTS 1 graf after 13th, `A supervisor...' with Eastern comment on worker
status. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This airport bedroom community,
founded by aviation pioneer Glen Curtiss, was hit especially hard
when Eastern Airlines idled 9,500 employees in last two days.
   Pedro Hidalgo has owned the Eldorado jewelry shop for eight years
in the corner of the central drug store in this city of 12,000 on
the edge of Miami International Airport. Now he wonders if he'll be
looking for a new job soon.
   Open for 2{ hours Tuesday, Hidalgo went to his desk to locate his
only receipt for the day _ a $2 repair.
   ``By this time of day, I was usually crowded and people were
waiting outside,'' said Hidalgo. ``My survival amount to cover
everything is $100 a day. Yesterday I made $62.''
   He feels the strike by the Machinists union against money-losing
Eastern is to blame.
   Shopkeepers around the downtown traffic circle estimate 40
percent to 60 percent of their business comes from the airline
industry and a significant segment of that from Eastern, whose
headquarters is just outside the city.
   Betty Russell, a newsstand employee at the airport for 17 years,
was wondering how much longer the airport concession would keep her
shop open in the nearly deserted Eastern terminal.
   ``I live in the Springs, and practically all the people that live
in the Springs work for Eastern,'' she said.
   At one point, she called the strike by the 8,500-member
Machinists union ``very foolish'' but, no matter what happens, she
concluded, ``Nobody's going to win.''
   Her employer already has closed stores on Eastern's shuttered
boarding ramps and is pushing its workers to take vacations or shift
to a four-day work week.
   ``I've been here 17 years and I make $5 an hour. I always say
half a loaf is better than nothing,'' she said. ``It's going to be a
sad thing down here in Miami. It's bad.''
   Ticket agents and skycaps who on Monday were placed on what
Eastern calls ``no-work status'' were called in Tuesday morning for
a meeting with management.
   A supervisor told them they could apply for unemployment benefits
but could be called back at any time. Their medical insurance
expired at midnight Monday, no vacation pay would be considered, and
questions about early retirement went unanswered.
   The ``no-work status'' means ``we hope it's a shorter term, in
other words, that we hope we'll be able to call them back to work,''
said Eastern spokeswoman Bobbi Giordano. ``We're hoping that they'll
be coming back, so that's where that stands.''
   Iza Emmett, a 24-year Eastern veteran who had been working in
international passenger services, hugged co-workers and wiped away
tears as she headed to pick up a paycheck.
   ``We don't get vacation pay, we don't get severance pay, we don't
get anything,'' she said.
   ``They're upset, very upset, because they want to know what's
happening in the future,'' said ramp service manager Joseph Brazeau,
a 23-year Eastern veteran.
   Skycap Red Bloise resents both Eastern and President ``George
`Ostrich' Bush, because he has his head in the ground.''
   ``They're giving us this no-work status garbage because this way
they don't have to give us the stuff we've earned,'' the 10-year
veteran said as he left for home and his children. ``Now that we're
out of a job, we won't even get to Disney World.''
   Joseph Leonard, Eastern's chief operating officer, said the
workers were laid off, but workers were told they had been placed on
``no-work status,'' eligible for unemployment benefits but without
severance pay, vacation pay, medical insurance or answers to
questions about early retirement.
   ``The difference is that we hope it's a shorter term, in other
words, that we hope we'll be able to call them back to work,'' said
Eastern spokeswoman Bobbi Giordano. ``We're hoping that they'll be
coming back, so that's where that stands.''
   In Miami Springs, Marilynn Yoss, whose grandmother worked for
Eastern, said she couldn't be anything but optimistic.
   ``I think that's the only attitude you can take is be positive,''
she said while filling orders at a gift shop filled with Easter
baskets, colorful balloons and St. Patrick's Day fare.
   Others weren't so enthusiastic.
   Fred White, operator of Circle Barber Shop and a real estate
agent, recalls airline workers mowing lawns and taking jobs pumping
gas in previous strikes.
</TEXT>
