<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SuddenAcceleration     03-07 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudden Acceleration,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Confusion Between Pedals Is Likely Cause of Sudden Acceleration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most likely cause of cases of sudden
acceleration involving the Audi 5000 and other cars is drivers
stepping on the wrong pedal, the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration said Tuesday.
   The agency, however, said drivers may not be to blame for
confusion between accelerator and brake. The difficulty in selecting
the right pedal may be ``aggravated by vehicle design,'' the agency
said.
   A yearlong study of sudden acceleration, conducted by the
agency's Transportation Systems Center in Cambridge, Mass., found
that a car can suddenly speed up to full power only if the throttle
is opened almost completely to provide oxygen to the engine.
   Other proposed theories of sudden acceleration, such as problems
with the cruise control or electronic idle speed control systems,
failed to meet the test of an open throttle while the brakes are
applied, NHTSA said.
   NHTSA has conducted more than 100 investigations of unwanted
acceleration involving 20 manufacturers since the late 1970s.
   The agency's investigations of the problem have resulted in 26
recalls and manufacturers have conducted another 75 recalls.
   A major sudden acceleration case involved the West German-made
Audi. In late 1986 the company recalled about 250,000 of its
5000-series automobiles for installation of a ``shift-lock'' device,
which prevents the transmission from being put into forward or
reverse without the brake pedal being depressed.
   Audi spokesman Joseph Bennett said in Detroit that the report
``is a breath of fresh air as far as we're concerned.''
   ``While the Transportation Center chose to use the term `pedal
misapplication,' we feel that it is fundamentally what we've been
saying,'' Bennett said.
   He was skeptical that design factors in the Audi could have
contributed to confusion among pedals.
   ``Our pedals are optimized for braking efficiency, for driver
control,'' Bennett said. ``These cars are designed to be driven on
autobahns at 100 mph plus.''
   The Center for Auto Safety, a critic of the auto industry,
declined comment until it could see a copy of the report.
   NHTSA rejected the conclusion of a Canadian study and some
automakers that sudden acceleration was due to driver error.
   ```Driver error' may imply carelessness or willfulness in failing
to operate a car properly,'' NHTSA said. ```Pedal misapplication' is
more descriptive of what occurs. It could happen to even the most
attentive driver who inadvertently selects the wrong pedal and
continues to do so unwittingly.''
   A report by Transport Canada, issued in January, concluded that
sudden acceleration ``occurs as a result of driver error.''
   Pedal placement, shape and feel may be factors that lead drivers
to press the wrong pedal, NHTSA said.
   However, the agency said proposals for any design changes must
await further research.
   Complaints of sudden acceleration are based on instances when
cars allegedly go to full power from a standstill or slow speed,
usually after the driver has moved the automatic transmission from
park into drive or reverse, NHTSA said.
   The agency excluded from its definition of sudden acceleration
instances of high idle speed or throttle sticking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890307-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     03-07 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Rise On Platinum's Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A resurgence of commercial and speculative buying pushed platinum
futures prices to a 3-month high Tuesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange and boosted gold and silver futures as well.
   On other markets, crude-oil futures tumbled; soybeans retreated;
grains were mixed; cattle futures advanced; and pork futures fell.
   Platinum settled $4.80 to $5.30 higher with the contract for
delivery in April at $551.50 a troy ounce, the highest close since
the market's mid-December collapse from levels near $600.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $5.20 to $5.80
higher with April at $395.70 a troy ounce; silver finished 6.5 cents
to 6.8 cents higher with May at $5.965 a troy ounce.
   Platinum's slow climb back from less than $520 an ounce reflects
both renewed commercial demand from the Far East and the gradual
return of bullish speculators who bailed out of the market following
the Ford Motor Co.'s Dec. 14 announcement that it had developed a
catalytic converter that did not use platinum as a primary
ingredient.
   The use of platinum as a chemical catalyst in the automobile
pollution-control devices accounts for about a third of global
platinum consumption.
   With Ford still testing its new converters, the platinum market's
attention has gradually returned to the existing tight-supply
situation, which is expected to persist into the 1990s.
   Yet platinum traders remain cautious, an attitude underscored by
Tuesday's activity. The April contract traded as high as $559 during
the session, then dropped back as traders lost their nerve and took
profits.
   ``Still, you've got to give the market some credit just for
getting up there,'' said Craig Sloane, a metal-market analyst with
Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   In contrast, the gold and silver markets closed near their highs,
indicating a greater willingness among traders to gamble that prices
of those metals will continue to rise.
   Peter Cardillo, commodity trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co.
in New York, said gold's performance on Tuesday ``tells me we're in
for a short-term pop to the $400 area,'' a level the gold market has
not seen since late January.
   Tuesday's sharp drop in energy futures prices on the New York
Mercantile Exchange was attributed to technical factors rather than
to a change in the bullish fundamentals that have recently driven
crude-oil futures to prices approaching $19 a barrel.
   Those positive factors include agreements by non-OPEC
oil-producing countries to reduce their crude-oil output in a
concerted effort to boost prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 23 cents to 37 cents
lower with April at $18.30 a barrel; heating oil was .35 cent to .57
cent lower with April at 51.08 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.18 cent to .54 cent lower with April at 51.41 cents a gallon.
   Soybean futures prices fell moderately on the Chicago Board of
Trade, reflecting concerns about the imminent arrival of new
supplies from the record-large Brazilian soybean crop.
   Grain futures finished narrowly mixed as spillover selling from
the soybean complex was offset by bullish forecasts for a week of
relatively dry weather in the Plains and Midwest, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents lower to 2} cents higher with March at
$4.34 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with March
at $2.78\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1{ cents higher with
March at $2.10 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 6\ cents lower
with March at $7.64\ a bushel.
   Cattle futures moved moderately lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in technically inspired selling while pork futures rose on
expectations for lighter marketings and higher cash prices.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent .42 cent lower with April at 77.57
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .35 cent lower with
March at 82 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent to .37 cent
higher with April at 44.10 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.08 cent to .55 cent higher with March at 39.10 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
