<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru   03-07 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to restore dropped material.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted a small loss Tuesday
after the Dow Jones industrial average made a short-lived run past
the 2,300 level.
   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips, up 20.53 points on Monday,
slipped 4.11 to 2,290.71.
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advances in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 708 stocks
rising, 730 falling and 524 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 172.50 million
shares, up from 168.88 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 204.94 million shares.
   The market's advance Monday was prompted in part by a monthly
report from a group of corporate purchasing executives that pointed
to a slowing of economic growth in February.
   That was interpreted as a positive portent for the inflation
outlook and possibly a sign that upward pressure on interest rates
could ease.
   But analysts said some traders were fearful that they might get
some contradictory evidence later this week when the Labor
Department issues its statistics on the employment situation for
February.
   Those worries were cited as a primary force behind a modest rise
in open-market interest rates Tuesday.
   Street estimates call for the report, due out Friday, to show an
increase of about 250,000 in nonfarm payroll employment.
   Time Inc. jumped 9\ to 116}. Analysts cited speculation that the
company, in reaching its weekend agreement to merge with Warner
Communications, might have opened itself up to a takeover bid from
some other direction.
   Warner shares rose | to 48~.
   Some other entertainment issues gained ground for the second
straight session in reaction to the plans for Time and Warner. Gulf
&amp; Western, which reported higher quarterly earnings, climbed 1\ to
47[, and MCA 1\ to 54\.
   Oil-service stocks, which have benefited from recent strength in
oil prices, were broadly higher today. Schlumberger gained } to 38|;
Halliburton 1[ to 31}; Dresser Industries | to 38, and Baker Hughes
{ to 17\.
   In the oil sector, Amoco, up 1 at 81; Mobil, up \ at 49{;
Atlantic Richfield, up 1\ at 91[, and Chevron, up ] at 52\, all made
new 52-week highs.
   Microsoft tumbled 8{ to 53{ as the most active issue in the
over-the-counter market. The company said it expects to report lower
earnings for its fiscal third quarter ending March 31.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $5.03 billion, or 0.17
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .35 to 165.28.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell .84 to 339.95, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down .94 at 293.87.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped .08 to 406.18. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 328.83, up .84.
</TEXT>
