<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Congress 1stLd-Writethru   03-07 0900</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru,0927</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee Moves Toward Eastern Strike Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New in first 6 grafs with subcommittee passage of bill; Picks
up 3rd graf pvs bgng: But Bush, ... adding 3 grafs at end with separate
bill to protect ticket holders, vote breakdown. Also moved on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A divided House panel approved a union-sought
bill Tuesday that would compel President Bush to intervene in the
Eastern Airlines strike, despite administration insistence that such
involvement would not settle the bitter dispute.
   The legislation, passed 21-12 by the House Public Works' aviation
subcommittee, would require Bush to appoint an emergency board to
study the impasse that has grounded most of the carrier's flights
and to recommend a solution. During this process, there would be a
cooling-off period of up to 60 days in which the striking employees
would return to work.
   The bill is not expected to reach the House floor until sometime
next week. Although many lawmakers concede that there are not enough
votes in Congress to override an expected presidential veto,
Democrats say the exercise is worthwhile because of the pressure it
places on Bush to find a solution to the work stoppage.
   ``When we send the bill to President Bush's desk, we're passing a
hot potato back to him,'' Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., said after the
panel's vote. ``What's his solution?''
   The legislation would require the emergency board to study the
dispute between not only Eastern and its striking machinists, but
between the airline and two other unions whose contracts have
expired: the Air Line Pilots Association and the Transport Workers
Union of America, which represents flight attendants.
   ``We want to stick it all into the same bag, settle it all at
once,'' said the subcommittee chairman, Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn.
   But Bsh, in a session with White House reporters, repeated his
belief that the ``free collective bargaining'' process should
resolve the standoff. He said it would be ``inappropriate'' for the
government to impose a solution.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner told the panel that he
would recommend that Bush veto the legislation, arguing that the
``frustrations and animosity'' between Eastern's management and its
striking workers was building and would fester despite a board's
appointment.
   ``You can't run an airline where you have the kind of animosity
over a period of time building up,'' Skinner said.
   Democrats, however, argued that a board could produce a solution
to the dispute, which began Saturday and has pitted Eastern against
its 8,500 machinists and ramp workers represented by the
International Association of Machinists. Most of the carrier's
pilots and flight attendants have also walked off their jobs in
support of the machinists, in a dispute focusing on wages and
benefits.
   ``The emergency board gives cover to both parties to reach
agreement,'' said subcommittee chairman James L. Oberstar, D-Minn.
   Elsewhere, House Speaker Jim Wright also sought to pressure Bush
to appoint a board, telling reporters that presidential leadership
was needed.
   ``He can do as previous presidents have done, as President
Kennedy did in the steel crisis,'' Wright said. ``That's
leadership.''
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland sounded a similar theme to the
House subcommittee, blaming Bush's failure to appoint a board for
the strike.
   ``It is time for Congress to fill the leadership void the
president has created,'' Kirkland told the lawmakers.
   Skinner told the subcommittee that administration remains poised
to introduce legislation that would prohibit secondary boycotts of
railroads and other airlines that labor has threatened to support
the Eastern strikers.
   ``A strike at Eastern alone does not substantially disrupt this
nation's transportation system,'' Skinner said. ``It is only the
specter of secondary activity that threatens to hold hostage this
nation's economy and our global competitive position.''
   In his session with reporters, Bush reiterated that secondary
boycotts ``are not in the public interest and I will send
legislation to Congress to forbid them, if that is necessary.''
   Skinner drew occasionally testy questions from the panel's
Democrats, who kept demanding to know why the administration has so
far adopted a passive role in the dispute.
   ``There hasn't been any rolling up of sleeves and getting in
there,'' said Rep. Douglas Bosco, D-Calif.
   ``I'm not afraid to go anywhere, anyplace, and put anybody in a
room'' to find a settlement to the strike, Skinner responded.
   Even some Republicans were critical of Eastern's owner, Frank
Lorenzo, and said they had not decided whether they would support
the Democrats' call for an emergency board.
   But other GOP lawmakers supported Bush's stance. Rep. John Paul
Hammerschmidt of Arkansas, ranking Republican on the House Public
Works Committee, said, ``To convene an emergency board and return to
the wages and working conditions of last week will only further
bleed Eastern and endanger its survival.''
   Democrats said they expected the administration to have little
chance of getting its bill through the Democratic-controlled
Congress.
   All 19 Democrats on the subcommittee who voted supported the
legislation. All but two of the panel's Republicans opposed the
measure: Reps. Sherwood Boehlert and Guy Molinari, both from New
York.
   On a related issue, Boehlert introduced a bill Tuesday that would
require air carriers to submit plans to protect their ticketholders
in case of bankruptcy.
   Boehlert said ``tens of thousands'' of travelers have already
purchased tickets for Eastern flights, some of which might not be
redeemed if the airline reorganizes under the bankruptcy laws.
</TEXT>
