<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LoneStar-Financing     03-07 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lone Star-Financing,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lone Star Seeks to Restructure Steel Unit's Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Texas Steel Facilities, a subsidiary of Lone
Star Technologies, is negotiating with lenders to stretch out
payments on $135 million in bank debt, the parent company said.
   The steel unit, formerly known as Lone Star Steel Co., faces a
$44 million payment on the debt March 31. The holding company is not
responsible for East Texas' debt.
   East Texas Steel Facilities met Friday with a group of its bank
lenders, led by NCNB Texas National Bank, to discuss restructuring
the debt, officials said Monday.
   In addition, Lone Star said auditor Arthur Andersen &amp; Co. may
include an ``explanatory paragraph'' in its report on the company's
financial results for the year. The paragraph, described as slightly
less severe than a qualified report, would reflect uncertainties
about Lone Star's ability to complete the proposed debt
restructuring, the company told the Dallas Times Herald.
   Buoyed by overly optimistic projections of demand for its
oilfield products, East Texas Steel borrowed heavily last year to
purchase high-quality slab steel used to manufacture pipe. Bank debt
in the year soared to $144.1 million from $108.3 million.
   But the steep downturn in world oil prices dried up the market
for oilfield products, and Lone Star in 1988 posted a $24.8 million
loss. Despite two profitable quarters early in the year, East Texas
steel operations contributed more than half of the loss.
   As a result of the latest downturn, the company in August laid
off 300 workers at its steel mill in Lone Star, which in its heyday
employed more than 6,000. In January, the company eliminated 150
additional jobs as part of its reorganization of its steel
operations.
   Lone Star said it has tried without success to find other sources
of financing. To raise cash, the company said, it sought possible
joint-venture partners or buyers for selected assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
