<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0326,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Up Moderately</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
after opening lower in Tokyo on Wednesday, and share prices also
rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar, which opened at 128.68 yen, down 0.35 yen from
Tuesday's close, inched up to 128.78 yen by late morning. The
currency moved in a range between 128.65 yen and 128.90 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
61.08 points Tuesday, added another 135.30 points, or 0.42 percent,
to finish the morning session at 32,073.24.
   Dealers said the index rose after investors regained confidence
in the market after a favorable showing in Tuesday's session.
   Stability in the foreign exchange market also contributed to the
Nikkei's rise Wednesday, said Yukio Nakajima of Nomura Securities in
Tokyo.
   He added, however,``There are still some uncertainties over how
the stock scandal will affect the government.''
   The Nikkei index declined upon the start of trading Tuesday
following the arrest of a leading executive on charges of bribery in
a major stock-profiteering scandal with links to leading politicians.
   On Wednesday, Takashi Kato, former vice labor minister, was
arrested on bribery charges in the same stock scandal but morning
trading closed before reports of the arrest surfaced.
   In currency dealings, the dollar slumped from the previous day
mainly due to selling for profit-taking, traders said.
   Market participants were reluctant to make major moves before
Friday's release of U.S. employment figures for February, said one
trader.
</TEXT>
